<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Angered at U.S. Trade Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The European Union filed a complaint against the  
United States before the World Trade Organization on Thursday, 
saying U.S. moves to impose sanctions in a dispute over bananas 
violate global trading rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, European targets of the sanctions, from prosciutto  
producers to cashmere companies, accused the United States of 
trying to destroy their industries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration notified U.S. importers that they are  
liable for hefty tariffs on $520 million worth of European goods in 
retaliation for European barriers on banana imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States says American banana companies lose $520  
million annually in sales to Europe because of illegal trade 
barriers that favor bananas imported from former European colonies 
in the Caribbean and Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	If allowed to stand, the U.S. tariffs would double the cost of  
the targeted goods, pricing them out of the American market. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe has asked the WTO to invoke a special process under which  
the United States and the 15-nation EU trading bloc would have 20 
days to settle their differences. If they failed, the EU could then 
ask the WTO to rule on the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Lader, the U.S. ambassador to Britain, was summoned for a  
meeting Thursday in London with Stephen Byers, Britain's Trade and 
Industry Secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue the dialogue to try and find a working  
solution in the context of the extraordinary friendship between our 
two countries,'' Lader said later. 
</P>
<P>
	British newspapers reported Friday that Lader's summons by the  
government was the first such formal protest for a U.S. ambassador 
to Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	British Trade Minister Brian Wilson called the U.S. action  
``potentially catastrophic'' for the British cashmere industry, 
which is concentrated in Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people there are saddened and utterly bewildered that the  
United States should attack them in this way over a dispute which 
has absolutely nothing to do with them or their industry,'' said 
Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of Italy's consortium of Parma ham producers, Stefano  
Fanti, accused the United States of unfairly targeting Italy to 
pressure the EU to modify its banana import system. Some 98 percent 
of prosciutto in the United States comes from Italy, and 94 percent 
is Parma ham. 
</P>
<P>
	Products from 13 of the EU's 15 nations risk being hit by the  
tariffs. These include Italian and Greek pecorino cheese, French 
handbags, German coffee makers and British biscuits. The 
Netherlands and Denmark have been spared because they sided with 
the United States in the trade dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
