<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Jordanian Prime Minister Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- King Abdullah has designated a seasoned  
politician and confidant of his late father to be Jordan's next 
prime minister and form a new government, state-run media said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdul-Raouf Rawabdeh, a longtime proponent of King Hussein's  
liberal outlook and a supporter of Jordan's 1994 peace treaty with 
Israel, will get the top spot, the Petra news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Cabinet was to be announced later today, once Prime  
Minister Fayez Tarawneh formally submits his resignation to the new 
king, according to Petra, the mouthpiece of the government. 
</P>
<P>
	An official in Tarawneh's office, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said the Cabinet has held its last meeting, during which 
Tarawneh and his ministers signed a resignation letter to be 
submitted to Abdullah. 
</P>
<P>
	The government change is Abdullah's first major executive  
decision. It was expected and seen as part of a widespread shuffle 
in senior public posts, including positions within the royal 
palace, police and intelligence. Tradition dictates that a serving 
Cabinet resigns when a new king comes to power. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah, 37, King Hussein's eldest son, ascended to the throne  
hours after his father died of cancer Feb. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawabdeh, a 60-year-old member of Parliament, consulted late  
into Wednesday night with potential Cabinet ministers, palace 
sources told The Associated Press on customary condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear when the king designated Rawabdeh, who has held  
several Cabinet portfolios in the past three decades, to be the 
next prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawabdeh, who was close to Hussein, also is known to be close to  
Prince Hassan, who was replaced as heir to the throne less than two 
weeks before Hussein died. 
</P>
<P>
	Days after taking office, Abdullah rejected the resignation of  
the present 23-member Cabinet headed by Tarawneh, who took office 
last August. Government officials said then that Abdullah was first 
consulting with aides and statesmen on the country's future 
political agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The palace sources said Abdullah has asked Rawabdeh to bring in  
a Cabinet of technocrats and liberal politicians to jump start 
economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, a country barren of natural resources, is saddled by  
$6.1 billion in foreign debt. Unemployment is at 15 percent, 
inflation is 6 percent and about a third of the country's 3.8 
million people live in poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawabdeh was elected in the country's first nationwide vote in  
1989 to the 80-seat lower house of Parliament, and has served there 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	For 18 months beginning in February 1997, Rawabdeh served as a  
deputy prime minister. Rawabdeh is from a prominent Jordanian 
family from the northern town of Sareeh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
