<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Saving Private Ryan' Wins Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan''  
won the top movie award from the Producers Guild of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Since inception of the awards in 1989, the top movie winner has  
gone on to win an Academy Award for best picture every year with 
the exception of 1995 and 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saving Private Ryan'' is nominated for 11 Oscars.  
</P>
<P>
	The PGA awards were announced Wednesday night. In television,  
David E. Kelley won for producing the series ``The Practice,'' 
which also won three Golden Globes and three Emmys. Kelley was also 
nominated in the same category for ``Ally McBeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In non-series TV, Tom Hanks won the PGA prize for HBO's ``From  
the Earth to the Moon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hanks was also awarded the Nova Award for most promising  
television producer for his ``Moon'' project. The Nova Award for 
movie producing was given to Peter and Bobby Farrelly for ``There's 
Something About Mary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spielberg also took home the Milestone Award honoring historic  
contributions to the motion picture industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:45:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oscars Don't Necessarily Help Studios </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An Oscar can jump-start a career, boost box  
office or get its director, producer or stars a better table at the 
hottest restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	But it can't protect a movie studio from going belly up.  
</P>
<P>
	Three studios and one production-acquisition house with films  
receiving Academy Award nominations this year are either dead or 
face uncertain futures, the result of corporate upheaval in the 
movie business. 
</P>
<P>
	PolyGram Films and its specialty label Gramercy Pictures have an  
armload of Oscar nominations: Gramercy's ``Elizabeth'' with seven 
nominations including best picture and PolyGram's ``What Dreams May 
Come'' with two nominations for its stunning visuals. 
</P>
<P>
	But after Seagram Co. purchased the PolyGram parent PolyGram NV,  
the domestic distribution offices of PolyGram Films are being shut 
and foreign operations melded into Seagram-owned Universal Studios. 
Gramercy is likely to be sold or folded into another studio, 
perhaps Universal's specialty label, October Films. 
</P>
<P>
	That is if October Films stays in the Seagram family. October,  
whose ``Hilary and Jackie'' picked up nominations for actresses 
Emily Watson and Rachel Griffiths, is another candidate to be sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, most of the operations of long-struggling Largo  
Entertainment, which produced ``Affliction,'' were closed by its 
corporate parent, JVC Entertainment of Japan, just days before two 
of its actors, Nick Nolte and James Coburn, received Academy Award 
nominations for best actor and supporting actor. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, the back-room turmoil won't be evident on the  
screen. The films will remain in release, with vigorous advertising 
and Oscar campaigns. The executives who got the boot will probably 
get new jobs and, this being Hollywood, higher pay. 
</P>
<P>
	But it does give some insight into how things work in the movie  
industry -- to a degree how they've always worked -- in this 
community that novelist Budd Schulberg likened nearly 60 years ago 
in ``What Makes Sammy Run?'' to a gold rush boom town whose chief 
products are movies, ambition and fear. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is bittersweet,'' said Barr Potter, Largo's chairman and  
chief executive, who will remain at the company to help with the 
shutdown. ``It's just an example of the extremes that one goes 
through in this business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was, perhaps, worse in the early 1990s, before the start of a  
Hollywood economic surge. Consider that the 1991 best-picture 
winner was ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' whose producers picked up 
the Oscars while the film's studio, Orion, was in the throes of 
bankruptcy. The movie also won Oscars for director Jonathan Demme, 
co-stars Anthony Hopkins and Jodie Foster and screenwriter Ted 
Tally. But with the Hollywood economy showing signs of cooling, and 
movie production costs continuing to soar, fear and uncertainty are 
as strong as they have been in years. Many studios, worried about 
staking too much on a single picture, are entering into financial 
partnerships with competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``These kinds of deals are done with more and more frequency,''  
said Miramax West Coast President Mark Gill, whose studio's 
best-picture nominee ``Shakespeare in Love'' is being financed and 
released in a partnership with Universal Studios. ``The rivalries 
are put aside, frankly, to moderate risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Between the co-production deals and the shifting corporate  
ownership of studios and their art house divisions, lines are now 
blurred all over the Hollywood map. It isn't always clear who 
should get credit -- or who will be around this time tomorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider the tale of this season's second costume drama, about  
the behind-the-scenes intrigue during the reign of England's Queen 
Elizabeth, has plenty of its own real-life drama behind it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elizabeth'' began life as a Working Title production for the  
Dutch-owned film and music company PolyGram NV, the same 
producer-studio partnership behind the Oscar-nominated ``Four 
Weddings and a Funeral.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Produced for about $22 million, ``Elizabeth'' was distributed  
through PolyGram's Gramercy Pictures, which handles lower-budget, 
artier films. After becoming a hit last September in the United 
Kingdom, the film came to the United States, where it built an 
audience and endeared itself to the Academy, which nominated it for 
the seven Oscars. 
</P>
<P>
	But a cloud has hung over Gramercy ever since Seagram, the  
Canadian liquor and entertainment giant, purchased PolyGram last 
year for $10.2 billion. Seagram already had a Hollywood studio in 
Universal and a specialty division in October Films, and suddenly 
PolyGram and Gramercy were looking expendable. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram sold off pieces of PolyGram -- MGM got most of the film  
library, a company called Carlton Communications Inc. got the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, a Saudi prince, Muhammad Bin Bandur Abdul Aziz, was  
reportedly willing to pay $400 million to $600 million for the rest 
of PolyGram, but the deal never happened. 
</P>
<P>
	So Seagram merged PolyGram's international businesses with  
Universal and started laying off employees in the domestic PolyGram 
office, leaving Gramercy in limbo. Gramercy still could be sold, or 
it could be merged into October Films. 
</P>
<P>
	But studio officials remained committed to ``Elizabeth,''  
despite the uncertainty. There was a vigorous Oscar campaign and a 
healthy marketing push, including television ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The film also has received a strong distribution commitment; it  
has been put in expanded release since the Oscar nominations, 
earning a modest box-office boost from the Academy. 
</P>
<P>
	Also caught in the Seagram-PolyGram whirlwind is ``Hilary and  
Jackie,'' which was released by October Films, whose own future is 
hardly clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade papers have reported that media mogul Barry Diller, who  
had purchased Universal's television operations from Seagram, may 
have his eye on October, though a sale to Diller has reportedly 
been rejected by October's partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Just who will ultimately own and control October remains a  
question, though the film is shielded from the turmoil. It, too, 
has an Oscar campaign and distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the major players would comment beyond a recent  
Universal statement that ``the process of integrating PolyGram 
Filmed Entertainment into Universal's film operations has now 
begun'' and that Gramercy's fate, like that of PolyGram's video and 
TV operations, is ``still currently under evaluation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More coldly certain is the fate of PolyGram Films' U.S.  
distribution offices, which didn't survive Oscar season, even as 
its Robin Williams film, ``What Dreams May Come'' competes for 
awards for art direction and visual effects. 
</P>
<P>
	People started clearing out their desks last month in the  
Beverly Hills offices. 
</P>
<P>
	But the corporate parents are still behind the film, which is  
getting a strong Oscar campaign in ads in the trade papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Largo's shutdown was long expected. Formed 10 years ago, it had  
produced or acquired ``G.I. Jane,'' ``John Carpenter's Vampires'' 
and ``Affliction.'' But it has struggled in recent years; JVC 
stopped its production financing last year, leaving Largo 
essentially a sales agent. Then last month, JVC discontinued even 
those activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Affliction,'' however, got a big Oscar push and remains in  
theaters (the movie is being distributed by Lions Gate). In the 
meantime, executives are mopping up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no specific plans at the moment,'' said Potter. ``I'm  
focusing on tying up all the loose ends. And once that's behind me, 
I'll be making every effort to find my next situation and explore 
any interesting opportunities.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
