<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Rise Again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rose for a third consecutive day Thursday,  
reaching their highest in nearly two months, on sudden declines in 
U.S. inventories. Heating oil and unleaded gasoline also rose 
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, sugar futures tumbled, while grains futures  
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude continued its trek higher, with prices having gained more  
than 10 percent this week, as investors interpreted inventory data 
as a sign that prices had finally bottomed out and could begin to 
move sharply higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute reported earlier this week that  
inventories plunged a sharp 5.903 million barrels last week to 
326,751 million barrels, confounding expectations for an increase 
and erasing what had been a year-over-year surplus in supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Inventories now are 1.01 million barrels below levels at the  
same time last year despite what continued oversupply by some of 
the world's top producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Unleaded gasoline and heating oil futures also were boosted by  
Tosco Corp.'s decision to shut its Avon refinery in California, 
which touched off a scramble for crude products in the West. Cash 
prices in the Northeast market rocketed higher as those holding 
supplies were content to wait for higher prices that may come as 
demand shifts westward. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures investors also are concerned gasoline destined for the  
important Northeast market might be diverted west as the peak 
demand season nears. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for April delivery rose 42 cents to $13.35 a barrel at the  
New York Mercantile Exchange; April heating oil rose 1.25 cents to 
34.80 cents a gallon; April unleaded gasoline rose 1.35 cents to 
41.26 cents a gallon; April natural gas rose 3.9 cents to 1.762 for 
each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures tumbled nearly 6 percent in heavy selling on the  
Board of Trade of the City of New York, posting new 11 1/2-year lows 
in a continued rout tied to oversupply and weak demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures have been on the defensive for months, pressured  
by bumper world supplies and fears Brazil, the world's largest 
grower, would export large amounts of its crop to help ease 
economic problems and bring in hard currency. 
</P>
<P>
	May sugar fell .35 cent to 5.50 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures jumped on the Chicago Board of Trade after the U.S.  
Agriculture Department reported exports in the past week of 1.14 
million metric tons, well above the highest analyst estimate of 
900,000 metric tons. The report put shipments to date 19 percent 
above the previous marketing year's pace and ahead of the USDA's 
estimate of a 15 percent increase for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat export sales came in at 702,900 metric tons, also well  
above expectations of 400,000 metric tons being shipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also were supported by an increasing number of analyst  
reports that estimate spring plantings will fall sharply over the 
previous year, as farmers plant more lucrative soybean crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures followed wheat higher early, but retreated at  
the end of the session as nervous traders eyed bumper crops from 
South America. 
</P>
<P>
	May wheat rose 2 cents to $2.62 1/2 a bushel; May corn rose 2 1/4  
cents to $2.17 per bushel; May soybeans rose 1/4 cent to $4.68 per 
bushel. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
