<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets closed lower Thursday on  
negative local news, but the region's largest exchange, Tokyo, 
bucked the trend and showed a slight gain on lower interest rates 
and a stronger U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 13.09  
points, or 0.09 percent, to close at 14,183.45. On Wednesday, the 
average had climbed 249.30 points, or 1.79 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower interest rates and a stronger dollar boosted investor  
confidence, with export-related shares soaring on hopes that gains 
by the dollar would help them earn more on overseas sales. Japanese 
products are more competitive abroad when the yen falls. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the yen for a second straight day,  
following a decision from Japan's central bank on Wednesday to 
lower short-term interest rates to a record low of 0.02 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.58 yen in late afternoon trading, up 1.40  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York 
level of 121.77 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares fell slightly as investors found little  
motivation in the government's budget plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 9.64 points, or 0.10 percent,  
to close at 9,912.76. The index rose 8.92 points or 0.09 percent on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Confirmation that the Hong Kong government was negotiating with  
Walt Disney Co. about building a theme park here may be good for 
the economy in the long term, but there was little in the budget to 
spur investor confidence right now, said Jerry Pang of HSBC 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares fell as foreign investors sold amid renewed  
pessimism over Thailand's bankruptcy law. The SET index lost 4.37 
points, or 1.3 percent, to end at 337.14. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell on continued selling of consumer-related  
and market heavyweight Telkom shares. The JSX Composite Index fell 
1.653 points, or 0.4 percent, to close at 394.154. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell as investors locked in profits after a  
two-day surge. The PSE index fell 11.24 points, or 0.6 percent, to 
close at 1,997.68. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose on buying of blue chips. The Composite  
Index rose 3.36 points, or 0.7 percent, to close at 516.59. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares fell as investors cashed in on the market's recent  
four-day rally. The KOSPI fell 2.20 points, or 0.41 percent, to 
close at 532.29. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares fell on a weak bond market and an overnight drop  
in Wall Street. The All Ordinaries Index fell 4.6 points, or 0.2 
percent, to close at 2,885.3. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on buying of property-related stocks. The  
STI rose 17.60 points, or 1.2 percent, to close at 1,433.41. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell as speculators cashed in earlier gains. The  
Weighted Price Index fell 9.40 points, or 0.14 percent, to close at 
6,393.74. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on buying of market heavyweight Telecom  
Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. The NZSE-40 capital index rose 6.02 
points, or 0.27 percent, to close at 2,163.79. 

</P>
</TEXT>
