<DOCNO> APW19990304.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:55:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fierce Winds Kill 3 in Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Residents of the Northwest and South picked up the pieces today  
after storms lashed both regions with damaging wind, rain and snow, 
knocking out power to hundreds of thousands of people. Three people 
were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Driving winds and likely tornadoes blew across several Southern  
states Wednesday, destroying homes and downing power lines. Nearly 
a foot of snow fell in parts of the Appalachians. 
</P>
<P>
	A 23-year-old Alabama man died when winds estimated at 60 mph to  
80 mph uprooted a tree and slammed it into his trailer home in 
Millbrook. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden you just heard a big boom,'' said a neighbor,  
Stephanie Cleckler. ``Glass started flying everywhere ... that's 
when everybody started screaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 45-year-old North Carolina woman was killed when winds threw a  
tree onto her car near Hendersonville. 
</P>
<P>
	The fierce winds slammed into a steel mill construction site  
south of Richmond, Va., mangling a half-dozen trailers and injuring 
16 workers, authorities said. Ten remained hospitalized with neck 
and back injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't expecting this, needless to say, at least not to  
this extent,'' State Police Lt. G.W. Taylor said. ``There was a 
combination of wrecks, vehicles that wouldn't go, snow, ice and 
strong winds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 20 inches of snow were predicted to fall in far western  
Maryland, where near whiteout conditions forced the temporary 
closure today of about 30 miles of Interstate 68. Allegheny Energy 
in Hagerstown said about 2,000 customers in its five-state region 
were without power this morning, down from about 24,000 overnight. 
Schools in five area counties were closed. 
</P>
<P>
	At its peak, the storm knocked out power for more than 100,000  
in North Carolina after leaving 8 inches of snow in the mountains. 
Most were back in service by this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Northwest, Washington Gov. Gary Locke declared a state of  
emergency in five western counties after a punishing storm with 
wind gusts of 68 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Waves measured 35 feet in steady 60 mph winds. A 36-year-old man  
was killed when a tree fell on the car about 30 miles north of 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Power was knocked out to more than 200,000 people, though most  
had it restored by early today. 
</P>
<P>
	One of two routes used by thousands of Seattle commuters to  
traverse Lake Washington was still closed today after its 
drawbridge malfunctioned. It wasn't expected to be fixed until 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	High winds also canceled passenger ferry service in the Puget  
Sound area Wednesday morning, affecting about 45,000 people. Better 
weather was expected for the region today. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Washington coast, heavy seas combined with high tides to  
temporarily flood downtown Raymond with up to 2 feet of water. Two 
apartment complexes were evacuated, and nearly 40 people sought 
shelter at a Red Cross facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south, heavy seas pushed the wreckage of a beached cargo  
ship back to shore in Oregon. The oil-laden bow section of the New 
Carissa broke free of a tug Tuesday night and drifted 50 miles to a 
beach near Waldport. 
</P>
<P>
	A string of storms late Tuesday also damaged homes in Texas and  
Florida. Several people were hurt in Texas' Jasper County, where 
twisters nearly demolished six homes and damaged as many as 25 
others. A tornado in the Florida Panhandle damaged about 55 homes, 
with 20 sustaining major damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
