<DOCNO> APW19990304.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:55:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Fund Assets Rise to $861 Bil / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market  
mutual funds increased by $5.91 billion to $861.81 billion in the 
latest week, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category rose  
by $4.64 billion to $708.75 billionfor the week ended Wednesday, 
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund 
assets increased by $1.27 billion to $153.06 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of institutional money market funds decreased by $7.03  
billion to $588.33 billion for the same period. Among institutional 
funds, taxable money market fund assets decreased by $7.17 billion 
to $539.30 billion; assets of tax-exempt funds increased by $139.4 
million to $49.03 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.450 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.451 trillion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose to  
4.37 percent in the week ended Tuesday from 4.34 percent in the 
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal 
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day 
average yield fell to 4.36 percent from 4.37 percent, IBC Financial 
Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield rose to 4.47 percent from 4.44  
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield fell to 
4.46 percent from 4.47 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
61 days, down from 58 days in the previous week, IBC Financial Data 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts was 2.16 percent as of 
Wednesday, down from 2.18 percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the annual  
percentage yield available on interest-bearing checking accounts 
held steady at 0.97 percent from a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank Rate Monitor said the annual percentage yield rose to 4.14  
percent from 4.13 percent on six-month certificates of deposit. 
Yields on 1-year CDs rose to 4.33 percent from 4.31 percent as they 
also rose on 2 1/2-year CDs to 4.39 percent from 4.37 percent. Yields 
on 5-year CDs rose to 4.52 percent from 4.51 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
