<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Afghanistan May Hold Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Afghanistan's feuding factions will  
hold face-to-face talks to try to find a peaceful end to their 
protracted and bloody conflict, a U.N. envoy said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the Taliban army, which controls roughly 90  
percent of Afghanistan, will meet with their northern-based 
opponents on March 10 in the Turkmenistan capital of Ashkabad, U.N. 
special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really appeal to the two parties not to disappoint once  
again the people of Afghanistan,'' Brahimi told a news conference 
in Islamabad, the capital of Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Brahimi warned that failure at the negotiation table will surely  
mean another season of bloodletting on the battlefield in 
Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Afghanistan is in the midst of a bitterly cold winter, which has  
caused a lull in fighting. Mountain passes are clogged with snow 
and troops generally stay hunkered down in their mountain bases 
until the weather improves. 
</P>
<P>
	But spring is approaching and Brahimi said that ``both sides are  
feverishly preparing for war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't say this is their last chance ... but this really is  
the chance I hope they will not waste,'' Brahimi said of the peace 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Brahimi's agenda during meetings with the Taliban  
leadership was the return to Afghanistan of the United Nations 
international staff, evacuated last August. 
</P>
<P>
	The world body withdrew its foreign staff after an Italian  
worker was shot and killed on Aug. 21, the day after the United 
States fired Tomahawk cruise missiles at eastern Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taliban blamed the killing on renegade soldiers seeking  
retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States was targeting alleged terrorist camps run by  
Osama bin Laden, who Washington believes masterminded the Aug. 7 
attacks on its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. 
</P>
<P>
	Brahimi said he has received a Taliban promise to protect United  
Nations staff. U.N. security personnel are assessing the safety 
situation before a decision about returning to the war-ruined 
country is made, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. special envoy leaves Friday for Iran.  
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan is a strong ally of the Taliban and one of only three  
countries to recognize the hardcore Islamic movement. Iran is 
believed to be supporting the opposition and in particular 
Afghanistan's minority Shiite Muslims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
