<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blackmun Abortion Ruling Reaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry Blackmun's 1973 Supreme Court opinion in  
Roe vs. Wade galvanized both sides of the national debate over 
abortion and spurred decades of activism in courts and on the 
streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun, who died Thursday, ``stood as the founder of modern  
day abortion-rights jurisprudence in the United States,'' said 
Simon Heller of the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy. ``We 
categorize him among the heroes of the pro-choice movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those who oppose the right to abortion saw Blackmun as far from  
a hero. He got more than 60,000 pieces of hate mail over the 
decision that legalized abortion nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun's opinion ``was without a doubt the catalyst that  
galvanized what we call the pro-life movement in the United 
States,'' said Jay Alan Sekulow of the American Center for Law and 
Justice, who has defended anti-abortion protesters in court on 
free-speech grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The national outcry clearly wasn't there until the Roe  
decision,'' Sekulow added. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the court issued the ruling in 1973, each state could  
decide for itself whether to allow abortion. Most did not. 
</P>
<P>
	The years since have seen numerous court cases over efforts to  
limit abortion, massive street marches by advocates on each side, 
clinic blockades by anti-abortion protesters, and violence -- 
including the killings of several doctors who performed abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion has been a big issue in many political races and in  
confirmation hearings for new Supreme Court justices. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, the highest court reaffirmed the basic right to  
abortion, although it also upheld many limits imposed by states. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pot keeps boiling 26 years later,'' said Clarke Forsythe,  
president of Americans United for Life, who criticized the idea 
that ``one national sweep of the pen could solve the abortion 
debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, formerly a pioneering women's  
rights advocate, suggested during her pre-Supreme Court days that 
the country might have been better off if the right to abortion had 
been established more gradually. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't agree,'' said Kate Michelman of the National Abortion  
Rights Action League. ``There's no question that we were moving to 
repeal the abortion laws ... but it was slow and it was state by 
state, year by year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marcia Greenberger of the National Women's Law Center said that  
if the Supreme Court had not ruled, more states may have allowed 
abortion in some form. But she added, ``Even today, there's no 
reason to think that every state would have legalized abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David O'Steen, executive director of the National Right to Life  
Committee, called abortion an issue that ``strikes so fundamentally 
at our sense of what is right and wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A social controversy such as this has not been seen in our  
nation since the debate over slavery of African-Americans,'' he 
said, and predicted the debate will continue into the next century 
over ``what abortion is and what it does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He wrote the worst Supreme Court decision in history,'' said  
Phyllis Schlafly, president of Eagle Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenberger added: ``There is no Supreme Court precedent that we  
can rely upon if there is a determined effort to appoint justices 
who are committed to overturning it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sekulow said Blackmun kept his legacy going as author of Roe vs.  
Wade by his separate opinions in later abortion cases. ``He knew 
what he was known for,'' Sekulow said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria Feldt, president of the Planned Parenthood Federation of  
America, said, ``Many women in the future will not ever have heard 
of Harry Blackmun, but they will have choices that women (before 
Roe) did not have.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
