<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Fund Missing Kids Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress would formally recognize the Center  
for Missing and Exploited Children and make annual appropriations 
to it under a bill approved Thursday by the Senate Judiciary 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure sets aside $10 million in federal money for the  
center annually from 2000 to 2004. This year, the center received 
$8.12 million and its Jimmy Ryce Training Center received another 
$1.25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would free the center from applying annually for  
authorization and money, committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, 
said. The government has awarded grants to the center for the past 
14 years to operate a national resource center in Arlington, Va., 
and a national 24-hour hot line. 
</P>
<P>
	``The center provides invaluable assistance and training to law  
enforcement around the country in cases of missing and exploited 
children,'' Hatch said. ``The center's record is quite impressive 
and its efforts have led directly to a significant increase in the 
percentage of missing children who are recovered safely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The center works with the FBI, the Justice, State and Treasury  
departments and other federal agencies to find missing children and 
prevent child victimization. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also would renew a law that targets federal money to  
areas with large number of runaway youths. One program created by 
the law provides grants for temporary shelter and counseling for 
youths under 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Other grants provide longer-term housing to homeless young  
people from 16 to 21 and helps them become self-sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure's projects ``benefit those children truly in need  
and at high risk of becoming addicted to drugs, sexually exploited 
or abused or involved in criminal behavior,'' Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed a similar bill last June, but it died in the  
House after lawmakers tried to attach controversial provisions 
dealing with juvenile crime. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 249.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
