<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Fans Are Into March Badness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While college basketball fans are immersed in March Madness, NBA  
fans are into March Badness after a month of February Futility. 
</P>
<P>
	When St. John's beat Notre Dame last week after looking inept in  
the first 20 minutes, coach Mike Jarvis said, ``It looked like the 
Knicks-Nets in the first half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis, of course, was referring to New York Knicks and the New  
Jersey Nets, who a few days earlier seemed to put the ball 
everywhere but in the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA likes to say it has the world's greatest athletes. What  
it could use are some basketball players. 
</P>
<P>
	What fans have been getting are preseason games at  
regular-season prices, although there have been some special ticket 
deals, as players huff and puff up and down the floor and throw up 
clinkers from all angles and distances. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a struggle for a team to hit 80 points in a game. The Utah  
Jazz contrived to score only 56 points, the second-lowest in an NBA 
game for a team since the 24-second shot clock went into effect in 
the 1954-55 season, eight years after the NBA was founded. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan could score that many points on a good night.  
Come back, Michael! 
</P>
<P>
	Ineptitude has become such a norm that it has become the story.  
Did the Bulls lose? That's no longer the question. Now it's `Did 
the Clippers win?' As of Tuesday, with no game scheduled Wednesday, 
the Los Angeles Clippers were 0-13 and in cold pursuit of the NBA's 
worst-start record of 0-17 set by the Miami Heat in the 1988-89 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	There are those who note that tough defense is a reason for the  
scoring drought. Maybe, but more legitimate reasons might be the 
playground mentality of many pros and the idea that showmanship is 
what counts. So if you can't slam dunk, then throw one up from 
downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps a bigger reason, because of the owner's lockout, is  
teams are being asked to play four or five games a week instead of 
two or three so that a 50-game season can be held before the 
interminable playoffs begin. Four games in seven days seem to be 
just too many for the world's greatest athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Is it possible that some of these multi-millionaires did not  
work at getting into and staying in the best physical condition 
during the lockout? 
</P>
<P>
	The shorter training camp and more intense schedule have to have  
had something to do with the rash of injuries that have hit the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance, however, has been good, and not only because of the  
league's public relations efforts. The faithful seem to be willing 
to put up with subpar play, at least for the current season. 
</P>
<P>
	But it would seem that the NBA could be headed for trouble in  
the post-Jordan era unless basketball becomes as important as show 
boating. If a player can't be a superstar, he should just settle 
for being a player and part of the game. The faithful would 
appreciate that. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the collegians take over the world's biggest stage --  
the country's television sets -- and you can be sure they'll make 
the most of the opportunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mice Smell Study Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Scientists believe they have figured out how the  
nose knows. 
</P>
<P>
	The mystery that has long perplexed experts is how creatures can  
distinguish among many thousands of odors with their 1,000 or so 
smell sensors. 
</P>
<P>
	A new study of mice found that instead of dedicating a single  
sensor to a single odor, mammals use their sensors in combination. 
The same sensors are triggered again and again in different 
combinations, and each combination spells out a unique odor. 
</P>
<P>
	The sensors, or olfactory receptors, line the wall of the nasal  
cavity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each receptor is used over and over again to define an odor,  
just like letters are used over and over again to define different 
words,'' said Dr. Linda B. Buck of the Howard Hughes Medical 
Institute at Harvard Medical School. 
</P>
<P>
	Buck and colleagues from the Life Electronics Research Center in  
Amagasaki, Japan, reported the discovery in Friday's issue of the 
journal Cell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:28:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Jump Into Race for White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As George W. Bush and Al Gore and Bill Bradley  
and Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander and Steve Forbes -- just to name 
a few -- have announced, they will be announcing one of these days 
that they are running for president in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The rites of announcement are well under way, creating  
candidates by degree. 
</P>
<P>
	The players already are running, of course. And in most cases,  
they have been, some for months, some almost full time since the 
last presidential election. But no matter. Announcing is part of 
the game. For the longest long shots, entering day is as good as it 
gets, and they become names down the list. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the money runs out or the voters do, at least 10  
Republicans and two Democrats are candidates, in varying stages of 
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan, the third-time GOP candidate, who always has  
played by his own rules anyhow, has just entered the 2000 campaign 
his own way. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan did not announce he was exploring whether to announce  
he would run and announce it later. He did it the old-fashioned 
way, and just said it outright. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mount up and ride to the sound of the guns,'' he exhorted in  
declaring his White House candidacy in Manchester, N.H., on 
Tuesday. Four years ago, he called his troops peasants with 
pitchforks. But even with new weapons, his prospects are minimal, 
even in the state in which he won the first primary of 1996, edging 
then front-runner Bob Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's rerun was telegraphed when he took a leave of absence  
from his between-campaigns job as a conservative commentator on 
CNN. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire announced earlier that he is  
running, a plunge that has not rippled in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming soon: Elizabeth Dole, who held two Cabinet posts, served  
as president of the American Red Cross and campaigned in her 
husband's losing cause in 1996. Her next step will be an 
exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Unannounced, she ranks high in the surveys of Republican  
opinion, second to Bush, who is announcing his exploratory 
committee on Sunday after saying he would say so. The governor had 
said he would tell Texas reporters first, which he did on Tuesday. 
Sunday, he is to go national. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio  
and Gary Bauer, a conservative who left as president of the Family 
Research Council to seek the GOP nomination, already have 
exploratory committees. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Gore and his Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill  
Bradley, already have presidential campaign committees, one step 
past exploratory organizations. Both are campaigning. Both are 
planning to announce later that they are candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the jargon of these exercises, those will be their formal  
announcements. That means staged for television, with speeches and 
cheering sections. Ironically, the most formal steps are the 
initial ones, the exploratory committees, which enable a potential 
candidate to legally raise and spend campaign money, ostensibly for 
the purpose of exploring whether to keep doing so as a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The money has to be raised within federal limits, no more than  
$1,000 from an individual, $5,000 from a political action 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step is a statement of candidacy, the point at which  
the candidate's finances are subject to Federal Election Commission 
restrictions and reporting. There are spending ceilings set by 
federal formula for each state. There also is an inducement because 
each donation can qualify for up to $250 in matching federal funds. 
</P>
<P>
	That system, tracing back to 1976, is a legal overlay on the  
traditional political ritual of announcing a campaign for 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Those did not come as surprises, either. They were not the real  
starting points; the candidates who would deepen their voices and 
pace their words to declare that ``I am a candidate for president 
of the United States'' already had been out raising money and 
lining up supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	But in those days before federal campaign finance laws, there  
was a point to being coy about candidacy. Once a candidate 
declared, rivals could demand equal TV and radio broadcast time, 
which did not apply to undeclared campaigners. Better to wait, and 
get more air time. 
</P>
<P>
	That is not the test now. It is raising and spending money in  
pursuit of the White House, with or without benefit of declared 
candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Which does not detract from the ritual of announcements, but  
adds more stages to be announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Alexander, the former Tennessee governor who ran four  
years ago and has not stopped since, is to announce his 2000 
campaign Tuesday. ``I'm off and running,'' he said the other day, 
campaigning in Des Moines, Iowa. Next week he will confirm what it 
is he is off and running for. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes is a nonstop campaigner, too, unfettered by the  
spending limits that will apply to rivals who accept matching 
federal funds for their primary election costs. There have been 
hints that Bush might forgo federal money, and thus spending 
limits, too. He would not say when he announced his forthcoming 
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Crafting Mitch Recovery Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is objecting to a  
$1.9 billion Senate measure that would provide aid to Central 
Americans struggling to recover from Hurricane Mitch. And a similar 
House bill is falling victim to political dueling over the federal 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Appropriations Committee planned to vote today on the  
legislation, which also contains funds for struggling U.S. farmers, 
the American steel industry, and aid to Jordan after King Hussein's 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay for the bill, panel Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, has  
included savings from food stamps and welfare accounts that were 
not expected to be spent this year, as well as a 5 percent 
across-the-board reduction in some domestic programs. That prompted 
an outcry today from the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockart accused senators of  
looking for ``a political fight,'' and urged them not to. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an emergency. The need is real. The need is  
desperate,'' Lockhart said. ``These are issues that should be above 
the partisan fighting here in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill  
Young, R-Fla., abruptly postponed a vote set for today by his own 
panel after House leaders ordered him to find savings to pay for 
his entire measure, which has a $1.2 billion price tag. Unlike the 
paid-for Senate bill, Young's would have only paid for the $100 
million for Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a general feeling we ought to find offsets'' to pay  
for the bill, said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, in a 
brief interview. ``It's been a thing we've done'' for emergency 
domestic spending in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton had proposed using part of this year's expected $109  
billion federal surplus to pay for most of the measure. But House 
leaders, eager to show they are more fiscally responsible than 
Clinton, decided against using the surplus in their very first 
spending measure of the year -- especially for a bill dominated by 
foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP fiscal conservatives had also complained that the measure  
should be paid for -- especially since this year's expected surplus 
comes entirely from Social Security trust fund surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we spend money, we won't steal it out of Social Security,  
and that's the first case out of the box,'' said conservative Rep. 
Tom Coburn, R-Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Senate bill contained budget savings to pay for  
itself, that put added pressure on House leaders to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Appropriations panel aides said they had already planned to trim  
defense and foreign aid funds to pay for the $100 million in aid to 
Jordan. But now, they are also hunting for savings to offset $956 
million for Central America and $152 million for American farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The House measure won't be ready until at least next week.  
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the money is to help Honduras, Nicaragua, El  
Salvador and Costa Rica recover from Hurricane Mitch. The October 
storm, considered the worst natural disaster ever in the Western 
Hemisphere, killed more than 9,000 people, left more than 3 million 
homeless and destroyed more than $8.5 billion worth of property. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton journeys to Central America to view recovery efforts on  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agriculture aid is to help U.S. farmers facing a weak export  
market caused largely by Asia's economic problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
