<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound; Dow Up 128.22 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were sharply higher at 2 p.m., although  
below their highest levels of the day, in a broad-based rally that 
included technology, retail, financial and energy shares. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 128.22 at 9,404.10. The Dow got as high as 9,448.66, up 172.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher as well, with the Nasdaq  
composite up 10.01 at 2,275.21, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index 
up 8.36 at 1,236.06. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume was strong at 508.84 million 
shares, above Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led higher by IBM, which was up 6 3/4 at 173 1/2, after  
soaring as much as 10 1/4 to 177. The computer giant agreed to provide 
Dell Computer with parts in a seven-year contract worth $16 
billion. Dell's shares were up 1 3/16 at 82 1/8 in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial-services stocks were higher as bond prices were stable  
after giving ground on Wednesday. The benchmark 30-year Treasury 
bond was unchanged, yielding 5.69 percent. American Express was up 
2 3/8 at 110 3/16. Salomon Smith Barney started coverage of the stock 
with a ``buy'' rating. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil and oil-service stocks were higher with oil prices. Dow  
member Exxon was up 1 3/4 at 67 7/16. Halliburton was up 1 33/64 at 31 
15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail stocks moved higher amid strong February sales figures.  
Wal-Mart, whose February sales rose 10.3 percent at stores open at 
least a year, was up 1 3/8 at 88 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	The market's rise, which extended a recovery in technology  
shares that started late Wednesday, was ``totally justified'' by 
recent economic data and the fact that investors still have a lot 
of money to put to work, said Thomas McManus, portfolio strategist 
at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Once prices get low enough, ``people find out that there's some  
strong underlying demand,'' McManus said. ``After all, there's lots 
of cash in money-market mutual funds, and so there is a lot of 
liquidity, and earnings growth is improving, the manufacturing 
economy is improving, and it doesn't look like (Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan) Greenspan has indicated that he plans to let 
inflation run away any time in the next few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market was quiet following a 10 a.m. Commerce  
Department report that new orders for U.S. factory goods rose 1.7 
percent in January to a $349.6 billion annual rate. 
</P>
<P>
	While that was a record high, it was still a little under  
economists' expectations and therefore didn't raise fears of 
inflation in the bond market, where the 30-year Treasury bond was 
unchanged and yielding 5.69 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
