<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sens. To Overhaul Crop Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Crop insurance would cost less and be more  
widely available to farmers under an overhaul proposed Thursday by 
farm-state senators. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation is an attempt to reinforce the safety net  
created by the 1996 farm bill. The market-oriented ``Freedom to 
Farm'' law replaced decades of federal subsidy programs with a 
seven-year system of direct, declining payments aimed at weaning 
producers off the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the crop insurance changes say farmers need new  
tools for handling market fluctuations as they move away from 
reliance on government subsidies tied to crop production. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this time of low prices and global economic woes, farmers  
and ranchers deserve an effective risk-management tool they can 
depend on,'' said Sen. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., the 1996 farm law's 
architect and a sponsor of the crop insurance plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, a fellow Kansan, said the  
proposal raises many of the ideas he has advocated, including 
providing more affordable and accessible insurance, speeding new 
insurance policies to market, helping farmers hit with multiyear 
losses and allowing federally sponsored livestock coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that this bill establishes a strong basis for  
working together toward meaningful crop insurance reform this 
year,'' Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman plans to hold several hearings across the country on  
the issue. But lawmakers were irate that President Clinton 
submitted his budget with no proposals on how to fund crop 
insurance changes, despite mentioning them in his State of the 
Union address. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would double the government's cost of providing crop  
insurance to about $3 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Roberts and other lawmakers saw crop insurance as a way  
to stabilize farmers hit with disaster. But many farmers still 
don't have crop insurance or don't have enough coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble is, crop insurance doesn't work where disasters have  
struck several years in a row, because policies are based on past 
crop yields. If yields drop, so does the available coverage. And if 
a producer, spurred by flexibility in the 1996 law, plants a 
completely new crop, insurers aren't willing to cover it until a 
few years later, when the crop is established. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would address those problems by creating an average  
production history credit program for start-up farmers or those who 
have added land or rotated crops. It would adjust the history for 
producers who have suffered calamities. 
</P>
<P>
	To encourage producers to buy crop insurance and boost coverage  
levels, the bill's sponsors propose to provide higher subsidy 
payments for those with more coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our bill inverts current subsidy formulas and increases the  
likelihood that farmers will find it a better way to manage risk,'' 
said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., another of the measure's co-sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would waive the current ban on insuring livestock.  
</P>
<P>
	It also would restructure the Federal Crop Insurance Commission  
Board and increase the Risk Management Agency's accountability to 
the board. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the measure would create a private-public  
partnership office within the Agriculture Department and a fee 
system designed to protect companies that develop new insurance 
policies sold by other companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
