<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Tests Fund-Raising Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley looked to  
his first presidential fund-raiser Thursday for a rush of early 
money that he hopes will make his bid for the Democratic nomination 
appear less of a long shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in his adopted home state after a series of campaign trips,  
Bradley hoped to bank $1.5 million from the evening event. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more fund-raisers geared at upper middle-class voters are  
scheduled over the next six weeks as Bradley tries to wrest the 
nomination from Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``The world of $1,000 contributors at the presidential level is  
not a large world as it is now defined,'' Bradley said last week in 
New Hampshire. ``It could be expanded if you're different enough, 
if you're talking about the future in a compelling-enough way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His campaign announced earlier this week that it had qualified  
for public matching funds by raising $5,000 in amounts of $250 or 
less in 21 states. Though the matching funds won't flow until next 
year, Bradley is using his early qualification as a sign of his 
viability. 
</P>
<P>
	His close friend Phil Jackson, a fellow New York Knick in the  
1970s and until recently the coach of the Chicago Bulls, provided 
star power at Thursday's fund-raiser and will attend another next 
week in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	John Moores, owner of the San Diego Padres, also is helping  
Bradley raise money. Bradley aides say other prominent sports 
figures will be involved in the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say presidential candidates in 2000 need to raise $20  
million by the end of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
