<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Claims Against Olympics' Coles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian Olympic Committee delegate  
Phil Coles allegedly accepted thousands of dollars worth of jewelry 
from a businessman connected to Athens' bid to host the 1996 
Olympic Games, a report said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Accepting the diamond and gold cufflinks and a gold necklace in  
1990 breached IOC rules, the Australian Financial Review reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations, which come on top of claims Coles received more  
than $60,000 worth of travel and gifts from Salt Lake City, were 
reportedly made by senior figures who worked on Melbourne's bid to 
host the Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources refused to be named. One told the newspaper that the  
estimated value of the jewelry was about $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, the International Olympic Committee rules barred  
gifts worth more than $200. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic corruption investigators would be happy to view any  
evidence of fresh allegations against Coles, International Olympic 
Committee member Jacques Rogge told Australian Broadcasting Corp. 
radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge, member of an IOC committee probing bribery allegations  
surrounding the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Games, said he had not 
heard details of the new allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to uncover every possible wrongdoing so if there is  
any information we would like to look for irrefutable evidence,'' 
he told ABC radio. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is irrefutable evidence of wrongdoing and breaching  
the rules we would apply sanctions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When told of the new claims, Rogge said he was interested in  
receiving documents to prove them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no doubts about what you're saying to me but before  
commencing I would like to have the facts, if any,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles returned from Switzerland this week after meeting IOC vice  
president Dick Pound, chairman of the investigation into the 
tainted Salt Lake City bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC will recommend to either expel, reprimand or exonerate  
Coles for allegedly accepting gifts and travel from Salt Lake 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Results of the investigation are expected in the next few days.  
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to contact Coles for comment were unsuccessful.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
