<DOCNO> APW19990304.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:36:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Banks Ask $62B in Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Fifteen of Japan's largest banks formally applied  
for $62 billion in government aid Thursday as part of a publicly 
funded cleanup of the nation's loan problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks -- which included some of the world's largest lenders,  
such as the Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd. and Sumitomo Bank Ltd. -- 
also had to submit restructuring plans to the Financial 
Reconstruction Commission, which is overseeing the cleanup, the 
commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will use the plans submitted Thursday to draw up  
the terms for preferred stock and subordinated bonds that the banks 
will sell the government to get the funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks get to pay low rates of interest for the money. Other  
than that, the stocks and bonds sold to the government will be 
treated like normal securities -- including giving the government a 
shareholder's say. 
</P>
<P>
	The final terms of the sale are to be released March 12, and the  
actual purchases will take place March 30, the commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The funds were approved late last year as part of a $210 billion  
bailout of the banking industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese banks are struggling to write off bad loans estimated  
at between $580 billion and $1.2 trillion. The loan problem has 
soaked up funds badly needed to help the economy pull out of its 
worst recession since World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
