<DOCNO> APW19990304.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:04:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online After-Hours Trading To Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long excluded from the world of after-hours  
trading, individual investors may now get the chance to react to 
late-breaking news when it occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning this summer, a leading Internet brokerage will offer  
an evening trading session for its customers through a new 
electronic exchange named IndivEx. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by Discover Brokerage, a unit of Morgan Stanley Dean  
Witter &AMP; Co., may be quite profitable considering how the soaring 
popularity of Internet trading has overwhelmed online trading 
systems at major firms in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts, however, cautioned that individuals may be better off  
if they remain sheltered from the sharp price swings typical of 
after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have the misimpression that by not being able to  
trade after hours, they are missing out on great opportunities,'' 
said Bill Burnham, an industry analyst for CS First Boston. 
``They're not likely to get some great deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The evening session would begin at 6 p.m. or 7 p.m. Eastern time  
and run for two or three hours. Right now, about 40 percent of 
Discover's trades are placed after 6 p.m. Eastern time and then 
executed the next morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a tremendous amount of pent-up demand for after-hours  
trading,'' said IndivEx co-founder Michael Satow, who previously 
worked as a lawyer for the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``Individual investors are well-suited for after-hours trading  
because they work all day,'' he said. It's when they get at home at 
night that they have time to digest the day's financial news, 
discuss it with their family, and make trading decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While many publicly held companies release important news after  
the 4 p.m. closing bell on Wall Street, only professional money 
managers have been able to buy or sell stock before the market 
reopens. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, many of these money managers are acting on behalf of  
individuals through the mutual funds and huge pools of retirement 
money they control. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, investors have long carped about having their personal  
assets frozen until the morning or for an entire weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	But while after-hours trading has been available to  
institutional investors for years, the volume has remained 
relatively light. If there's a major imbalance between buyers and 
sellers, stock prices can move wildly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without a lot of liquidity, the after-hours market (for  
individual investors) could be very volatile,'' said Burnham. 
</P>
<P>
	Eclipse Trading, the creator of IndivEx, hopes to protect  
investors from sudden price swings by requiring them to place 
``limit orders'' that specify an exact price for any stock they 
want to buy or sell. A size limit such as 5,000 shares may also be 
set. 
</P>
<P>
	IndivEx also announced Wednesday that Bernard L. Madoff  
Investment Securities, a top ``market maker,'' has signed onto the 
project. Market makers are a crucial link in any electronic trading 
system, matching buy and sell orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Discover and Madoff may not be the only securities firms that  
see an opportunity in after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Goldman Sachs and ETrade each bought a 25 percent  
stake in Archipelago, the operator of an electronic trading system 
for Nasdaq stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	But ETrade, the No. 2 online broker, and Charles Schwab, the  
biggest, both said they have no plans at this time to offer 
after-hours trading for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	And Instinet, a unit of Reuters that pioneered post-market  
trading and still conducts the bulk of all such trades, declined to 
comment on whether it might develop a retail business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 09:26:03 </DATE_TIME>
