<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Jesuit order's weekly magazine, America, has  
appointed its first lay Catholic and first woman staff member in 90 
years of publication. Patricia A. Kossmann will be literary editor, 
mainly responsible for book reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Kossmann,a specialist in publishing Catholic books, succeeds the  
Rev. Patrick Samway. She was a senior editor at Doubleday and 
manager of its Image Books imprint, and executive editor of Triumph 
Books and Liguori Publications. She is a past president of the 
Catholic Book Publishers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	America's editor, the Rev. Thomas J. Reese, said the Kossmann's  
appointment ``is in keeping with the Jesuit commitment to 
collaborative ministry with the laity, and solidarity with women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Church yearbook shows continuity    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The 1999 Yearbook of American and Canadian  
Churches, produced by the National Council of Churches, generally 
shows continuity in religious trends. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest U.S. denominations remain in the same order as last  
year: the Roman Catholic Church; Southern Baptist Convention; 
United Methodist Church; National Baptist Convention, USA, Inc.; 
and Church of God in Christ. The Catholic Church also is the 
largest group in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Several predominantly white and relatively liberal denominations  
affiliated with the National Council of Churches continue to lose 
members, while conservative groups outside the council continue to 
grow. But the yearbook said the rates of decline and increase have 
flattened in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	The yearbook acquired financial reports from 58 U.S.  
denominations showing annual contributions totaling $24.9 billion. 
Those groups account for 28 percent of the 157.5 million members of 
organized religion in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Evangelical group names president    	
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Bishop Kevin W. Mannoia of the Free  
Methodist Church has been named president of the National 
Association of Evangelicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannoia, 43, of Rancho Cucamonga, Calif., was named by the board  
at the annual meeting of the NAE, a theologically conservative 
association claiming 43,000 local churches, 49 denominations and 
250 independent ministries. The appointment is effective in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Before becoming a bishop in 1996, Mannoia was a district  
superintendent, pastor and college executive. He has a theology 
degree from Trinity Evangelical Divinity School in Illinois and a 
Ph.D. in higher education administration from the University of 
North Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannoia succeeds the Rev. Don Argue, who has been named  
president of Northwest College in Kirkland, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *50 church fires may be traced to one man    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A man charged with seven fires at Indiana  
churches may be responsible for up to 50 fires throughout the 
Midwest and South, according to probable cause affidavits. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Justice Department said Jay Scott Ballinger, 36, of  
Yorktown, was arrested and charged with setting seven Indiana 
church fires dating back to 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Also charged with one count each of arson are Angela Wood, 24,  
of Atlanta, described as an exotic dancer and Ballinger's 
girlfriend; and Donald A. Puckett, 37, of Lebanon, Ind. Wood is in 
federal custody in Macon, Ga., and Puckett is being held in 
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests stemmed from the work of the National Church Arson  
Task Force, established in 1996 after a series of fires at black 
churches in the South. Those arrested are white, and most of the 
Indiana churches burned were in mainly white rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	An affidavit from a Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms  
agent said Ballinger, who was tracked to a hospital where he was 
treated for burns Feb. 7, admitted as many as 50 church fires. 
Jerry Singer, an ATF special agent, said the fires occurred from 
Ohio to Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Orthodox Jews protest changes in Israeli law    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Some 25,000 Orthodox Jews chanted psalms at a  
prayer vigil in protest of Israeli supreme court rulings that could 
reduce Orthodox influence over everyday activities in the Jewish 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks earlier, some 200,000 Orthodox Jews protested in  
Jerusalem over the same grievances. Among them: a recent Israeli 
supreme court edict that could allow seminary students to be 
drafted and another challenging Orthodox control of marriage, 
burial and Sabbath travel. 
</P>
<P>
	Orthodox Jews make up only 10 percent of Israel's population.  
But they control the parliament through political parties. The 
rulings put them at odds with secular Jews, who comprise 70 percent 
of the population. 
</P>
<P>
	Many secular Jews in Israel fear increased Orthodox influence  
and object in particular to an exemption from compulsory military 
service if Orthodox youths are engaged in full-time, 
government-subsidized religious studies. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent court ruling ordered Israel's parliament, the Knesset,  
to either legalize the exemption or draft the ultra-Orthodox. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
