<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ind. Ax Killings Jury Deadlocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A jury deadlocked on murder charges that a  
teen-ager faced in the ax killings of his pastor and the 
clergyman's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion County Prosecutor Scott Newman said he planned to retry  
17-year-old Sean Rich in the Dec. 15, 1996, slayings of the Rev. C. 
Frederick Mathias of Northminster Presbyterian Church and his wife, 
Cleta, because he wanted to gain closure for the Mathias family. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel could not agree Wednesday on murder, arson, battery  
and other charges after 11 hours of deliberations but convicted 
Rich on one count each of burglary and theft and two counts of 
confinement. It acquitted him on a charge of cruelty to an animal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich could receive up to 93 years in prison when he is sentenced  
April 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Mathias family and the congregation shook their  
heads in disbelief as Judge Gary Miller read the verdicts to a 
packed courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't express how disappointed we are that this hell the  
Mathias family has suffered through will continue,'' said Mark 
Moore, the congregation's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Mathias and his wife were found lying face down and bloodied in  
their family room, their hands bound behind their backs. 
Investigators said an ax was stuck in the back of the minister's 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple's pet cat had been kicked to death and was found  
under a Christmas tree. Police suspect that Rich, who was 15 at the 
time of the crimes, started a fire to destroy evidence of the 
crimes. Police discovered a container of lighter fluid at the 
scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich's friend, Paul Brightman, testified during the trial he had  
handed the ax to Rich and watched his young accomplice swing the ax 
and kill the couple. Brightman testified as part of a plea bargain 
in which he accepted a 65-year prison sentence for his role in the 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich's attorney, Glenn Huelskamp, tried to portray Brightman as  
an unreliable witness who was scared by police into placing Rich at 
the crime scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Raises Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- In his first day on the job,  
Brazil's new central banker Arminio Fraga raised interest rates to 
45 percent Thursday in a controversial effort to stamp out 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga called the increase in the Central Bank's lending rate for  
commercial banks necessary to keep prices from exploding. ``Our 
main commitment is to (control) inflation,'' Fraga told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have risen sharply since January, when Brazil stopped  
spending dollars to prop up its currency. The real has lost about 
43 percent of its value since then, which has made imported goods 
and components more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets reacted well to Fraga's announcement. The  
Bovespa index of the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, Latin America's 
largest, was up 2 percent in afternoon trading. The real 
strengthened to 2.07 to the dollar from 2.14 at Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	But many economists say raising interest rates will have a  
disastrous impact on the deficit and recession. The government 
admits the economy will shrink 3 percent to 4 percent this year, 
and private analysts predict it will be even worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs said Wednesday that Brazil  
should immediately cut interest rates to 20 percent to create jobs 
and take pressure off the deficit. But Brazilians are afraid of a 
return of the four-digit inflation that plagued the economy for 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The inflation rate will determine whether or not we have  
problems,'' said Fraga, a former associate of U.S. financier George 
Soros. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga gave himself powers to lower interest rates whenever he  
wanted but said the bank's monetary policy committee would have to 
approve any further increase. 
</P>
<P>
	By next month, Brazil expects to receive about $9 billion from a  
$41.5 billion aid package put together by the International 
Monetary Fund. The money will be available after the two sides 
reach an agreement on ways to fix the economy, which could be 
announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The show of command by Fraga was seen as a positive sign, after  
a month when monetary policy was virtually adrift. Fraga's 
predecessor, Francisco Lopes, was fired on Feb. 2 for failing to 
stop speculation that weakened the real. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:53:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Boeing Sold Jets Below Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A report by an aerospace analyst concludes that  
Boeing Co. last year sold its planes below the cost of producing 
them, with average prices paid by customers 14 percent to 27 
percent below list prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Nisbet, an analyst for JSA Research, attempted to quantify  
Boeing's practice of discounting its jetliners to customers in its 
price war with European archrival Airbus Industrie. 
</P>
<P>
	In his report, Nisbet uses a new figure disclosed by Boeing to  
subtract revenues it received for such extras as spare parts, 
training and modifications from its overall commercial-jet revenues 
of $35.5 billion. Alan Mulally, president of Boeing Commercial 
Airplane Group, told financial analysts last week that those extras 
amounted to $4 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	By subtracting the extras, Nisbet said he could estimate for the  
first time the prices customers paid last year for the airplanes 
themselves, and compare them with list prices, which Boeing has 
raised by 2 percent to 10 percent since last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, customers paid $31.5 billion for the 559 planes Boeing  
delivered last year, Nisbet said. He then calculated the average 
actual prices paid per aircraft model and compared them with the 
list prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked at what I found,'' he said. ``The airline that  
needs some airplanes in the short term might have to pay the list 
price for quick delivery, but the others are not coming close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing officials refused to comment on Nisbet's report or his  
methodology. The company does not release details of its aircraft 
sales, other than a gross value when a customer gives permission. 
Each sale is unique, varying widely by aircraft model, customer, 
financing arrangements, and the deal Boeing can cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing, the world's largest maker of commercial jet aircraft,  
made $1.12 billion profit last year on $56 billion in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Nisbet said that not only did Boeing sell its planes at a  
discount, it sold them below cost, losing almost $600 million on 
aircraft sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Nisbet figures Boeing had a 1998 pretax profit of $651 million  
on the sale of parts, services, training and other extras. Overall, 
the commercial airplane group reported a 1998 profit of just $63 
million, meaning Boeing ``was $590 million in the hole on their 
aircraft,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
