<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:25:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Threatens To Veto Bank Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A financial overhaul bill proposed by Senate  
Banking Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, split the committee along 
partisan lines today. 
</P>
<P>
	It faces a presidential veto because President Clinton believes  
the bill, which would lift the Depression-era barriers between 
banks, securities firms and insurance companies, fails to protect 
consumers and would hurt community lending laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure was adopted and sent to the full Senate by the  
Banking Committee, 11-9, with only the Republican senators 
supporting it. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also approved a GOP amendment exempting small  
banks -- with less than $100 million in assets -- from the community 
lending laws. In a party switch, Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., voted 
against the amendment while Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D., voted for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at an impasse before we even start,'' Sen. John Kerry,  
D-Mass., said at the beginning of a drafting session on Gramm's 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm said he regretted that the bill lacked the Democrats'  
support, and he promised to try to work out the differences. ``This 
is the beginning of the process,'' he told his colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Gramm added, ``I am increasingly convinced that the  
president doesn't want a bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In principle, the Clinton administration supports legislation to  
overhaul the financial services laws. But the White House has 
threatened to veto several versions in recent years that took an 
approach it rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal drafted by Gramm is more in line with the views of  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan than those of the 
administration. The bill calls for most new financial activities to 
be conducted by affiliated companies within bank holding companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin on Wednesday expressed  
the administration's ``strong support'' for a bipartisan compromise 
bill in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official cited as an example a provision in  
the compromise House bill, but absent from Gramm's, that would 
require banks selling securities to make sure they are appropriate 
for a consumer's income and circumstances. The official spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the House and Senate bills would create huge financial  
``supermarkets,'' offering consumers checking accounts, mutual 
funds, insurance policies and much more. Ralph Nader and other 
consumer advocates have expressed concern that the legislation, by 
allowing banks, brokerage firms and insurers to merge and get more 
deeply into each other's businesses, could bring a dangerous 
concentration of economic power in fewer hands. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Gramm, Clinton said his proposal would  
``undermine the effectiveness of the Community Reinvestment Act 
..., a law that has helped to build homes, create jobs and restore 
hope in communities across America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm, in response, insisted that his proposal would not weaken  
the community investment law that banks must follow, but would 
``restore its integrity.'' The 1977 law requires banks and thrifts 
to lend to the poor and minorities in their neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm's opposition to the law led him to block financial  
overhaul legislation in the Senate's waning days last fall. The 
legislation had squeaked through the House in May by one vote, 
214-213. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his new proposal, banks would not have to get a  
satisfactory community-lending rating from the government to 
conduct new financial activities within holding companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Financial services modernization is of such overriding  
importance to the national economy that President Clinton will be 
compelled to sign'' the bill, Gramm said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, Banking Committee Chairman Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa,  
and Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the panel's senior Democrat, on 
Monday unveiled a bipartisan compromise bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the lawmakers Wednesday, Rubin expressed the  
administration's ``strong support.'' The Treasury chief said the 
bill ``would benefit consumers, businesses and communities.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Rise on Export News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and wheat futures advanced Thursday on  
Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by unexpectedly heavy export 
demand. Soybean futures finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures jumped after the U.S. Agriculture Department  
reported exports in the past week of 1.14 million metric tons, well 
above the highest analyst estimate of 900,000 metric tons. The 
report put shipments to date 19 percent above the previous 
marketing year's pace and ahead of the USDA's estimate of a 15 
percent increase for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat export sales came in at 702,900 metric tons, also well  
above expectations of 400,000 metric tons being shipped. Wheat 
futures were also higher on assumptions of possible dry pockets in 
the Plains states, news that China's winter wheat crop is under 
moisture pressure and a generally tight worldwide winter wheat 
market, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also were supported by an increasing number of analyst  
reports that estimate spring plantings will fall sharply over the 
previous year, as farmers plant more lucrative soybean crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures followed wheat higher early, but retreated at  
the end of the session as nervous traders eyed bumper crops from 
South America. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery rose 2 cents to $2.62 1/2 cents per bushel;  
May corn was up to 2 1/4 cents to $2.17 cents per bushel; May oats 
were up 1 3/4 cents to $1.06 1/4 cents per bushel; May soybeans were up 1/4 
cent to $4.68 cents per bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and feeder cattle retreated on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs and pork bellies were both 
higher. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle was down .65 cent to 67.60 cents per pound;  
March feeder cattle fell .68 cent to 72.42 cents per pound; April 
lean hogs were up .87 cent to 43.42 cents per pound; March pork 
bellies were up 3 cents to 51.50 cents per pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:56:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Disaster Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government would help states  
prepare for natural disasters through a bill the House passed 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, approved 415-2, would provide $25 million in  
the current fiscal year and $80 million for 2000 to aid state 
program aimed at reducing losses from disasters. It also outlines 
steps to streamline programs to assist victims after disasters 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be spent for such things as mapping flood  
plains, relocating buildings and informing citizens about 
damage-prevention measures. Each state would receive at least 
$500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., a chief sponsor of the bill,  
estimated it would save the federal government $109 million in 
disaster relief over the first five years. Last year, more than $2 
billion was spent to help disaster victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``What this bill does is move us in the direction of not  
continuing to pay over and over again for the same losses to the 
same people in the same geographic areas,'' said Rep. James 
Oberstar, D-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, which still requires Senate consideration, also  
would increase to $25,000 the amount of federal aid available to 
each disaster victim family and provide up to $5,000 for emergency 
repairs to each home not covered by disaster insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the House passed a bill that would require  
the Small Business Administration and the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency to set up a pilot loan program to help small 
businesses and homeowners relocate and take other steps to reduce 
the impact of natural disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 707.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
