<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Edge Lower / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices edged lower Thursday as another  
flurry of strong economic data left traders bracing for signs of 
inflation in Friday's unemployment report. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/32, or  
$0.31 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, held steady at late Wednesday's seven-month 
high of 5.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds have been hit hard over the past two weeks by a series of  
reports revealing surprising strength in the economy that could 
prove inflationary. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend continued Thursday with retailers reporting strong  
February sales and new government data showing a rebound in factory 
orders and a 10-year low in new claims for unemployment benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors fear the Federal Reserve will slow the economy with a  
boost in interest rates. Rising interest rates hurt bonds by making 
their yields less competitive, while inflation makes fixed-income 
investments less attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Thursday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities fell 1/32 to 3/32 point, while intermediate maturities 
fell 1/8 to 7/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 2.48 
points to 1,274.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.60 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.48 
percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.74 percent, as the discount 
rose 0.02 percentage to 4.56 percent. One-year yields rose to 4.88 
percent, while the discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.64 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged from late Wednesday at 4.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 11/32 point to 123 9/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.27 percent from 5.25 percent late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
