<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fisk Might Return to Red Sox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Nearly 19 years after an angry parting  
with the Boston Red Sox, Carlton Fisk is considering returning to 
the team he hit one of baseball's most famous homers for. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing on the field Thursday before Boston's spring training  
opener, Fisk said he had a ``nice conversation'' with general 
manager Dan Duquette in the morning and planned further 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Although an exact role hasn't been determined, Duquette said  
Fisk could be ``a role model, a liaison'' or a catching instructor. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk, 51, said he didn't have much interest in returning to the  
Red Sox when he and Duquette first spoke about the possibility two 
years ago, but said ``it's starting to grow a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps his most memorable at-bat in a 24-year career that ended  
in 1993 with the Chicago White Sox came in Game 6 of the 1975 World 
Series. He hit a ball down the left field line, waved both arms 
toward fair territory and ended up with the game-winning homer in 
the 12th inning. But Cincinnati won Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years later, he became a free agent when the Red Sox failed  
to mail a contract on time. He joined the White Sox, where he had 
another bitter departure when they released him while they were on 
the road in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been a lot of water under that bridge,'' he said of  
his Red Sox experience. ``I think we've all matured and grown.'' He 
pointed out that different people ran the Red Sox then. 
</P>
<P>
	``That relationship is a long time ago,'' Duquette said. ``I  
think Carlton Fisk will be remembered above all else for his 
heroics in Game 6.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That could help him get into the Hall of Fame, although he fell  
short in the voting this year, the first time he was eligible. Fisk 
wouldn't say whether he would have a Red Sox or White Sox cap on 
his plaque if elected. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he wasn't angry about falling short in a year when  
Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Robin Yount all were elected in their 
first year of eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't feel unrecognized. I felt just a little disappointed.  
The three guys that were elected were absolutely deserving,'' Fisk 
said. But he's sure he is, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know in my heart that I was as good at my position as they  
were at theirs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk set the major league record of 2,226 games caught and had  
351 homers at that position, the most ever by a catcher. He had 25 
homers in games when he was not catching. He was only the third 
catcher to hit at least 300 home runs, score 1,000 runs and drive 
in 1,000 runs; the others were Yogi Berra and Johnny Bench, both 
Hall of Famers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
