<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hair Test May Reveal Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A test for breast cancer can be done be analyzing a single pubic  
hair, Australian researchers reported today in the journal Nature. 
</P>
<P>
	Radiologists at the University of New South Wales in Sydney  
found that microscopic characteristics in the hair may reveal 
whether a woman has breast cancer. They also believe that the hair 
may indicate whether a woman is carrying a certain gene mutation 
that raises the risk of later developing the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Pubic hair was found to be easier to read than scalp hair  
because it it less likely to be damaged by perms, dyes or the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Other scientists, however, said the study is too small to be  
conclusive. They also questioned whether the method is an 
improvement over existing tests -- mammograms for finding cancer, 
blood tests for identifying genetic risks. 
</P>
<P>
	The test is not approved for clinical use.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the researchers, radiologist Veronica James, said the  
hair test could help women living in poor, remote areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samples for this test could be posted from anywhere in the  
world in an envelope,'' Ms. James said. ``In many poorer countries, 
no mammography is available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers used sensitive X-ray equipment to analyze the  
scalp hair of 23 women who earlier had been diagnosed with breast 
cancer, and found their hair contained one or more extra rings in 
the keratin, or protein layer. Of 28 women who were known to be 
cancer-free, all but four did not have the extra rings. 
</P>
<P>
	The same pattern was found in 12 women whose pubic hair was  
analyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can look at the patterns we are getting from our hair  
samples and know that the diseased ones are different from the 
normal ones because they have changed in structure,'' Ms. James 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five women in the study had not been diagnosed with breast  
cancer, but earlier tests found they carried a mutation of the 
BRCA-1 gene associated with an inherited form of the disease. Hair 
from all five patients contained full or partial extra rings 
similar to those in the breast cancer patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. James said the results suggest that a woman's hair could  
indicate the presence of the BRCA-1 mutation even before cancer is 
detected. 
</P>
<P>
	David Savitz, chairman of epidemiology at the University of  
North Carolina, said pubic hair is a more reliable biological 
sample than scalp hair; he has used it to determine people's 
history of cocaine use. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the Australian study was too small and its results  
must be repeated in larger studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Savitz said he also questions widespread screening for the rare  
BRCA-1 form of the disease -- which accounts for as few as three in 
211 breast cancer cases, according to one 1998 study -- especially 
when there is no ``useful'' way to prevent it. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who have the defective genes sometimes choose drastic  
options, such as having their breasts removed while they are still 
healthy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
