<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Berates Shock Jock Remark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Thompson, in his new job as a radio talk  
show host, confronted a shock jock who was fired for making a 
racist remark. 
</P>
<P>
	And it was a one-sided conversation Thursday, with the former  
Georgetown basketball doing the talking. 
</P>
<P>
	``If one kid hears something as irresponsible as you said, that  
is dangerous to all of us,'' Thompson said in lecturing Doug ``The 
Greaseman'' Tracht on WTEM-AM. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracht was dismissed from his morning drive job at WARW-FM last  
week for playing part of a song by Grammy-award winning recording 
artist Lauryn Hill and then commenting, ``No wonder people drag 
them behind trucks,'' a reference to the dragging death of James 
Byrd, Jr. in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracht made an apology tour Wednesday, but the appearance on  
Thompson's show was a clash of two strong, divergent personalities 
well known in the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, along with co-host and ex-Washington Redskins player  
Doc Walker, lashed out at Tracht, who had little to say in his own 
defense other than repeated confessions of guilt and requests for 
forgiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Several times I've listened to you and laughed and said,  
`That's funny,' but that is a disappointment to me,'' Thompson 
said. ``I see absolutely no humor in racism. Can I forgive you? 
Yes. Can I forget? Very difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson suggested that Tracht receive counseling, and Tracht  
indicated he might. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hits home, and it hits home hard,'' Tracht told Thompson.  
``I have no justification. I'm not going to say, `Look at it this 
way.' I can't argue with anything you've said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is not the first time that Tracht has run afoul of the  
black community. In 1986, he made a disparaging remark about the 
Martin Luther King holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
