<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cheaper or Free Internet Entry Seen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Until now, it's been an Internet fact of life:  
No one roams the Web for free. 
</P>
<P>
	But nothing is set in stone online, least of all access plans  
and their price tags. And monthly dial-up fees could go the way of 
the dot matrix printer if others keep giving away what America 
Online -- the biggest Internet provider -- is trying to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL's popular unlimited access plan costs $21.95 a month and  
some companies offer restricted monthly plans for $9.95. With the 
advent of free Internet service, however, some Web users are 
deciding 10 bucks a month isn't such a great bargain after all. 
</P>
<P>
	Gateway announced last week that it would throw in a free year  
of its Internet service with any computer purchase of more than 
$1,000. Even more threatening to the stranglehold of 
pay-for-service providers has been the early success of some rivals 
that let customers dial up for free. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1 million Britons have signed on with Freeserve, which  
began operating in September and already has surpassed AOL as 
Britain's most popular Internet access provider. 
</P>
<P>
	NetZero, brought to the Web by the same venture capitalists who  
sparked an online stampede last month by giving away 
advertisement-rigged computers at www.Free-PC.com, has signed up 
400,000 customers since it launched a free service in October. 
</P>
<P>
	While it is a fraction of the more than 2 million subscribers  
added since mid-November by AOL, the king of connectivity with 16 
million subscribers, it is hardly a marginal development. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for free Web access, these services want free access  
to your eyes -- and a fixed portion of your computer screen -- for a 
parade of advertisements. Most Web users are used to this. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the free services are successful, Internet access could  
be reduced from a revenue-producer to a mere marketing gimmick -- a 
throw-in like PC software or pin-striping on a new car. 
</P>
<P>
	Some wonder if consumers will be getting what they bargained for  
from the upstart services, most of which have meager resources. 
</P>
<P>
	David Meier is among the skeptics, though he loves a good  
cyber-bargain. He even guides people to ``free stuff'' on the 
Internet with his site at www.y4i.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would always pay for access, because I don't want  
problems,'' he said. ``I don't want to worry about getting online 
or them being too busy, and I don't want that little box on my 
screen. I'd rather pay the 20 bucks a month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even those happy with their switch to a free Internet provider  
have doubts, including a young woman who subscribed recently to 
NetZero. 
</P>
<P>
	She sent the Westlake Village, Calif., company an e-mail  
bemoaning companies that go out of business within months leaving 
subscribers ``with a blank look on their face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She asked for a heads-up if business went bust: ``How long have  
you been operating, and if you DO go out of business anytime in the 
foreseeable future, will you let all the users know well in 
advance?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the listings that came up in a browser search for ``free  
Internet access'' were many with links to www.Freewwweb.com. But 
the Internet service isn't exactly free. The Connecticut-based 
company charges a one-time fee of about $120 but seems to be one of 
the few NetZero rivals with local dial-up numbers across most of 
the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Another service, webCOMBO, charges a one-time fee of $149.95 for  
otherwise free access to its national network. Others such as 
zDial, FreePPP and FreeI charge nothing but only have dial-up 
numbers in a specific region. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online has no plans to get into a price war with new  
services. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is certainly a very competitive industry, but we believe  
we offer the best value,'' said AOL spokeswoman Wendy Goldberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Most new services are far more vulnerable to financial pressures  
and technological problems than big players like AOL, AT&AMP;T, 
Microsoft Network, EarthLink and MindSpring. 
</P>
<P>
	That could mean little or no customer support and the risk that  
the service might suddenly vanish along with your e-mail address. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers also have doubts as to whether the advertising revenue  
alone can cover the huge costs of running an Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not funded big time, there's no way you can provide  
good service,'' said Ilan Klein, president of Vizooal Inc., a New 
York-based Internet marketing firm. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Fans Are Into March Badness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While college basketball fans are immersed in March Madness, NBA  
fans are into March Badness after a month of February Futility. 
</P>
<P>
	When St. John's beat Notre Dame last week after looking inept in  
the first 20 minutes, coach Mike Jarvis said, ``It looked like the 
Knicks-Nets in the first half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis, of course, was referring to New York Knicks and the New  
Jersey Nets, who a few days earlier seemed to put the ball 
everywhere but in the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA likes to say it has the world's greatest athletes. What  
it could use are some basketball players. 
</P>
<P>
	What fans have been getting are preseason games at  
regular-season prices, although there have been some special ticket 
deals, as players huff and puff up and down the floor and throw up 
clinkers from all angles and distances. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a struggle for a team to hit 80 points in a game. The Utah  
Jazz contrived to score only 56 points, the second-lowest in an NBA 
game for a team since the 24-second shot clock went into effect in 
the 1954-55 season, eight years after the NBA was founded. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan could score that many points on a good night.  
Come back, Michael! 
</P>
<P>
	Ineptitude has become such a norm that it has become the story.  
Did the Bulls lose? That's no longer the question. Now it's `Did 
the Clippers win?' As of Tuesday, with no game scheduled Wednesday, 
the Los Angeles Clippers were 0-13 and in cold pursuit of the NBA's 
worst-start record of 0-17 set by the Miami Heat in the 1988-89 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	There are those who note that tough defense is a reason for the  
scoring drought. Maybe, but more legitimate reasons might be the 
playground mentality of many pros and the idea that showmanship is 
what counts. So if you can't slam dunk, then throw one up from 
downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps a bigger reason, because of the owner's lockout, is  
teams are being asked to play four or five games a week instead of 
two or three so that a 50-game season can be held before the 
interminable playoffs begin. Four games in seven days seem to be 
just too many for the world's greatest athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Is it possible that some of these multi-millionaires did not  
work at getting into and staying in the best physical condition 
during the lockout? 
</P>
<P>
	The shorter training camp and more intense schedule have to have  
had something to do with the rash of injuries that have hit the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance, however, has been good, and not only because of the  
league's public relations efforts. The faithful seem to be willing 
to put up with subpar play, at least for the current season. 
</P>
<P>
	But it would seem that the NBA could be headed for trouble in  
the post-Jordan era unless basketball becomes as important as show 
boating. If a player can't be a superstar, he should just settle 
for being a player and part of the game. The faithful would 
appreciate that. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the collegians take over the world's biggest stage --  
the country's television sets -- and you can be sure they'll make 
the most of the opportunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Heads to Kosovo Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. Bob Dole says he will urge ethnic  
Albanians in Kosovo to sign a proposed peace agreement as soon as 
possible because further delays can only benefit Serb leader 
Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	After a scheduled departure from Washington this afternoon, Dole  
plans talks with a variety of Kosovo Albanians on Friday as an 
emissary of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of an administration diplomatic offensive for a peace  
settlement, the administration also is considering sending 
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke to Belgrade in the coming days to try 
to win Serb approval of the six-nation plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was a key architect of the October cease fire in  
Kosovo that has been widely violated since then. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James Foley pointed to recent  
encouraging signs that the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have been 
moving toward acceptance of the plan. The key features of the plan 
include continued Serb sovereignty over the province plus self-rule 
for the majority Albanian population. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Albanians formally agree, Foley predicted, ``pressure  
on the Serbs to do so will mount. '' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that that message will become increasingly clear to  
President Milosevic in the days to come,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement late Wednesday, Dole, former Republican  
presidential candidate who lost to Clinton in 1996, said the peace 
plan is not perfect but provides the best chance to put the people 
of Kosovo on a course of self-rule and liberty. 
</P>
<P>
	Of particular importance, Dole said, is the provision calling  
for implementation of the agreement by NATO troops with U.S. 
participation. ``With NATO troops for protection,'' he said, ``the 
people of Kosovo can determine their own agenda and future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said Milosevic's ``aggressive policies continue to threaten  
the entire region. The United States and our NATO allies must act. 
We cannot afford to allow this destabilizing situation to continue 
to spill over into neighboring countries or tear our NATO allies 
apart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole's assignment pleased Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the  
senior Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob Dole brings credibility in the Balkans,'' Biden told a  
group of reporters. Biden also suggested that Dole's role ``freezes 
some elements of the Republican party'' from criticizing the 
administration's efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is eager for a settlement to be reached by  
the time peace talks resume in Paris on March 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley's remarks were devoid of military threats, suggesting that  
for now, the administration is content to rely on diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, officials expressed concern over military  
deployments by the Yugoslav Army in violation of the October truce. 
They said the violations were not one-sided, pointing to 
provocative actions taken by Kosovar Albanian rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Defense Secretary William Cohen predicted that  
without a peace plan and peacekeepers, there was a ``likelihood of 
bloodshed continuing to take place on a massive scale, with 
migrations of tens of thousands of people out of the region 
spilling into the other areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That, Cohen said, could ``present us with a military mission in  
the future which would be far more expensive'' than the 
4,000-member U.S. contingent the administration envisions for 
Kosovo under a peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:46:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Campaign Hits Higher Gear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, kicking his  
presidential campaign into higher gear, will visit Iowa and New 
Hampshire on the same day this month. 
</P>
<P>
	That swing on March 15 will be followed by a separate trip to  
Iowa later in the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time we will do Iowa and New Hampshire as  
campaign stops and the first time that we know of that we're going 
to do both on the same day,'' said spokeswoman Patricia Ewing. Gore 
has repeatedly traveled to the early primary and caucus states, but 
called it official travel and billed taxpayers for the trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign will pay a portion of his political travels.  
</P>
<P>
	The vice president has formed a campaign committee and opened  
offices in Washington, but will not formally announce his candidacy 
until late summer or early fall. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George Bush's presidential exploratory committee will  
be headed by a diverse and high-profile list of Republicans, aides 
said. They are keeping the list secret until Bush's news conference 
Sunday, though the group is said to include former Secretary of 
State George Shultz. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has invited national reporters to Austin, Texas, for a news  
conference unveiling his committee. Several members of the 
committee will be on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign will file its papers with the Federal Election  
Commission on Monday, allowing Bush to raise and spend money as he 
decides whether to seek the presidency. Associates expect him to 
run, though a final decision and formal announcement are several 
months away. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, several sources close to Bush, speaking on  
condition of anonymity, say his political director is expected to 
be Maria Cino, former executive director at the Republican House 
campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	A potential Bush rival, millionaire businessman Steve Forbes,  
has a press secretary in mind for his yet-to-be-announced campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Juleanne Glover Weiss, senior policy adviser for Republican Sen.  
John Ashcroft of Missouri, will be Forbes' top spokeswoman if, as 
expected, he seeks the GOP nomination, a source close to Forbes 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft toyed with the idea of running for president, but  
backed out at the last minute. Weiss, 30, has been publicity 
director for the conservative Weekly Standard magazine and 
legislative director for the Project for the Republican Future. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Another GOP hopeful, conservative activist Gary Bauer, says he  
has raised $750,000 in 30 days and has qualified for federal 
matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	A candidate must show $50,000 in eligible contributions from  
more than 20 states to qualify. ``Gary has strong support -- 
financially and politically -- all across the country,'' spokesman 
Tim Goeglein said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He is still far short of the $15 to $20 million that most  
financial experts say will be needed to compete in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Being a political consultant was never enough for Tom Cole. The  
49-year-old is Oklahoma's state's secretary of state, top adviser 
for Gov. Frank Keating and liaison with leaders of the 
legislature's Democratic majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he will be the new chief of staff for Republican Party  
chairman Jim Nicholson. 
</P>
<P>
	``My loss is definitely the RNC's gain,'' said Keating, chairman  
of the Republican Governors' Association. 
</P>
<P>
	He appointed Cole secretary of state in 1995, after his first  
election. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole heads up a highly successful Oklahoma-based political  
consulting firm, Cole-Hargrave Snodgrass and Associates. He was 
executive director of the GOP House campaign committee from 1991 to 
1993, an Oklahoma state senator from 1988 to 1991 and state party 
chairman from 1985 to 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson has been under pressure to strengthen the party's  
political operation after weaker-than-expected results in 
November's midterm elections. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITORS NOTE: Associated Press Writer Mike Glover contributed to  
this report from Des Moines, Iowa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
