<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:06:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Seeks Hurricane Mitch Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress to provide  
enhanced trade benefits to countries of Central America and the 
Caribbean to help them recover from the devastation of Hurricane 
Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's proposal was announced today -- four days  
before the president travels to Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador 
and Guatemala to inspect the damage from the storm that killed more 
than 9,000 people and left millions more homeless. Clinton has 
asked Congress for $956 million to help rebuild the region. 
</P>
<P>
	National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said the new measure  
would eliminate U.S. tariffs on certain textile and apparel 
products. The benefits would apply from Oct. 1, 1999 to June 30, 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill would authorize the president to offer enhanced,  
temporary trade benefits to Caribbean Basin countries,'' Berger 
said. He said the benefits would help Caribbean and Central 
American countries ``recover from the serious damage'' of Hurriance 
Mitch and encourage them to adopt policies that could pave the way 
for their participation in a broader free trade agreement in the 
Americas. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Echaveste, Clinton's deputy chief of staff, said that  
Central American leaders, when they met with Clinton in December, 
said that trade concessions were ``at the top of their list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the proposed benefits were a step toward giving the  
Caribbean and Central American nations parity with Mexico, which 
enjoys trade breaks under the North American Free Trade Agreement. 
``It's a part of it, it's not full, it's not NAFTA,'' Echaveste 
said. ``It gets closer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an attempt to get closer to conditions that exist in  
NAFTA, not just for textiles but also the non-textile areas,'' said 
Peter Romero, acting assistant secretary of State for Latin 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it also was intended to ``make it more attractive for  
investors to rethink Central America and the Caribbean in terms of 
particularly textile investments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, White House press secretary Joe Lockart said ``there  
is a general concern'' about the Senate's handling of the Central 
American relief bill. He said some senators were trying to use this 
bill to ``set up a political fight here,'' much like they did with 
legislation for the International Monetary Fund bailout last year 
and the 1997 flood relief bill. He urged lawmakers not to ``head 
down a partisan path'' on this legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an emergency. The need is real. The need is  
desperate,'' Lockhart said. ``These are issues that should be above 
the partisan fighting here in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger said the Hurricane Mitch was the worst natural disaster  
ever to hit the Western Hemisphere. The countries suffered losses 
estimated at between $7 billion to $10 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0090 </DOCNO>
