<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Rule Ends Senate's Secret Holds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators may still block, but they no longer  
can hide. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the word from Senate leaders Wednesday as they ended an  
age-old practice that individual senators used to delay action on 
bills or nominations they found objectionable while remaining 
anonymous among their peers. 
</P>
<P>
	They can still place holds, but they won't be anonymous.  
</P>
<P>
	In a joint letter distributed to colleagues, Majority Leader  
Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said 
the change was made to ``address some concerns raised regarding 
this practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents say the practice -- known as a ``hold'' -- is unfair and  
undemocratic. 
</P>
<P>
	It began decades ago as a senatorial courtesy but has become  
more common and controversial, especially when used to block White 
House nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	By placing a ``hold,'' a single senator could block action on a  
bill, nomination or other business without explanation or being 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we believe that all members will agree this practice of  
'secret holds' has been a senatorial courtesy extended by party 
leaders for many Congresses, it is our intention to address some 
concerns regarding this practice,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	From now on, members who want to delay any legislation or  
nomination must notify the bill's sponsor and the appropriate 
committees. Members must also notify their respective leaders in 
writing. 
</P>
<P>
	The news brought instant praise from two senators who've tried  
to end the practice. Holds are not part of the Senate's formal 
rules but grew out of a century-old tradition by which senators who 
were unable to attend debates or votes would ask their leaders to 
postpone action and the requests would be honored. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an outrageous practice, it should have been changed  
years ago and it comes pretty close to amounting to legislative 
blackmail,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who has campaigned to 
eliminate it since joining the Senate since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said the delays wasted time.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost impossible to run down, in some instances, who's  
holding things up,'' he said. ``This will make it out in the open, 
make us more productive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley and Wyden have used ``holds'' themselves, but are among  
the few who go public by stating their objections in the 
Congressional Record, the official transcript of House and Senate 
proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	Wyden said the change should help boost public confidence in the  
Senate, particularly after the rules required it to shut the people 
out during key decision-making moments in President Clinton's 
impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate is sending a message that there's going to be some  
sunshine on the floor of this body,'' Wyden added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 19:24:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Ballpark Has Toxic Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A huge mound of lead-contaminated dirt sits  
in the middle of what will be center field at the San Francisco 
Giants' new ballpark while officials figure out what to do with it. 
</P>
<P>
	A convoy of trucks hauled about 6,000 cubic yards of the toxic  
soil across the bay to an Alameda County landfill before state 
toxicologists decided they had mistakenly declared it safe to move 
and that the soil is, in fact, hazardous waste. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves 12,000 cubic yards of the dirt smack in the middle  
of what will be Pacific Bell Park while the state conducts more 
tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants said the problem will not delay completion of the  
$210 million ballpark, scheduled to open in April 2000. ``We're 
certainly expecting to be able to haul to Altamont,'' said Giants 
vice president Jack Bair. 
</P>
<P>
	The situation may force special hearings by the San Francisco  
Environmental Commission, which advises Mayor Willie Brown and the 
Board of Supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there are toxic contaminants in the dirt, we'd want to look  
into how it will be disposed of and the method of transport,'' said 
Commissioner Steve Krefting. 
</P>
<P>
	Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano also scheduled a  
hearing on the problem, which was first reported in the city's SF 
Weekly newspaper last month. The discovery of the mistaken 
classification, which the San Francisco Chronicle reported about 
Thursday, makes the hearing all the more important, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to get to the bottom of this. I understand the drive  
of the Giants to get their stadium, but I don't want to sacrifice 
the citizens' safety. Let's see what the hearing unearths,'' 
Ammiano said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of downtown San Francisco, including the waterfront and the  
area where the ballpark is being built, was created by filling in 
parts of San Francisco Bay with debris from the 1906 earthquake and 
other sources. The fill contained collapsed buildings that had been 
painted with lead-based paint. As a result, the soil contains 
elevated levels of lead. 
</P>
<P>
	State toxicologists had allowed the transfer of the excavated  
soil to begin last week, telling the Giants that the level of lead 
in the dirt was not dangerous enough to classify it as a hazardous 
material, which costs much more to dispose. 
</P>
<P>
	But late Tuesday, the Department of Toxic Substances Control  
informed the Giants their original classification was in error. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Baker, a spokesman for the department, said scientists in  
the waste evaluation unit mistakenly used a less-stringent federal 
standard to determine that the dirt was not sufficiently poisonous 
to be deemed hazardous waste. 
</P>
<P>
	The soil doesn't threaten the health of workers or the general  
population, but could contaminate groundwater, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Jim Spagnole, spokesman for the California Environmental  
Protection Agency, said it was possible the remaining dirt could be 
taken to Altamont, even if its lead content exceeds the state 
standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 08:47:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blackmun Made Key Abortion Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry A. Blackmun knew he would be remembered  
forever as the author of Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court 
decision that legalized abortion nationwide. But he always hoped 
his 24-year tenure on the high court would yield a broader legacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope I would be remembered as a person of judicial integrity  
who wrote acceptably well and contributed in more than one field,'' 
he once told The Associated Press. ``I'd like to be known just as a 
good worker in the vineyard who held his own and contributed 
generally to the advancement of the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun died today. He was 90, and had retired as a Supreme  
Court justice in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	To those who didn't know him, Blackmun might have seemed a  
cranky old guy. On the bench, he often displayed a judicial scowl 
and could be snappish with lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	At other times, his homespun questions hid the intellect of a  
magna cum laude mathematics graduate of Harvard who considered 
becoming a doctor and for years served as general counsel to the 
Mayo Clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Blackmun took off the judicial robe and put on one of  
the ever-present cardigan sweaters he wore in his offices, warmth 
and humor emerged. 
</P>
<P>
	He could talk at length about his three daughters and his  
grandchildren, about his former law clerks and their families. And 
he could joke about his longevity. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 1990 interview, Blackmun called himself one of the high  
court's ``three old goats'' whose inevitable departure, he 
predicted, would solidify conservative domination of the court for 
the next 40 or 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 81 at the time. Fellow Justices William J. Brennan and  
Thurgood Marshall were 84 and 82, respectively. Both retired 
shortly thereafter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Time will take its toll on the three old goats,'' Blackmun  
said. ``We will be replaced by appointees of the current 
administration or the next one, which is probably going to be 
another Bush administration. So it seems to me that before too long 
the court could be nine conservatives, and that surely will last 
well into the next century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was wrong. Bill Clinton beat George Bush in the 1992 election  
and picked Blackmun's successor, Stephen G. Breyer. Clinton also 
named Ruth Bader Ginsburg to the high court. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun once was called a conservative, but in later years was  
called a liberal. He believed he always was somewhere in between. 
</P>
<P>
	``One has to develop his attitude toward the (Constitution's)  
great phrases,'' he once told an interviewer. ``What does equal 
protection mean? What is cruel and unusual punishment? I would hope 
that I have grown in that respect over the years. But as far as 
shifting from conservatism to liberalism, I don't believe I have 
done that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his sometimes passionate rhetoric, Blackmun also had a  
passion for baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	He followed the Minnesota Twins and the Chicago Cubs, but his  
love of baseball transcended team allegiance. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Blackmun the baseball fan who wrote what may be the most  
extraordinary paragraph in American law. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 1972 decision called Flood vs. Kuhn, the Supreme Court  
allowed major league baseball to keep its exemption from federal 
antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the court, Blackmun began with what might be called  
an ode to the national pastime. In the fifth paragraph, he embarked 
on a journey through some of the game's most famous names -- 88 
players, owners, managers and even umpires in all. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are the many names, celebrated for one reason or  
another, that have sparked the diamond and its environs and that 
have provided tinder for recaptured thrills, for reminiscence and 
comparisons, and for conversations and anticipations in-season and 
off-season: Ty Cobb, Babe Ruth, Tris Speaker, Walter Johnson, Henry 
Chadwick, Eddie Collins, Lou Gehrig, Grover Cleveland Alexander, 
Rogers Hornsby, Harry Hooper, Goose Goslin, Jackie Robinson, Honus 
Wagner ... Rabbit Maranville, Jimmie Foxx, Lefty Grove. The list 
seems endless,'' Blackmun wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:43:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' DeShields Breaks Thumb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Baltimore second baseman Delino  
DeShields will be out 5-7 weeks after fracturing a bone near the 
base of his left thumb in Thursday's intrasquad game. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor-league outfielder Luis Matos hit a line drive that struck  
the thumb portion of DeShields' glove as he made the catch for the 
final out. DeShields, who signed a three-year, $12.5 million 
contract this winter after two seasons in St. Louis, removed his 
glove and shook the hand as he headed toward the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	DeShields singled to left field in the bottom of the third  
inning and later scored in the A team's 12-7 victory. He was 
replaced by Carlos Casimiro and taken to Dr. Jim Guerra's office in 
Fort Lauderdale for X-rays, which revealed the fracture. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Frank Wren said DeShields' hand will be in a  
cast 3-4 weeks and he'll need another 2-3 weeks of rehabilitation, 
meaning he won't be ready by Opening Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Wren said the thumb was ``very tender'' when trainer Richie  
Bancells examined it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ball was hit very hard. I don't know if it knuckled on  
him, but it kind of took off at the last moment,'' Wren said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he's also battling health problems, utility infielder  
Jeff Reboulet's playing time is certain to increase with DeShields' 
injury. Reboulet, who has been receiving treatment for tendinitis 
in his left heel, will start at second base and bat in DeShields' 
No. 2 slot in Saturday's exhibition opener against Minnesota at 
Fort Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	Reboulet started at second base for the B team in Tuesday's  
opening intrasquad game and doubled in three at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing in the game was fine,'' he said, ``but running off the  
field, which is more of a heel-toe action, bothers me more than 
running around the bases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Amaral, who signed a two-year deal this winter, also will  
be considered as an alternative to DeShields. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt he would be a guy we'd look for to go full-time during  
DeShields' absence,'' Wren said. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Ray Miller said he'll also rotate minor-league  
infielders Jesse Garcia, Jerry Hairston and Carlos Casimiro at 
second, then decide on a long-term option if DeShields' injury 
proves more serious. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a tough kid. It won't take him long to come back,''  
Miller said. ``The funny thing is, he went up the next time and hit 
a rocket. Obviously, he's down right now, but he'll bounce back. 
Sometimes things happen for a reason, though I don't know what the 
reason is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Mike Bordick has been using this time in camp to get  
acquainted with DeShields, 30, after two seasons with Roberto 
Alomar as his double-play partner. Alomar signed with the Cleveland 
Indians as a free agent this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more you play with somebody, the more you learn their body  
language and how they respond. In that regard, it's going to be 
tough,'' Bordick said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
