<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Tips on Dangerous Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If abducted in a public place, don't go  
quietly, the State Department advises Americans who get in trouble 
abroad. Instead, ``make as much commotion as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If aboard a hijacked plane, observe the characteristics of the  
hijackers, privately think up nicknames for each one for later 
identification, and ``respond in a regulated tone of voice'' if 
spoken to, the department says. When traveling on business, make 
hotel reservations without using a company's name, only its 
address. 
</P>
<P>
	The worldly wise branch of the U.S. government doesn't want to  
restrain people's wanderlust. But it knows how dangerous the world 
can sometimes be. Known for its travel warnings -- the list of 
countries Americans are advised to avoid completely -- the 
department's Consular Affairs Bureau offers a lot more information 
than that for those who know where to find it. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Americans who rely solely on the travel warnings when  
deciding where to go are missing information that could mean the 
difference between life and death. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the slaughter of eight tourists at the edge of the Bwindi  
National Park, U.S. officials did not highlight Uganda as posing 
special danger. In fact, the area of the attack is described in a 
December consular report as ``generally safe,'' with ``some 
banditry and armed robbery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that same report, publicly available if little-known, is  
full of so much foreboding about Uganda in general that it is 
likely to give all but the most adventurous tourist pause. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar reports, or ``consular information sheets,'' offer the  
same level of detail on all countries, but tourists often don't 
know that when they book a vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans do not like surprises,'' said a State Department  
consular official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``These 
sheets give them lots of foreshadowing of surprises that may befall 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Americans traveling to Russia are told that in the  
Caucasus region, ``local criminal gangs routinely kidnap 
foreigners, including Americans, for ransom.'' Trouble spots are 
noted in countries that tourists don't hesitate to visit -- for 
France, the Paris train lines most popular with thieves are 
described. 
</P>
<P>
	And about Uganda, tourists are told in great detail about the  
criminal and political violence experienced in many parts of the 
country -- and warned not to take food or drink from strangers on 
public transit, because it might be doped. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials question whether much of this information is being  
passed on by travel agents and tour companies, which are more 
likely to stick to the State Department's list of countries to 
avoid -- 28 currently. 
</P>
<P>
	``Does a travel agent who's hypothetically trying to sell an  
umpteen-thousand-dollar trip to see gorillas necessarily want to 
tell the customer about the consular information sheet? Well, they 
should,'' the State Department official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alistair Ballantine, president of Abercrombie and Kent  
International, an upscale tour group that ran a gorilla camp where 
the assault happened, said the area had been open for seven years 
without trouble for tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	``We rely very much upon the State Department and their  
advice,'' he said. ``If there's a full warning on a place, we 
insist on the clients reading and signing the warning.'' But 
because most bookings come through travel agents, he said, ``we 
look to them to pass on current information'' such as that 
contained in consular sheets. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from countries on its don't-go list, the State Department  
has 12 ``public announcements'' in effect for other nations and 
four in effect for worldwide threats. These detail risks that may 
be confined to certain areas of a country or are temporary, 
</P>
<P>
	The Ugandan attack prompted the department to issue a public  
announcement advising Americans to postpone travel to western 
Uganda. 
</P>
<P>
	Another such announcement, issued Jan. 5, warned that extremists  
may be planning attacks on U.S. interests in Egypt and that 
Americans there should keep a low profile, vary routes and times of 
travel and treat unfamiliar mail suspiciously. That advice is 
standard for Americans traveling or living in possibly unsafe 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Even those announcements, however, don't contain the wealth of  
information supplied by the consular sheets. Despite all the 
trouble noted in Uganda in the December report, no public 
announcement was in effect for that country until the latest 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Travel warnings, public announcements, consular sheets and tips  
on safety abroad are available at the Bureau of Consular Affairs 
web site at http://travel.state.gov or by calling 1-202-647-5225 
and pressing 3. To have a report automatically faxed, call 
1-202-647-3000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
