<HEADLINE> Cablevision Might Try To Buy Mets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If Cablevision's chairman is negotiating to buy  
the New York Mets, it's news to Nelson Doubleday, the team's 
co-owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Doubleday is denying reports that Charles Dolan, rebuffed in his  
attempt last year to buy into the New York Yankees, has approached 
him about selling the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's an old pal of mine,'' Doubleday told the New York Post.  
``Believe me, if he was interested in buying this team, I would 
know about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doubleday was not immediately available for further comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Mets co-owner Fred Wilpon refused comment on a report  
that Cablevision is willing to pay $500 million to $600 million for 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing I can say,'' explained Wilpon, who the Daily  
News said is interested in conjunction with Dolan in developing a 
parcel of property for a new Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Cablevision spokesman Charles Schueler neither confirmed nor  
denied there are talks concerning purchase of the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``While it is our policy not to comment on rumors and  
speculation in the media, we note that Cablevision has enjoyed 
excellent long-term relationships with the Mets and Yankees as 
their primary television provider,'' Cablevision said in a 
statement. ``We communicate regularly with the ownership of both 
teams and maintain an active interest in the future of those 
relationships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cablevision already owns the New York Knicks and Rangers, and  
holds television rights to the Yankees, Mets, Knicks, Rangers, 
Islanders, and New Jersey Nets and Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan's chances of buying the Yankees ended with last week's  
announcement that the baseball club and the Nets had signed a 
letter of intent to merge the two teams' business operations. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to Dolan's attempts to buy the Yankees, under which  
George Steinbrenner would have remained as the general partner, the 
proposed Mets deal would result in Cablevision purchasing the team 
entirely and keeping Wilpon as the general partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
