<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Vs. Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar jumped against other currencies  
Thursday as U.S. economic fundamentals continued to outshine poor 
performances in Japan and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has been buying (dollars) today,'' said Hajime Sato,  
assistant general manager of the treasury department at Daiwa 
International Trust Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 123.35  
Japanese yen, up from 121.77 on Wednesday. Also in late trading, 
the euro was quoted at $1.0805, down from $1.0890. The euro dipped 
as low as $1.0790, its first time below $1.0800 since its 
inception. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the yen began during Asian trading  
when investors seized upon remarks by Kazuyoshi Kaneko, who heads a 
newly created Liberal Democratic Party committee to monitor the 
turbulent bond market. The government is trying to dig the country 
out of its worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaneko said he was considering new ways to cap the rise in  
long-term interest rates, perhaps by having the central bank buy 
more government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Bank of Japan did just that: It bought  
short-term government bonds, flooding the interbank loan market 
with cash. That sent a key interest rate to an all-time low of 0.02 
percent and undermined the value of the yen. Lower interest rates 
make a country's currency and assets less appealing to foreign 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's problems came as the European Central Bank,  
representing the 11 countries using the new currency, decided not 
to change interest rates during a policy meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were discouraged because they expected a rate cut to  
stimulate borrowing and spending to move the economy along. The 
euro dropped to another low right after the announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast with Japan and Europe's economic problems, fresh  
economic reports displayed the U.S.'s strength. 
</P>
<P>
	New orders to U.S. factories surged in January for the second  
consecutive month, retailers reported higher-than-expected sales in 
February and the average level of new applications for unemployment 
benefits in February reached a 10-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4699 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4597, and 1.5253 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5267. The British 
pound fell to $1.6098, down from $1.6134. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8100 German 
marks, up from 1.7960; 6.0716 French francs, up from 6.0241; and 
Italian lire, 1,792.11, up from 1,779.36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
