<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama Senate Shuts Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- The shouting in the Alabama Senate this  
week was so intense that a 5-year-old girl visiting her senator 
father cried. Now the shouting has turned into a silent standoff, 
with Democrats staging a boycott in their power struggle with the 
Republican lieutenant governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen Democrats -- a majority of the 35-member Senate --  
refused to show up for work Wednesday and Thursday. That is a 
strong act of protest in a state where the Legislature can meet 
only 30 days a year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, they are suing Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, calling  
him a ``madman'' who violated their constitutional rights by 
pushing through rules dramatically increasing his power. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's insane to think one man can run over the majority of an  
elected body,'' said Senate President Pro Tem Lowell Barron, a 
Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	The battle started in November, when Windom became the first  
Republican elected lieutenant governor in Alabama this century. 
That also made him presiding officer in the Senate, which has been 
controlled by the Democrats for more than 100 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the Democrats stripped him of most of his power in  
an organizational session presided over by Gov.-elect Don 
Siegelman, a Democrat who was still lieutenant governor at the 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	But Windom snatched the power back on Tuesday, the Legislature's  
opening day, by gaveling through new rules on a voice vote while he 
ignored the shouts and shaking fists of Democrats demanding a roll 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	One visitor to the chamber called it a ``war zone.'' Sen. Rodger  
Smitherman's 5-year-old daughter, Crystal, became so frightened by 
the screaming grown-ups that she started crying. 
</P>
<P>
	The quickly gaveled rules, among other things, allow Windom to  
appoint new committees to consider major bills and to decide which 
committee considers each bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 17 of Windom's allies -- 12 Republicans and five  
Democrats -- did attend the Senate sessions on Wednesday and 
Thursday, that is one short of the number needed for a legal 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the state constitution, the Senate has to keep trying to  
meet each day -- including Saturday and Sunday -- until a majority of 
the Senate shows up. Each day that is missed kills one of the 30 
meeting days the Legislature is allowed each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are prepared to stay out however long it takes to get our  
right restored to vote in that body,'' Barron said. ``We're 
protecting democracy and there is no price too great to pay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides expect the boycott to last at least through Monday,  
when a judge is scheduled to hear the Democrats' lawsuit. By that 
time, nearly one-fourth of the legislative session will be gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Windom's allies said taxpayers will tire quickly of senators  
drawing their pay and doing nothing, as well as spending taxpayer 
money on a lawsuit over Senate rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman has refused to get involved, saying, ``My job is to  
fix schools, not rules.'' But he is trying to cut Windom's budget 
by two-thirds, prompting Windom to say on Thursday: ``It's another 
indication the whole purpose has been to destroy the constitutional 
office of lieutenant governor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the business of the people is on hold, including  
Siegelman's plan to create a state lottery to pay for education 
programs and college scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	State GOP chairman Winton Blount sees no quick end.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to have to melt down some more,'' he said. ``Then  
they will find something in the middle.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:55:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell, IBM Make $16 Billion Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They won't carry labels saying ``IBM Inside,''  
but Dell Computer Corp.'s machines will soon fill up with more 
hard-disk drives, memory chips and other parts made by Big Blue. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM and Dell, two of the computer industry's biggest rivals,  
announced a remarkable supply deal Thursday in which Dell agreed to 
buy $16 billion worth of equipment from IBM over the next seven 
years. The companies also arranged to jointly develop new 
technology and give each other sneak previews of future products. 
</P>
<P>
	High-tech companies routinely share technology blueprints, but  
the unusually broad agreement between IBM and Dell underscores how 
intense industry pressures have grown, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM is the world's biggest maker of computers, but its personal  
computer business been struggling for several years due to sluggish 
sales and price wars that have squeezed profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Dell -- the fastest-growing PC maker and the No. 2  
manufacturer behind Compaq Computer Corp. -- reported last quarter 
that its sales fell short of Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	While IBM already sells parts to Dell, ``What is new is the size  
and the magnitude of the whole thing,'' said Chris Goodhue, an 
analyst with the Gartner Group research firm in Stamford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal ensures steady sales for IBM while giving Dell  
consistent supplies and a potential technology edge over its 
rivals. That is key to helping Dell expand its sales beyond mainly 
desktop PCs to more powerful and profitable machines called servers 
which run business computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrangement also promises to shake up already delicate  
supplier-manufacturer arrangements in the industry, where companies 
seeking the lowest price frequently switch suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal computer makers buy many of the parts that go inside  
their machines from others. Intel Corp., the biggest maker of 
computer chips, arranges for its customers to post stickers on 
their boxes saying ``Intel Inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dell's deal with IBM allows it to continue to buy parts from  
others, but it has a strong incentive to give a large chunk of 
business to IBM. In particular, analysts say, Dell is likely to 
step up purchases of IBM's hard-disk drives that store computer 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said that could steal business from other suppliers  
such as Seagate Technology Inc., the world's largest independent 
maker of computer disk drives. Seagate gets 5 percent of its sales 
from Dell, but last year lost $530 million amid a worldwide 
oversupply of drives. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagate shares fell 5 percent Thursday, losing $1.62 1/2 to $28 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	A Seagate spokesman played down the supply move.  
</P>
<P>
	Dell ``is a key customer for us and we definitely have a  
strategic relationship with them and will continue to do so,'' said 
the spokesman, Phil Montero. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM closed up $4.25 at $171 on the NYSE. Dell's shares rose 94  
cents to $81.87 1/2 in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	For IBM, the deal helps ensure a steady and increasing flow of  
business from a company that is already one of its largest 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a significant growth opportunity,'' said Dave Ernsberger,  
an IBM vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM likely will give Dell a nice discount on the parts, said  
Barry Jaruzelski, a partner at the Booz, Allen &AMP; Hamilton 
consultant firm. Company officials declined to comment on price. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a safe assumption the pricing agreement must be fairly  
attractive for Dell to agree to such an expansive arrangement,'' 
Jaruzelski said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 02:53:02 </DATE_TIME>
