<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Ship Beached Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALDPORT, Ore. (AP) -- The New Carissa's haunting of the Oregon  
coast has reached one month, and it's not going to end any time 
soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The oil-laden bow section of the cargo ship has found a new  
beach to menace, running aground early Wednesday near Waldport 
after breaking free from a tug in a storm the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	The 420-foot wreck drifted for 14 hours before landing at  
Waldport. It had gone out 50 miles -- and come back to land, 80 
miles farther north. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to get that thing,'' said an exasperated Bill  
Milwee, salvage consultant to the ship's Japanese owners. ``She's 
not going to beat me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It could be several days before crews are able to try again.  
</P>
<P>
	The ship drifted aground at Coos Bay on Feb. 4, and a week later  
was set on fire with plastic explosives and napalm in an attempt to 
keep most of the 400,000 gallons of fuel from leaking out. 
</P>
<P>
	But a spectacular explosion and fire succeeded in burning away  
only about half the oil on board, and the ship split in two, 
streaking the beaches with 70,000 gallons of sticky black goo. Some 
50 birds have died from oil. 
</P>
<P>
	After abandoning an effort to pump the remaining oil out, the  
tug Sea Victory began towing the bow 200 miles out to sea, where it 
was to be sunk with gunfire in deep water. But a storm snapped the 
tow cable and the bow section was on its own. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Waldport, a fishing town of 1,750 about 100 miles  
southwest of Portland, woke up to find the ship squatting just 
offshore from their back yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came in this morning and saw it sitting there, for a  
minute I wondered if I've been watching too much TV,'' said Darle 
Marquardt, manager of an auto parts store. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours of the wreck's arrival, sticky tar balls began  
showing up on the beach. Authorities said it appeared to be residue 
and tanks holding up to 130,000 gallons of heavy bunker fuel were 
not leaking. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers in yellow rain slickers fanned out near the wreck with  
shovels to scoop up the tar balls, and booms were set up to protect 
the fragile estuary around nearby Alsea Bay. Several birds and sea 
lions or seals were coated with oil, but no dead animals had been 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	State agriculture officials warned against harvesting mussels or  
clams along a 7-mile stretch of beach surrounding Alsea Bay because 
of possible contamination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:56:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 191 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied hard today after two days of weak  
performance, boosted by benign economic data, strong retail sales 
reports and higher oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 191.52 at 9,467.40, near the day's high. The 
blue-chip index more than erased the 48-point loss over the 
previous two sessions and ended above 9,400 for the first time in 
more than a week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 18.96 to 1,246.66, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 27.72 to 2,292.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,723 up, 1,195 down and 611 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 768.79 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
745.22 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 8.20 to 590.75, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.07 to 698.52. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.08 to 394.03.  
</P>
<P>
	The market's recovery, which extended a turnaround in technology  
shares that started late Wednesday, was ``totally justified'' by 
recent economic data and the fact that investors still have a lot 
of money to put to work, said Thomas McManus, portfolio strategist 
at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Once prices get low enough, ``people find out that there's some  
strong underlying demand,'' McManus said. ``After all, there's lots 
of cash in money-market mutual funds, and so there is a lot of 
liquidity, and earnings growth is improving, the manufacturing 
economy is improving, and it doesn't look like (Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan) Greenspan has indicated that he plans to let 
inflation run away any time in the next few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The market opened stronger after IBM announced that it had  
agreed to supply Dell Computer with computer parts in a $16 
billion, seven-year pact. Analysts said the arrangement could lead 
to more highly lucrative deals for IBM, whose stock was up 4 3/8 at 
171 1/8 at the close. Dell was up 7/8 at 81 13/16 in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil and oil-service stocks rose for the second day in a row,  
after oil prices pushed above $13.25 a barrel, following reports of 
dwindling oil supplies and a temporary interruption of pumping in 
Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow component Exxon was up 2 1/8 at 67 13/16. Schlumberger was up  
3 1/4 at 55. Crude oil for April delivery was trading at $12.93 a 
barrel late in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	And financial-services stocks rose as bond prices were stable  
after giving ground on Wednesday. The benchmark 30-year Treasury 
bond was about unchanged, yielding 5.69 percent. American Express 
was up 5 3/16 at 113. Salomon Smith Barney started coverage of the 
stock with a ``buy'' rating. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market was quiet following a 10 a.m. Commerce  
Department report that new orders for U.S. factory goods rose 1.7 
percent in January to a $349.6 billion annual rate. While that was 
a record high, it was still a little under economists' expectations 
and as such, didn't raise fears of inflation in the bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	The price advances stalled on profit-taking in mid-afternoon,  
but resumed climbing in the final hour. Edward Laux, the head 
trader of listed stocks at ABN/Amro First Chicago, attributed the 
pull-back to nervousness ahead of Friday's release of February 
unemployment data. ``A lot of people thought there would be a 
reasonable spate of profit-taking in front of the unemployment 
number,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many analysts believe the nation's unemployment rate will hold  
at its current 4.3 percent, a 29-year low. But a decline in the 
jobless rate, or a growth in the payroll census more than the 
anticipated 250,000 to 300,000, could spark a sharp sell-off in 
bonds and stocks, Laux said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, retail stocks also moved higher amid strong February  
sales figures. Wal-Mart, whose February sales rose 10.3 percent at 
stores open at least a year, was up 2 at 89 3/8. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
