<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tripp Demands Apology From Moran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Linda Tripp demanded an apology Thursday from  
a congressman who questioned why she is being allowed to return to 
a $94,098-a-year ``makeshift job'' at the Defense Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Rep. Jim Moran's comments ``inaccurate, offensive ...  
unseemly,'' Mrs. Tripp's spokesman said she risked her career by 
telling prosecutor Kenneth Starr that Monica Lewinsky was 
pressuring her to commit perjury in the Paula Jones sexual 
harassment lawsuit against President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	At a hearing Wednesday, Moran told Defense Secretary William  
Cohen that ``one particular employee, who has been paid ... to do 
nothing ... spent much of her year listening to some stupid 
adolescent talk about her sex life. So you've rehired her in some 
makeshift job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton had cut many area civilian defense jobs in the name of  
government streamlining, noted Moran, D-Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Tripp has had a distinguished 19-year government career  
and, like all federal employees, she had a legal obligation to 
report knowledge of possible crimes,'' said her spokesman, Philip 
Coughter. ``At a staggering personal cost, she fulfilled that 
obligation. ... She awaits the congressman's apology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon instructed Mrs. Tripp to work from home for the  
past year. She was brought back to work Wednesday as a public 
affairs specialist at the Defense Department's Manpower Data Center 
in Rosslyn, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	She was director of the Joint Civilian Orientation Conference at  
the Pentagon when she triggered the investigation of the 
president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky by giving Starr's office 
her taped phone calls with the young woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Testifying before the House Appropriations defense subcommittee  
on Clinton's fiscal 2000 defense budget, Cohen indicated he would 
respond in writing to Moran, who represents the northern Virginia 
suburbs of Washington, where many Pentagon workers live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
