<DOCNO> APW19990304.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:31:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico Doesn't Get Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Puerto Ricans who got a rerun of a  
Ted Koppel special instead of an interview with Monica Lewinsky 
were seething Thursday, claiming the blackout was an example of 
their second-class status as U.S. citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky's interview with Barbara Walters was billed in  
full-page newspaper advertisements by the local cable TV firm. But 
a terse message Wednesday night announced a blackout due to 
unspecified restrictions, and the special on crime and punishment 
was aired instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a boycott of the Puerto Rican people! As American  
citizens we have the right to know Monica Lewinsky's version,'' 
saleswoman Maribel Rodriguez, 38, complained on a local radio talk 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lack of respect!'' fumed Hermes Ayala, a 24-year-old  
student. 
</P>
<P>
	The blackout actually stemmed from contract issues, but that did  
little to calm many Puerto Ricans. 
</P>
<P>
	The island's 3.8 million residents are U.S. citizens and serve  
in the military, but they don't pay federal taxes, can't vote for 
U.S. president and have no vote in Congress -- an arrangement many 
view as colonial. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the idea of petitioning Congress to become the 51st state  
has been repeatedly rejected, most recently in December. Many 
Puerto Ricans fear statehood would dilute their Hispanic culture. 
</P>
<P>
	All the local stations broadcast in Spanish, and none are U.S.  
network affiliates. But U.S. networks, including Walters' ABC, are 
available through cable TV outlets that receive signals beamed to a 
satellite from mainland network affiliates. With ABC, that is 
Nashville, Tenn.'s WKRN-TV, received via an intermediary, New York 
City-based Prime Time 24. 
</P>
<P>
	WKRN general manager Mike Sechrist said ABC told the station not  
to beam the interview to satellite -- and thus to Puerto Rico -- 
because of ``the deal they did with the Lewinsky people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter sent Thursday to Cable TV of Greater San Juan, Prime  
Time 24 marketing director Denise Haertel wrote that the company 
had ``worked until late in the evening'' in a failed bid to 
convince ABC not to pull the program off satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Satellite Business News, a newsletter of the satellite industry,  
wrote Thursday that almost a million satellite viewers in the U.S. 
mainland also were affected and charged that the move was ABC's 
``most aggressive participation in the broadcasting industry's 
campaign against the satellite industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ABC spokeswoman Eileen Murphy told The Associated Press that  
ABC had no choice in the matter because it only had rights to 
distribute the interview in North America. Allowing it to go on the 
satellite might have meant that non-qualifying areas would have 
also received it. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Murphy admitted she had not even been aware  
``that any cable outlet in Puerto Rico is entitled to our 
programming.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
