<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Ends 191.52 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied today, boosted by benign economic  
data, strong retail sales reports and higher oil prices. The Dow 
Jones industrials ended up 191.52 points at 9,467.40. NYSE 
advancers led decliners 1,717-1,187 The Nasdaq ended at 2,293.04 
points, up 27.84. The Dow was led higher by IBM, which was up 4 3/8 at 
171 1/8 at the close, after soaring as much as 10 1/4 to 177. The 
computer giant agreed to provide Dell Computer with parts in a 
seven-year contract worth $16 billion. Dell's shares were up at 
close 7/8 at 81 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Marine Pilot Acquitted in Crash  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury acquitted a Marine  
pilot today of all charges that he recklessly flew his jet into an 
Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 people more than a year ago. 
The verdict sparked a whoop in the courtroom at the Camp Lejeune 
Marine base, and outrage from Italian officials. Capt. Richard 
Ashby, 31, was charged with 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter 
among other things. The crash and its aftermath strained relations 
between the United States and Italy, a NATO ally. 

</P>
<P>
	Italians Decry Marine Acquittal  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italians were stunned and indignant today at the  
acquittal of a Marine pilot whose jet severed a cable, sending a 
gondola packed with 20 people to their deaths in the Italian Alps. 
``I am really baffled by this ruling,'' said Italian Premier 
Massimo D'Alema through a translator while visiting the John F. 
Kennedy Museum in Boston. ``With that kind of a massacre, with so 
many causalities, I think it is a duty to ensure ... that justice 
is done.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Retired Justice Harry Blackmun Dies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The retired Supreme Court Justice who authored  
the 1973 Roe versus Wade decision that legalized abortion has died. 
Justice Harry Blackmun was 90. Blackmun served 24 years on the 
nation's highest court after being appointed in 1970 by President 
Richard Nixon. He retired in 1994. The lifelong Republican was 
considered a staunch conservative in his early days on the court, 
but by the time he retired he was considered its most liberal 
justice. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Reduces Noriega's Sentence  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega had his  
sentenced reduced by a U.S. judge today, meaning he could eligible 
for parole by 2007. Noriega's sentence was cut from 40 years to 30 
years. Noriega had asked U.S. Judge William M. Hoeveler in December 
to reduce the sentence for money laundering and drug trafficking to 
no more than 15 years. The judge said he considered the nature of 
Noriega's confinement and the ``disparity between the defendant's 
sentence and the sentences served by his co-conspirators'' -- some 
of whom are out of prison. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole To Push for Kosovo Peace  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. Bob Dole says he will urge ethnic  
Albanians in Kosovo to sign a proposed peace agreement as soon as 
possible because further delays can only benefit Serb leader 
Slobodan Milosevic. Dole plans talks with a variety of Kosovo 
Albanians tomorrow in Kosovo as an emissary of President Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T: We Don't Want To Buy AOL  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. doesn't want to acquire the  
nation's largest Internet provider, America Online, despite 
persistent rumors about such a deal, AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael 
Armstrong said today. ``We are absolutely not interested in, nor 
are we pursuing acquiring America Online,'' Armstrong said. 

</P>
<P>
	Blood Pressure, Senility Linked  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Treating high blood pressure in middle age can  
lower the risk of small, ``silent'' strokes that cause senility in 
later years, researchers say. Among 414 men studied from middle age 
into their 70s, even moderately high blood pressure -- and to a 
lesser extent, smoking, drinking and diabetes -- were linked to 
faster aging of the brain. ``If you have risk factors and don't 
treat them, your brain will be a decade older when you hit 70,'' 
said lead author Dr. Charles DeCarli, director of the Alzheimer's 
Disease Center at the University of Kansas. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 3 Connecticut 57, Seton Hall 56  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kevin Freeman scored 22 points, including a  
tip-in with 1:27 left that gave top-seeded Connecticut the lead for 
good today, and the Huskies held on for a 57-56 victory over Seton 
Hall in the quarterfinals of the Big East tournament. Connecticut 
(26-2), ranked third in the nation, advanced to tomorrow's 
semifinals against the winner of the quarterfinal between 
fourth-seeded Syracuse and fifth-seeded Villanova. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
</TEXT>
