<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Owners Postpone Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Baseball commissioner Bud Selig on  
Thursday canceled the owners' meeting scheduled for March 16-18, 
delaying consideration of the proposed sale of the Kansas City 
Royals until at least June. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig's decision had been expected because baseball's lawyers  
have not completed their investigation of Miles Prentice's group, 
which in November agreed to buy the team for $75 million. No other 
major issues needed a decision, so Selig called off the meeting, 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked for them to approve it the day we submitted  
it,'' Prentice said. ``I'm disappointed in the sense we haven't 
been approved, but I understand the nature of the process. I have 
to continue to be patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most baseball sales, especially those involving partnerships  
with a large number of limited partners, take six to nine months 
for approval once an agreement has been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the death of founding owner Ewing Kauffman's death, the  
Royals have been run by a board of directors led by Wal-Mart 
executive David Glass. Kansas City hasn't finished first since 
winning the World Series in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice's group includes such local celebrities as golf pro Tom  
Watson and millionaire banker R. Crosby Kemper Jr. and has more 
than 40 investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Logistically it just presents more information they have to  
review,'' Prentice said. ``The size of the group will ultimately be 
its strength.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
