<DOCNO> APW19990304.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:36:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Pilots Describe Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's not just the high pay offered by airlines  
that is coaxing pilots to leave the armed services, a group of 
disillusioned military pilots told a congressional hearing 
Thursday. Also to blame, they said, are the military's poor working 
conditions, constant deployments overseas, broken equipment and 
routines hard on family life. 
</P>
<P>
	``No amount of bonus money would keep me on active duty,''  
Marine Capt. James P. Clay told a House Armed Services 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The retiring Harrier jet pilot based at the Cherry Point Marine  
Corps Air Station in North Carolina cited ``low morale and low 
flight hours.'' He said it was ``not uncommon to see days when 50 
percent of the aircraft are not ready for flight.'' He said he gets 
barely 10 hours of flight time per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Navy Lt. Cmdr. Leon W. Smith, who flies E-2C radar planes from  
Norfolk, Va., testified he's leaving in April after 14 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hangar I've spent most of 11 years working out of -- it's  
pathetic: rats, mice, lead paint, asbestos, no air conditioning,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee on military personnel is studying the  
Pentagon's pilot retention problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy says it was 1,153 pilots short of its 7,712 positions  
last year, a 15 percent shortfall. The Army was down 113 pilots, 
about 11 percent of its 1,059 requirement. And the Air Force 
reported a shortage of 648 pilots, almost 5 percent of its 13,986 
requirement. The Marine Corps said it had no shortage. 
</P>
<P>
	``In simple terms, for every two pilots that walk in, three walk  
out,'' said Lt. Gen. Donald Peterson, Air Force deputy chief of 
staff. The Air Force ended last year 648 pilots short, a shortage 
that could grow to 2,000 in three years, he said. He cited the 
abundance of civilian jobs and ``robust airline hiring'' as leading 
culprits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department contends that every time a veteran pilot  
walks out the door, it costs taxpayers $5.9 million in lost 
training time and experience. 
</P>
<P>
	But subcommittee Chairman Steve Buyer, R-Ind., said the military  
will never be able to compete with the airlines in terms of salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pilot retention is not just about money,'' he said. ``Pilots  
are leaving the military for the same varied and complex reasons 
that all the other people, both enlistee and officer, are leaving 
the military.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials said pay and benefit increases proposed by  
President Clinton, and an even more generous package approved by 
the Senate, would help some. Even so, they predicted the situation 
would get worse before it gets better. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its grumbling, the Pentagon itself could do a better job  
in keeping its pilots, Christopher Jehn of the Congressional Budget 
Office told the subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm completely puzzled,'' Jehn said. ``The services claim they  
are in the midst of a crisis, but aren't using bonuses to the 
maximum.'' For instance, he said the services can pay pilots up to 
$25,000 per year of experience in special annual bonuses, but the 
Air Force pays only up to $22,000, the Navy up to $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A CBO study of the pilot shortage concluded it ``may not be as  
large or as daunting as some observers have suggested,'' Jehn said. 
He said the services are counting as shortages many desk-job 
positions held by pilots who do not fly. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Chief Warrant Officer Kenneth Engasser Jr., an Apache  
helicopter pilot stationed at Hunter Army Airfield in Savannah, 
Ga., cited long tours in South Korea, Germany, Bosnia and Kuwait. 
He recalled desert stays in tents with 140-degree temperatures 
while ``Air Force pilots live in air conditioning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Navy Lt. Louis J. Schager, an F-14 jet fighter pilot based at  
the Oceana Naval Air Station in Virginia Beach, Va., described 
himself as ``in the minority of late'' because he was staying in 
the service despite the long tours, aging aircraft and dwindling 
parts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most aviators will do their jobs for less compensation, but  
they won't do their jobs for less parts,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
