<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Gov. Sounds Off On Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman gave harsh  
grades Wednesday to both parties in Congress, President Clinton, 
feminist groups and the media for a year of scandal that left 
voters apathetic and annoyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The citizens of our nation have been turned off by the events  
of the past 16 months,'' Whitman told a National Press Club 
luncheon. ``They feel that Washington is out of touch with them and 
out of touch with what really matters to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a controversy from her own state capital followed Whitman  
down to Washington. Of 24 questions submitted by members of the 
luncheon audience, four were related to diversity within and 
alleged racial ``profiling'' by New Jersey's State Police. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman this week fired State Police Superintendent Carl  
Williams over his comments that minorities were more likely than 
others to be involved in trafficking of some drugs. She told the 
press club gathering that Williams is not a racist but that his 
remarks showed ``a level of insensitivity that was not what we 
need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assessing blame for public fatigue with the impeachment process,  
Whitman said, ``I think I have to start with my own party, the 
Republican Party. Republicans emerged with a popular image rivaling 
that of Kathy Bates in Stephen King's 'Misery' -- a perception that 
we are mean-spirited, vindictive and obsessed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the governor also criticized Democrats for rallying behind  
Clinton while using words like ``indefensible'' to describe his 
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman said ``media saturation of the story wore on the  
public's interest and patience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And she accused feminist leaders who continued to support  
Clinton of sending a message ``that if you do good things for women 
as a group, it doesn't really matter what you do to them 
individually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her biggest applause line of the day followed a question about  
the difference between Democrats and Republicans now that Clinton 
has adopted so many trademark GOP issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference, she said, is: ``We believe in them.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
