<DOCNO> APW19990304.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:28:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> People Magazine Has 25th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When People magazine first hit newsstands 25  
years ago, it was easy reading, a who-did-what-when -- and pssst, 
with whom -- in a gossipy whisper far from Page One news. 
</P>
<P>
	But the whisper grew louder, leaving its roots in a ``people''  
page in the back of Time magazine to become Time Inc.'s No. 1 
publication, and paving the way for today's personality-crazed 
media. 
</P>
<P>
	The success of the weekly and its formula are clear in this  
week's 340-page anniversary issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``The media have become addicted to soap opera stories,'' said  
Howard Kurtz, media critic for The Washington Post. ``And you can 
see a People-style approach in almost every corner of the media 
marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What People launched in 1974 with Mia Farrow on the cover was  
the cult of personality, whether famous or obscure, as the ultimate 
audience seducer. Since then, that concept has increasingly powered 
mainstream news. 
</P>
<P>
	``More and more papers are going for gossip, for the celebrity  
of the moment,'' said Gene Roberts, managing editor of The New York 
Times until last year and former executive editor of The 
Philadelphia Inquirer. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line: It pays.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's huge money,'' said People managing editor Carol Wallace.  
</P>
<P>
	Each week, Time Inc. sells 3.6 million copies of People. Every  
page of advertising costs at least $138,000, leading the industry 
with about $626 million in ads last year alone. The magazine rakes 
in $1 billion in revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's more than money, Wallace said: ``At the same time,  
it's not a bad thing to entertain while showing readers what makes 
people in the news tick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The formula shows up in magazines, newspapers and television  
awash in instant fame, spun with embarrassing details that the most 
staid society can't resist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington used to be considered hopelessly boring by the  
likes of People magazine,'' said Kurtz, who in his book ``Spin 
Cycle'' analyzes President Clinton's press machine. ``But in the 
era of Bill and Monica, Paula and James Carville, it's clear that 
the Beltway culture has also been bitten by the celebrity bug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even The New York Times, which sets the country's serious news  
agenda for many, is flirting with the who's-who concept with a 
chatty weekday column, ``Public Lives,'' and a daily arts section 
box, ``Footlights,'' which highlights big names around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	But the difference between People and the Times ``is like the  
view from two different planets. Most Times stories are built 
around people who are substantive, and you see real depth there,'' 
said Roberts, the former managing editor who now teaches journalism 
at the University of Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	The editors of People are proud of reaching a mass audience with  
its common touch. ``I love the audience we reach. They want to see 
a celebrity in a bubble bath, or Sophia Loren and a pizza in the 
kitchen,'' Wallace said. 
</P>
<P>
	The typical People reader is a 40-year-old woman with an annual  
income of about $50,000, who leans toward stories about glamorous 
women. Princess Diana was the favorite, with 50 covers; the issue 
on her death was People's best-selling edition at more than 5 
million copies. Elizabeth Taylor was second with 14 and Jacqueline 
Kennedy Onassis had 13. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not all celebrity fluff. The most beautiful, sexiest and  
best-dressed people share a world with the worst-dressed, the dead 
and the dying. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine, Wallace said, has ``put a face'' on disturbing  
issues like eating disorders and AIDS, with personalities such as 
the late singer Karen Carpenter, who died of anorexia, and an 
ordinary, HIV-positive little boy, Ryan White. ``And even beautiful 
princesses like Diana can get bulimia,'' Wallace said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:52:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panthers' Bure Tears Knee Cartilage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- Pavel Bure's season took another detour  
Thursday when the Florida Panthers found torn cartilage in his 
right knee that will sideline him at least two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Magnetic resonance imaging tests found a torn meniscus in the  
knee, along with a bone bruise. He was scheduled to undergo surgery 
on Friday to repair the damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Bure is expected out of action from two to three weeks, Panthers  
officials said. That would leave less than a month in the regular 
season, as Florida seeks the final Eastern Conference playoff spot. 
Heading into Friday, the Panthers had 60 points and were in a tight 
race with Montreal, Boston and the New York Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury took place when Bure was bent backward by an open-ice  
check from Colorado's Adam Foote in the first period of Florida's 
7-5 loss Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-scoring Russian continued to play and scored three  
goals in the first two periods as Florida jumped to a 5-0 lead. But 
he sat out the third as the Avalanche roared back with seven 
unanswered goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was getting worse and worse in the second (period),'' Bure  
said after the game. ``With about five minutes to go in the second, 
there was just so much more pain. The doctors said it was not safe 
to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The injury happened to the same knee he strained in a Feb. 5  
</P>
<P>
	game at Pittsburgh, causing him to sit out eight games. His  
return lasted just four games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts, there's no doubt,'' Panthers coach Terry Murray  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bure's hat trick Wednesday night was his second since the  
Panthers acquired him from Vancouver in a seven-player trade Jan. 
17. Bure was a holdout for the season's first three months after 
demanding a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite playing just 11 games this season, Bure's 13 goals ranks  
fifth on the Panthers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
