<DOCNO> APW19990304.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ramon Martinez May Report by Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Ramon Martinez may report to the Boston  
Red Sox training camp by Monday once final details of a two-year 
deal are worked out, general manager Dan Duquette said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, recovering from shoulder surgery after spending the  
past 11 seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers, said Wednesday he had 
agreed to a contract that would reunite him with his brother Pedro. 
</P>
<P>
	They pitched together with the Dodgers in 1993 when Pedro was a  
rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're working on finalizing the details of bringing him to  
Boston. We're not quite there yet,'' Duquette said before Boston 
opened its exhibition season with a 9-2 win over the Minnesota 
Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez still has to pass a physical, ``one of the key hurdles  
in an agreement of this type,'' Duquette said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was hopeful that Martinez, who has been working out  
in the Dominican Republic, would join the club Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to see him in here so we can assess exactly where he  
is in the program,'' Duquette said. It's possible Martinez then 
would return to the Dominican Republic to continue his 
rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez said Wednesday he thought he might be ready to pitch in  
the majors before the All-Star break. He underwent rotator cuff 
surgery on his right shoulder last June 30, and Duquette said the 
usual recovery time is 12 to 14 months before a pitcher can play in 
a major-league game. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he comes around like we hope he will he can have an  
impact,'' Duquette said. ``He's a good leader, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox second baseman Jose Offerman, who played with Martinez  
in Los Angeles from 1990-95, was pleased with the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good feeling because we've been together in the past.  
Ramon is a good man and a good teammate,'' Offerman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, 30, was 7-3 with a 2.83 ERA in 15 starts last season  
before he was hurt and the Dodgers bought out his option for 1999. 
He had spent his entire career with the Dodgers, posting a 123-77 
record and a 3.45 ERA. In the past five seasons, he was 61-28. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Martinez was 19-7 with a 2.89 ERA last season, his first  
with the Red Sox. In 1997, he won the NL Cy Young award with 
Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Duquette said he still would be interested in adding another top  
starter. He reportedly has shown interest in Kansas City's Kevin 
Appier. That would add even more experience to a veteran rotation 
that includes Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, Tim Wakefield, Mark 
Portugal and Pat Rapp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't worry about that,'' Wakefield said of Ramon Martinez's  
impending arrival. ``I've got to worry about getting guys out on 
the field every five days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just keep working hard,'' Rapp said. ``When he (Ramon  
Martinez) is ready, he'll do what he can do. I can only control me. 
I can't control what happens around me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Against Minnesota, Wakefield pitched one inning, retiring the  
side in order in the first on nine pitches. Rapp pitched the next 
two innings, allowing one run on two hits with one strikeout and a 
hit batter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
