<HEADLINE> Microsoft Gets Into E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Microsoft Corp., hoping to reverse its  
image as a laggard in the world of electronic commerce, rolled out 
a major package of Internet services and software for online 
shoppers and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft announced Thursday it would improve its msn.com Web  
destination to make it easier for shoppers to find products they 
want to buy and compare prices over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Online shoppers will be able to use an electronic ``wallet''  
that includes credit card numbers, passwords and mailing addresses, 
so they don't have to re-enter the information again and again. 
</P>
<P>
	For businesses, Microsoft offered new software, called BizTalk,  
they can use to sell products online. The software will help 
businesses track supply and demand, execute orders quickly and 
accurately and communicate with vendors. The system is already 
being tested by 1-800-FLOWERS, barnesandnoble.com, Best Buy Co., 
Dell Computer Corp. and Eddie Bauer Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``To get more than a million new businesses into e-commerce, we  
need to help their software speak the language of business in a 
consistent way,'' Microsoft chairman Bill Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was intended to expand Microsoft's existing  
e-commerce efforts, which include MSN Expedia for travel services, 
MSN Carpoint for auto sales and MSN HomeAdvisor for real estate 
listings. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether the new initiatives would improve  
Microsoft's position in the growing world of electronic commerce. 
Several Microsoft rivals such as IBM and Sun Microsystems have 
already staked major claims in selling e-commerce software, an 
attempt to grab a piece of consumers' estimated $12 billion in 
Internet purchases this year, expected to increase tenfold within a 
few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are talking about e-commerce, Microsoft isn't the  
company that comes to mind,'' said Gartner Group analyst Scott 
Winkler. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
