<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Is One To Beat in Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Maybe this event should be renamed in honor  
of Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA Indoor Track and Field Championships begin Friday, and  
the Razorbacks have ruled it unlike any other team in NCAA history, 
winning 14 of the last 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Coached by John McDonnell, Arkansas has won 14 indoor and eight  
outdoor NCAA titles in addition to nine cross country championships 
since 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the women in the two-day event at the RCA Dome, top-ranked  
Texas will be seeking its second consecutive title after ending 
LSU's five-year reign here last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Division II meet will be run concurrently with the  
perennially powerful Abilene Christian Wildcats defending both the 
men's and women's titles. 
</P>
<P>
	The men are going for their fourth consecutive championship and  
sixth in seven years, while the women have won six straight and 10 
of the last 11 indoor championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, the runner-up to Arkansas last year, is again the top  
challenger to the Razorbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stanford will be very tough,'' McDonnell said. ``They are  
doubling and tripling guys. We're not going to do much of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonnell's team features sophomore Kenny Evans, who won the  
high jump championship as a freshman last year by clearing 7 feet, 
6 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Arkansas distance runners are potential champions -- Seneca  
Lassiter (mile), Michael Power (3,000) and Sean Kaley (5,000). To 
give them a better chance at individual victories, McDonnell isn't 
going with what would likely be his best chance for victory in the 
distance medley. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be too tough on them,'' he said of Lassiter and  
Power. ``Sharif Karie and Murray Link have come around. They'll run 
the distance medley with Ryan Stanley and James Karanu. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still a good team but we could have put an awesome team  
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaley, who finished second in the 5,000 last year, will also  
compete in the 3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a tough double but he wants to do it. This is it for  
him. This is Sean's last event as a Razorback. He wants to go out 
strong,'' McDonnell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lassiter faces a major challenge in the mile from a pair of  
Stanford runners -- junior Michael Stember and sophomore Jonathan 
Riley. Both have seed times of under four minutes. And Kaley can 
expect to find any of three Stanford juniors -- Brad and Brent 
Hauser, along with Jason Balkman -- on his heels in the 5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas women have three defending champions returning from a  
team that won the championship by a record 30-point margin last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Suziann Reid is the defending 400-meter champion and her time of  
51.58 is the fastest in the event in college this year. Defending 
high jump champion Eric Aldrich ranks first nationally with a 6-4 3/4 
performance this year and LaKeisha Backus is the defending champion 
in the 200. 
</P>
<P>
	A teammate may deprive Backus of repeat laurels. Nanceen Perry  
won the 200 in the 1997 championships and her fast time of 23.34 
ranks second nationally this year. LSU's Peta-Gaye Dowdie is 
another title contender in the event, having won the SEC 
championship with a nation-leading time of 22.99. 
</P>
</TEXT>
