</P>
<P>
	IBM-Dell Pact Boosts Wall Street  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The market opened stronger today after IBM  
announced that it had agreed to supply Dell Computer with computer 
parts in a $16 billion, seven-year pact. Analysts said the 
arrangement could lead to more highly lucrative deals for IBM, 
whose stock was up 4 3/8 at 171 1/8 at the close. Dell was up 7/8 at 81 
13/16 in Nasdaq trading. Oil and oil-service stocks rose for the 
second day in a row. Dow component Exxon was up 2 1/8 at 67 13/16. 
Schlumberger was up 3 1/4 at 55. Financial-services stocks rose as 
bond prices were stable after giving ground yesterday. American 
Express was up 5 3/16 at 113. Salomon Smith Barney started coverage 
of the stock with a ``buy'' rating. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. Retail Sales Beat Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at the nation's biggest retailers topped  
expectations in February as the U.S. economy remained strong. Not 
only were consumers buying up discounted winter merchandise, there 
was also great demand for full-priced spring goods as well. The 
healthy results pleased merchants who had anticipated that 
consumers would scale back their spending in 1999 amid expectations 
that global financial turmoil would slow down U.S. economic growth. 
The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer of 
sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was up 
4.5 percent in February. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Rise 1.7 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New orders to U.S. factories surged in January  
for the second consecutive month, perhaps signaling the start of a 
rebound in American manufacturing after a year of struggling with 
fallout from Asia's economic crisis. Orders increased 1.7 percent 
to a seasonally adjusted $349.6 billion following an even stronger 
2.3 percent increase in December, the Commerce Department said 
today. Meanwhile, the Labor Department reported that the number of 
Americans filing first-time applications for unemployment benefits 
fell last week and, for February, the average level of new 
applications reached a 10-year low. Jobless claims totaled a 
seasonally adjusted 286,000 last week. The department is due to 
report the unemployment rate for February tomorrow. Analysts 
believe it will hold at a 29-year low of 4.3 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Closer To Approving the Pill  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japese health officials confirmed today that a  
government committee has dropped its resistance to the sale of 
birth control pills. The change comes nine years after it took up 
the question -- and five weeks after an uproar over the speedy 
approval of Viagra. The Health Ministry committee studying the 
safety of the pill concluded yesterday that there was no reason to 
withhold approval any longer, although it stopped short of actually 
approving the sale, ministry official Yasuhide Furusawa said. The 
committee, expected to give its OK in June, first wants to write up 
guidelines for doctors and women, including plans to encourage the 
use of condoms to prevent the spread of the AIDS virus, Furusawa 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazil Raises Interest Rates  
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- In his first day on the job,  
Brazil's new central banker Arminio Fraga raised interest rates to 
45 percent today in a controversial effort to stamp out inflation. 
Fraga called the increase in the Central Bank's lending rate for 
commercial banks necessary to keep prices from exploding. ``Our 
main commitment is to (control) inflation,'' Fraga told reporters. 
Prices have risen sharply since January, when Brazil stopped 
spending dollars to prop up its currency. The real has lost about 
43 percent of its value since then, which has made imported goods 
and components more expensive. 

</P>
<P>
	German Industry Fighting Tax Reform  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- The lower house of Germany's legislature  
passed a bill overhauling the country's tax system, increasing the 
burden on industry to allow relief for average-income families. 
Bitterly attacked by the conservative opposition and industry, the 
bill passed on the strength of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's 
center-left majority by 312-251 votes, with 27 abstentions. The law 
includes cuts in personal income and corporate tax rates, but also 
scraps a string of corporate tax exemptions. 

</P>
<P>
	Europe Keeps Interest Rates Steady  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Europe's central bank left its  
benchmark interest rate unchanged at 3 percent today despite new 
signs of trouble in Germany's economy, the largest in the region. 
Concerns about worsening the euro's slide against the dollar, as 
well as the European Central Bank's determination not to be seen as 
giving in to political pressure, all argued against the bank 
lowering rates for the 11-nation bloc that uses the new currency. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 8,000 to 286,000  
</P>
<P>
	Factory orders: up 1.7 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales: up 4.5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Unemployment  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Consumer credit  

