<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meares Getting Acclimated With NL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- They congregate every morning in a corner  
of the Pittsburgh Pirates' clubhouse -- telling stories, talking 
ball, remembering how it was in their former baseball life in the 
American League. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's a coincidence the lockers of Pat Meares, Brian Giles  
and Ed Sprague are crowded together in a pocket of the clubhouse 
known as AL Alley, but more likely it's not. 
</P>
<P>
	The three players didn't know many others in their new club and  
their new league, but at least they knew each other. And a friendly 
face beats an unfamiliar one anytime in the transient lifestyle of 
a major league player. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an adjustment for everyone,'' said Meares, the shortstop  
who rejected an $11 million, three-year contract offer from 
Minnesota only to sign a $1.5 million, one-year deal with 
Pittsburgh. ``I've got to admit, the Pirates' uniform did look 
strange the first day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially since Meares had worn the Minnesota Twins' blue and  
red for 8 1/2 years and planned to wear it a lot longer until an 
unusual contract dispute led his longtime team to effectively 
release him. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little strange,'' Meares said.  
</P>
<P>
	Meares, who drove in a career-high 70 runs last season, was  
offered the multiyear deal last fall even as the Twins prepared to 
pare their payroll from $24 million to $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But Meares' agent, Steve Comte, thought the shortstop was worth  
more on the open market and they rejected the offer. The Twins 
subsequently pulled it off the table and, rather than go to salary 
arbitration, declined to offer a 1999 contract. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Dec. 20, five days before Christmas. Rather than being a  
millionaire, Meares found himself unemployed and, with most teams' 
offseason moves mostly completed, without many options. 
</P>
<P>
	``I signed with Minnesota in 1990, I was with them for 8 1/2 years,  
so it's difficult going through something like that,'' Meares said. 
``It was tough on my wife and family because they liked 
Minneapolis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The situation was unusual because teams rarely give up on  
productive players such as Meares without receiving any 
compensation. He had career highs in RBIs (70) and hits (141) last 
season and is a .260 career hitter and reliable if not Gold 
Glove-level fielder. 
</P>
<P>
	Unexpectedly finding himself on the open market, Meares sought a  
multi-year contract but wasn't offered one. 
</P>
<P>
	He waited a week after the Pirates offered him a  
take-it-or-leave-it $1.5 million offer before deciding to take it. 
His only other options were as a backup in Cincinnati and Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``We decided to be patient, and I'm glad I did because that  
approach resulted in us adding a quality major league shortstop,'' 
Pirates general manager Cam Bonifay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares is more comfortable with the move now, especially since  
Pittsburgh has begun increasing its payroll just as Minnesota is 
cutting salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way I was looking at things, Minnesota was going in the  
other direction, and I think this team is on the right track,'' 
Meares said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Meares at shortstop and Mike Benjamin at second base, the  
Pirates have significantly upgraded their up-the-middle defense. 
Shortstop was a comedy of errors and poor offense last season, as 
Lou Collier, Kevin Polcovich and prospect Abraham Nunez combined 
for 45 errors -- or 21 more than Meares. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try to catch the ball and get outs for guys,''  
Meares said. ``Nothing against the guys who were at shortstop last 
year, but I'm going to try to bring some level of consistency to 
the position that wasn't there. ... That's tough on a pitching 
staff to have two or three guys playing shortstop a year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
