<DOCNO> APW19990304.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 23:44:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Book Reveals All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In her new book, Monica Lewinsky goes beyond  
her affair with President Clinton to disclose many details about 
her private life, from an abortion to antidepressants to a stint at 
an eating disorders clinic. Is all that really necessary? And will 
it sell books? 
</P>
<P>
	Booksellers say the 14-month-long presidential sex scandal  
probably raised the bar on how much private information needed to 
be in Ms. Lewinsky's book to attract the public, which seemed to 
tire long ago of the affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Starr Report was more lurid than this book,'' said Bill  
Curry, spokesman for Amazon.com, an online bookselling outfit, 
referring to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress 
about his investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, issued in September and published in book form,  
caused a stir for containing explicit accounts of Ms. Lewinsky's 
sexual encounters with the president. 
</P>
<P>
	The former intern's book does not go into detail about the  
sexual trysts -- ``in terms of sex secrets, there wasn't much 
left,'' says Curry -- but it does give details, some might say 
embarrassing ones, about Ms. Lewinsky's private life, including: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Her stint at an eating disorders clinic when she was a  
teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	-- That she lost her virginity at 19 to a married man whose wife  
was expecting a baby. 
</P>
<P>
	-- That after she found out the man was seeing someone else, who  
was younger, she paid ``him back for his treachery by having a 
fling with his younger brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- An abortion resulting from a three-month fling with a Pentagon  
worker that came in the midst of her relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	-- That she was taking antidepressants.  
</P>
<P>
	Author Andrew Morton, who interviewed Ms. Lewinsky extensively  
over a three-week period and spoke to her family, friends and 
neighbors, said he considered some key issues -- such as the 
abortion and her affair with a married man -- unavoidable because 
they had already been made public. 
</P>
<P>
	He discussed whether to include the abortion with the publisher,  
St. Martin's Press, but did not consult Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I don't put it in and it becomes a big issue, I'll be  
criticized for doing a whitewash,'' he said in an interview 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As for other details of Ms. Lewinsky's private life, Morton said  
he decided to include them to show the events that helped shape 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	Morton said Ms. Lewinsky, who did not have veto power over his  
writing, found some parts ``a bit too candid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in the end, she was happy with it, Morton said.  
</P>
<P>
	``She thinks it's a vivid warts-and-all portrayal of her,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gennifer Flowers, another Clinton paramour turned author, went  
much further than Ms. Lewinsky, giving explicit details of alleged 
sexual encounters with the president in her 1995 book ``Passion and 
Betrayal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When your integrity and honesty are being questioned, you have  
a tendency to go overboard so people think you're an honest 
person,'' said Ms. Flowers, who is working on another book about 
her life. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton denied Flowers' claim that they'd had a 12-year affair  
in Arkansas. Last year he said in a deposition in the Paula Jones 
sexual harassment case that they had sex once. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Ms. Lewinsky's book came out, the public supposedly  
had grown weary of the Clinton scandal and all its tawdry details 
about cigars, a stained dress and ``the definition of sex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the book, ``Monica's Story,'' topped Amazon.com's ``Hot  
100'' list of best-selling books on Thursday, outselling the latest 
volume recommended by Oprah Winfrey's book club and novelist John 
Grisham's new work. 
</P>
<P>
	Just how long the book will remain popular is uncertain, but if  
history is a guide, it may not be long. Curry said sales of other 
Clinton investigation books were driven by news events of the last 
year, such as the impeachment trial. When the news subsided, so did 
interest in the books, he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
