<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pepsi To Debut New Ads at Oscars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pepsi-Cola Co., dumping an advertising theme  
viewed as too limiting for a soft drink company seeking mass 
appeal, plans to launch an ad campaign called ``Joy of Cola'' for 
its flagship brand later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The beverage company from Purchase, N.Y., disclosed Thursday the  
first three commercials in the new campaign will debut March 21 on 
the Academy Awards show on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Aretha Franklin has recorded a new anthem for the soft drink  
maker that will be heard in the ads and will make a cameo 
appearance in one of the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Marlon Brando and entertainer Issac Hayes will narrate the  
other ads although neither man will be shown in the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Child actor Hallie Eisenberg, who has previously appeared for  
Pepsi in an ad in which she adopts an unusually gruff voice when 
she finds Pepsi isn't served at a diner, will appear in all three 
ads. 
</P>
<P>
	In one ad, the little girl appears to sing the new anthem but it  
is Aretha Franklin's voice. Brando's voice is channeled through the 
girl in another ad in which she has been denied a Pepsi, while 
Hayes' voice comes through her when she poses as a disc jockey in 
the third ad. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi officials said the new campaign leverages the company's  
``key equities of humor, humanity and music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new theme replaces ``Generation Next'' which had been  
faulted by Phil Marineau, president of Pepsi-Cola North America, 
for appearing to appeal to only a narrow segment of the audience 
that Pepsi should court. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi-Cola's corporate share of the $56.3 billion U.S. soft  
drink market rose 0.5 percentage point to 31.4 percent last year, 
according to the Beverage Digest/Maxwell report. Coca-Cola Co.'s 
leading share rose 0.6 percentage point to 44.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pepsi-Cola brand's share fell 0.3 percentage points to 14.2  
percent, while industry leader Coca-Cola Classic was flat at 20.8 
percent of the market, the report said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:53:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Agree to Budget Frame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican congressional leaders agreed  
Thursday on a framework for the fiscal 2000 budget that they said 
would prevent Social Security surpluses from being used for tax 
cuts, and would stick to spending limits enacted two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, announced at the end of weeks of private meetings  
among top House and Senate Republicans, would also allow for a tax 
cut that would begin next year, just as the presidential and 
congressional election campaigns are under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Next year's tax reduction would likely be relatively small  
because lawmakers would have to find savings and new revenues to 
pay for them. The cut will probably be about $15 billion next year 
and from $150 billion to $190 billion over the next five years, 
surging to $700 billion to $900 billion over the next decade, said 
Republicans who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal represents the GOP's attempt to frame this year's  
fight with President Clinton over what to do with massive budget 
surpluses expected for the foreseeable future. It also seems to 
spell a truce between House and Senate Republicans, whose bickering 
over cutting taxes last year resulted in Congress' first failure in 
24 years to produce its own budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``The House and Senate have come together, and we think it is  
historic,'' said House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich, 
R-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration quickly moved to the attack.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be looking particularly to see if this plan  
does anything to strengthen the solvency of Social Security and 
Medicare, as the president's plan does,'' said White House 
spokesman Barry Toiv. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has had the field virtually to himself since sending  
Congress a $1.77 trillion budget last month for fiscal 2000, which 
begins Oct. 1. In it, he proposed setting aside most of the 
expected surpluses for buttressing Social Security and Medicare, 
and spending the rest on new federally subsidized personal 
retirement accounts as well as on an array of defense and social 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressional leaders will now take the blueprint to  
rank-and-file Republican lawmakers. Kasich and Senate Budget 
Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who announced the plan 
with Kasich, will now craft budgets that they hope to push through 
their committees later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the plan were sketchy and in some instances not yet  
finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans agreed to try to enact legislation requiring  
that Social Security's annual surpluses -- being amassed to prepare 
for the baby boomers' retirements -- be used to retire government 
debt held by the public. The measure would be aimed at blunting 
Clinton's oft-repeated accusation that the GOP wants to divert 
Social Security funds to pay for tax cuts for the rich. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a Domenici plan, those Social Security surpluses could  
only be spent for other purposes with 60 votes from the 100-member 
Senate. Even so, budget experts say such a mechanism is unlikely to 
guarantee that the money would remain untouched because lawmakers 
eager to get at it could simply vote to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said their plan would let them to set aside $1.8  
trillion over 10 years to reduce the national debt or to use for 
any overhauls enacted of Social Security and Medicare. Citing 
figures by the Congressional Budget Office, they said that was 
about $150 billion more than Clinton would reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, House and Senate Republicans had clashed over how  
much, if any, of the Social Security surpluses to use to finance 
the tax cuts that many in the party consider their hallmark. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute was crucial because the Congressional Budget Office  
expects a 2000 surplus of $133 billion -- coming entirely from 
Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans, worried about Clinton's attacks, were  
insistent that none of the Social Security money be used for tax 
cuts, and they prevailed. House Republicans had argued that they 
needed some of those funds to enact a tax cut in 2000 that people 
would notice. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have already signaled that merely protecting the  
Social Security money, however, will not be enough. They also want 
billions set aside for Medicare, which provides health insurance 
for elderly Americans and is nearly as politically sensitive as 
Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans ``are two-thirds of the way there,'' Senate Minority  
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said earlier of GOP plans to protect 
Social Security funds. ``We think Medicare and Social Security 
ought to be locked up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici, however, said the GOP proposal would ``lock away every  
penny of the Social Security trust fund surpluses for our nation's 
elderly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that, he said, was better than Clinton. He cited a CBO  
analysis released Wednesday that said Clinton would save only 58 
percent of next year's $137 billion Social Security surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's running around saying he's the one saving Social  
Security,'' Domenici said. ``If saving the trust fund and not 
spending it is the test, we're 100 percent pure, and he's 58 
percent pure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said their plan would also live within next year's  
spending limit of roughly $550 billion for discretionary spending. 
That category covers all annually approved defense and domestic 
programs, but excludes automatic benefits such as welfare and 
payments to holders of federal debt. 
</P>
<P>
	And they said they would do so while increasing defense  
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	They did not, however, explain how they would stay within those  
limits, which many Republicans concede will be a major problem. 
Because of inflation, just to have the same programs as this year 
will take cuts of at least $15 billion -- not including increases 
desired by both parties for defense, education and other programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:25:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racial Tensions Tear at N.C. Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.C. (AP) -- For years, racial tensions were expressed  
in glares and overheard whispers in this small town of decaying 
Victorian mansions and brick storefronts. 
</P>
<P>
	But tensions have been running especially high since last week,  
when Trenton's white mayor of 16 years told a reporter that blacks 
are unfit to serve in town government. 
</P>
<P>
	The remark came after a few blacks sued officials of the  
all-white town government in January for not annexing some mostly 
black outlying areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not leaders. A black man would rather work for a  
white person,'' Mayor Joffree Leggett told the Kinston Free Press. 
He went on to say that if three blacks were working together in a 
store, ``within a few years, they'd be stealing from each other and 
they'd be out of business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 81-year-old mayor -- at the urging of the three-member town  
board -- resigned this week. But his words have inflamed the 
community and sparked a monthlong boycott of the white-owned 
businesses that line Jones Street, the main drag in this farming 
center of 200 people on North Carolina's coastal plain. 
</P>
<P>
	The state NAACP has met here, promising to support the lawsuit.  
The lawsuit accuses officials of ignoring requests to annex three 
black neighborhoods of about 100 people for fear that such a move 
would lead to the election of a black to the town board. 
</P>
<P>
	``These people say we can't do nothing because of our color,''  
said community activist Johnson Willis, one of the plaintiffs. 
``The people, they are so afraid of blacks. Try us first before you 
condemn us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Willis, a retired Air Force veteran, said that although the town  
board persuaded the mayor to resign, that does not change the 
political realities in a town where whites have all the power. ``He 
spoke for the board, every word he spoke,'' Willis said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 blacks live in Trenton; only 23 are registered voters.  
A black has never been elected to the town board. 
</P>
<P>
	Trenton hasn't annexed any land since the early 1900s. A 1949  
ordinance still on the books bars ``persons of color and/or persons 
of undesirable character and reputation'' from owning land in 
Trenton. But the ordinance is considered unenforceable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why not give us a voice?'' Willis asked. ``If those people  
were smart, they'd give us one black on the board. Now, they've got 
trouble because of thick-headedness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some in town say Willis is the problem. He has filed more than  
30 lawsuits against his hometown in the past 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's cost us more than $80,000 in legal fees,'' said Charles  
Jones, a town board member and owner of Trenton's only car 
dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said relations between black and white residents -- with  
the exception of Willis -- have been relatively good over the years. 
He also disputed Willis' claim the mayor's remarks reflect the 
board's sentiments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope people with enough sense will realize that this is just  
one old man who made a foolish statement,'' Jones said. ``Right 
now, you've got friends divided with friends. It's just most 
unfortunate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to the mayor's home this week went unanswered. But he has  
said that in his remarks about three blacks working together, he 
was referring to people like Willis. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said the board never received a proper annexation petition  
from the areas. He said he doubts most residents there really want 
annexation. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Willis said he submitted a proper petition a decade  
ago, and ``I'm not jumping through that hoop again. They always 
have some stipulations for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toni Strayhorn, a resident of the largest of the three black  
neighborhoods, Haiti, said the board members are out of touch. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't spoke to any of us,'' she said. ``The town  
council members are presumptuous. Quite frankly, I don't think they 
want to know what we think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse Koonce, another resident of one of the black  
neighborhoods, said the mayor's comments have helped to rally 
people to the cause, and the pressure won't let up until the town 
board incorporates the areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``To push an issue, you've got to get what pressure you can,''  
Koonce said. ``You can't choke a man by grabbing him around the 
waist.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 07:16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mattel Overhauls Executive Suite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mattel Inc. took another step to revive its  
sales and profits with a broad overhaul of its management team, 
including the departure of two of its top executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The shakeup, announced Wednesday, includes the resignation of  
president and chief operating officer Bruce Stein, who analysts say 
may have clashed with chairman and CEO Jill Barad over the 
direction of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Baughman, president of the Fisher-Price preschool division,  
will also leave the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The restructuring comes as Mattel rethinks the way it does  
business. Its profits were under pressure last year, and sales of 
its traditional toys -- like Barbie dolls -- have been sliding. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many of its most important retail customers,  
including giant Toys R Us, drastically cut back their orders and 
asked for delivery of inventory closer to the time that they wanted 
to put the toys on store shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel has been aggressively developing CD-ROMs and other  
high-tech toys to better keep pace with sophisticated interests of 
today's children. It also is exploring new retail channels, like 
the Internet and direct sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new organizational structure we have developed will  
provide for faster decision making, and encourage action that is 
entrepreneurial and responsive to change,'' Barad said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the reorganization, Mattel will be divided into five  
divisions, each headed by a president who will report directly to 
Barad. 
</P>
<P>
	The units will include boys, girls/Barbie, Fisher Price, Mattel  
Media and the Pleasant Company, which makes the American Girl dolls 
as well as focuses on Mattel's direct-to-consumer business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This restructuring is all about cutting costs,'' said Jim  
Silver, who runs The Toy Book, a New York-based trade publication. 
``I think part of the problem Mattel was having is there were too 
many people with the same job. There was too much overlap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts also said the loss of Stein could hurt Mattel. The  
44-year-old is a seasoned toy industry veteran with lengthy 
experience at Mattel, as well as at Sony Interactive Entertainment 
and Hasbro. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought that Bruce Stein was one of those people who was a  
visionary about toys, and really gets where kids are today and what 
they want to play with,'' said Chris Byrne, a toy industry 
consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	While Stein said in a statement that he ``needed a new  
challenge,'' analysts, who spoke on condition of anonymity, 
questioned whether the decision to leave was all his. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
