<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Fund-Raiser Dies in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Alex Haught, the chief fund-raiser for  
Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign in Tennessee, died 
in a car accident. He was 34. 
</P>
<P>
	Haught's car collided with a van Wednesday night, killing Haught  
and injuring two people in the van, which smashed into the front of 
a restaurant, police said. Haught was alone in his car. 
</P>
<P>
	Police issued an arrest warrant Thursday charging Jimmy  
Millican, 42, with vehicular homicide, vehicular assault and 
driving on a revoked license. They said he ran a red light in the 
crash and appeared intoxicated. A blood sample from Millican was 
sent to the state crime lab to determine alcohol content. 
</P>
<P>
	Millican is to be charged after his release from Vanderbilt  
University Medical Center, where he and his passenger were in 
stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Haught took a leave of absence as chief of staff for Rep. Bob  
Clement, D-Tenn., to work on the Gore campaign in the vice 
president's home state. He was working with Johnny Hayes, who 
recently stepped down from the Tennessee Valley Authority's board 
of directors to work as finance director of Gore's national 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Haught previously was finance director for the unsuccessful U.S.  
Senate campaign of Rep. Jim Cooper in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include Haught's parents, Max and Joy Haught, and a  
sister, Melissa Haught, all of Nashville. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
