<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US-EU Banana Trade Hassle Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fancy French handbags, German coffee makers,  
Scottish cashmere sweaters, and millions of dollars of other 
European imports soon could disappear from American store shelves 
as the world's two largest trading partners, the United States and 
the 15-nation European Union, stood on the brink of a trade war 
over bananas. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, EU Trade Comissioner Leon Brittan said today that  
the United States action ``risks a major confrontration,'' hinting 
that the EU would likely retaliate against American goods. But 
Brittan said that any EU retaliation would be ``in accordance'' 
with rules of the World Trade Organization, the global referee of 
trade disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration on Wednesday began notifying U.S.  
improters that they now are liable for hefty tariffs on $520 
million worth of European goods because of the long-running dispute 
involving European barriers on banana imports. 
</P>
<P>
	If allowed to stand, the tariffs of 100 percent effectively  
would double the cost of the targeted European goods, pricing them 
out of the American market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the action of a party seeking a rapid settlement''  
of the banana case, Brittan told reporters. He called the U.S. 
response ``unacceptable and unlawful,'' arguing that the United 
States had no authority to impose the penalty tariffs before 
receiving a go-ahead from a WTO arbitration panel. The WTO earlier 
this week postponed a decision asking both sides to supply more 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is seeking to retaliate against European  
producers by an amount equal to the lost sales claimed by 
U.S.-based banana companies because of European barriers found by 
the WTO to violate global trade rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight over bananas is just one of a number of economic  
tension points between the two trading partners coming at a time 
when America's trade deficit is skyrocketing as the global currency 
crisis pounds American manufacturers and farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States met with a trade delegation from the EU today  
in Washington in an effort to head off possible trade sanctions in 
another long running dispute, Europe's refusal to allow U.S. beef 
treated with growth hormones to be sold in Europe. The U.S. beef 
industry says it is losing $250 million in European sales because 
of the ban, which a WTO panel held was an illegal restraint of 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the food fights, the two trading partners are  
also squabbling over airlines. The House on Wednesday 
overwhelmingly passed a bill threatening to ban Europe's supersonic 
Concorde in retaliation for a ruling that would ban many older 
American jets from landing at European airports. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials emphasized Wednesday that they will not collect  
any punitive tariffs in the banana dispute until the WTO rules on 
the appropriate size of the sanctions. But the did order importers 
of products on the retaliation list to start posting bonds and 
assume liability for the higher tariffs pending the WTO's final 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House today, presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart  
said that the credibility of a rules-based trading system 
supervised by the WTO was at stake in the banana fight. ``The EU 
needs to understand how important it is to let the WTO do its 
work,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States contends that American banana companies are  
losing $520 million annually in lost sales to Europe because of 
illegal trade barriers that favor bananas imported from former 
European colonies in the Caribbean and Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiquita Brands International Inc. and Dole Food Co., the major  
American companies involved, grow their bananas on plantations in 
South America. 
</P>
<P>
	Europeans say politics is driving the United States to the brink  
of a trade war with its biggest trading partner. Carl Lindner, the 
head of Chiquita, is a major campaign contributor to both Democrats 
and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	While the United States won a WTO case on this issue, the EU  
argued that the matter needed further review because it has changed 
some banana import rules. But the United States has rejected the 
changes as failing to remove the objectionable barriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The target list of products, first published last year, includes  
Louis Vuitton plastic handbags from France, sweet biscuits from 
Britain, Parma ham and pecorino cheese from Italy, German coffee 
makers and a host of less fancy imports ranging from plastic 
packing material to batteries. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:54:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Urges Saving Open Spaces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, celebrating the 150th  
birthday of the Interior Department, urged broad support Thursday 
for a $1 billion-a-year program to set aside treasured lands and 
open spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, addressing a packed auditorium at the Interior  
headquarters, recalled a visit 30 years ago to the Grand Canyon 
when he watched the sunset across the canyon's multicolored cliffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got over it,'' said the president, adding that  
protection of such natural resources is at the heart of the 
Interior Department's history of land stewardship. 
</P>
<P>
	The president used the celebration to call on the Republican-led  
Congress to stop ``wasting precious time battling over senseless 
anti-environmental riders ... which I'm going to veto anyway'' and 
join in approving a permanent guarantee of annual funding for 
protecting open spaces and buying land for preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-term ``land legacy'' fund would be similar to what  
Clinton proposed as part of his budget last month, but the 
president said Congress should make such funding permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of bills already have been introduced by both Democrats  
and Republicans in the House and Senate that would boost spending 
for land preservation. The money would come from royalties on 
offshore oil leases. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Interior's block-long granite headquarters is but a few  
blocks from the White House, a presidential visit is a rarity with 
the last such visitor having been Jimmy Carter 22 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps more than any, the Interior Department really embodies  
the history of our country,'' said Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Created in 1849 after a rapid expansion of U.S. territory in the  
West, no federal agency played a greater role in the sculpture of 
America. It directed development of the West, parceling out 
millions of acres of land; opened vast areas to logging, ranching, 
mining and the railroads. In the 1880s the department controlled 
the destiny of more than 1 billion acres -- at the time nearly half 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's reach is still substantial as steward of 440  
million acres of land, including 378 units of the national park 
system, 514 refuges, wilderness areas, millions of acres of 
rangeland and such American crown jewels as Yellowstone National 
Park and the Grand Canyon 
</P>
<P>
	The halls of Interior headquarters, a massive building built as  
part of the Depression-era work programs, remind visitors of 
America's heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	Floor-to-ceiling murals, painted in the 1930s, show homesteaders  
racing westward vowing Oklahoma or bust; wildcatters working the 
oil fields of Texas; a landscape of barren Southwest desert turned 
to lush green thanks to a government dam and irrigation a dogsled 
team cross the wilds of Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a real sense, the history of the Interior Department  
mirrors the history of American expansion and western settlement,'' 
said Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who is the 47th person to 
head the department. ``It also dramatizes America's evolving 
relationship with the land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to Clinton's remarks, the Great American Indian Dancers  
performed a variety of Indian dances. The department in the 19th 
century was charged with dealing with Indians, sometimes with 
horrendous consequences. It remains the federal trust agency for 
Indian tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a department whose primary concern was helping ranchers,  
timber and mining interests exploit American resources, the agency 
now often finds itself challenging those same industries to protect 
those same resources -- the grasslands, threatened species, scenic 
parks and wilderness and open spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	To expand such protection, Clinton said federal spending should  
be assured year-in-year-out. Congress long has authorized as much 
as $900 million for conservation-minded land purchases, but usually 
only about a third of that has been provided. 
</P>
<P>
	Bills introduced by Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., and Sen.  
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., would establish permanent funding of more 
than $2 billion, including $900 million for land purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	A different version, introduced by lawmakers mainly from coastal  
states with offshore oil interests, would calls for even more 
spending, but would earmark nearly $1.2 billion for mitigating 
coastal impacts from oil development. Environmentalists have 
opposed those bills because, they say, they would funnel 60 percent 
of the money to a half dozen states with offshore oil development 
and encourage new oil drilling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
