<DOCNO> APW19990304.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:54:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Urges Saving Open Spaces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, celebrating the 150th  
birthday of the Interior Department, urged broad support Thursday 
for a $1 billion-a-year program to set aside treasured lands and 
open spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, addressing a packed auditorium at the Interior  
headquarters, recalled a visit 30 years ago to the Grand Canyon 
when he watched the sunset across the canyon's multicolored cliffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got over it,'' said the president, adding that  
protection of such natural resources is at the heart of the 
Interior Department's history of land stewardship. 
</P>
<P>
	The president used the celebration to call on the Republican-led  
Congress to stop ``wasting precious time battling over senseless 
anti-environmental riders ... which I'm going to veto anyway'' and 
join in approving a permanent guarantee of annual funding for 
protecting open spaces and buying land for preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-term ``land legacy'' fund would be similar to what  
Clinton proposed as part of his budget last month, but the 
president said Congress should make such funding permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of bills already have been introduced by both Democrats  
and Republicans in the House and Senate that would boost spending 
for land preservation. The money would come from royalties on 
offshore oil leases. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Interior's block-long granite headquarters is but a few  
blocks from the White House, a presidential visit is a rarity with 
the last such visitor having been Jimmy Carter 22 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps more than any, the Interior Department really embodies  
the history of our country,'' said Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Created in 1849 after a rapid expansion of U.S. territory in the  
West, no federal agency played a greater role in the sculpture of 
America. It directed development of the West, parceling out 
millions of acres of land; opened vast areas to logging, ranching, 
mining and the railroads. In the 1880s the department controlled 
the destiny of more than 1 billion acres -- at the time nearly half 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's reach is still substantial as steward of 440  
million acres of land, including 378 units of the national park 
system, 514 refuges, wilderness areas, millions of acres of 
rangeland and such American crown jewels as Yellowstone National 
Park and the Grand Canyon 
</P>
<P>
	The halls of Interior headquarters, a massive building built as  
part of the Depression-era work programs, remind visitors of 
America's heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	Floor-to-ceiling murals, painted in the 1930s, show homesteaders  
racing westward vowing Oklahoma or bust; wildcatters working the 
oil fields of Texas; a landscape of barren Southwest desert turned 
to lush green thanks to a government dam and irrigation a dogsled 
team cross the wilds of Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a real sense, the history of the Interior Department  
mirrors the history of American expansion and western settlement,'' 
said Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who is the 47th person to 
head the department. ``It also dramatizes America's evolving 
relationship with the land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to Clinton's remarks, the Great American Indian Dancers  
performed a variety of Indian dances. The department in the 19th 
century was charged with dealing with Indians, sometimes with 
horrendous consequences. It remains the federal trust agency for 
Indian tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a department whose primary concern was helping ranchers,  
timber and mining interests exploit American resources, the agency 
now often finds itself challenging those same industries to protect 
those same resources -- the grasslands, threatened species, scenic 
parks and wilderness and open spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	To expand such protection, Clinton said federal spending should  
be assured year-in-year-out. Congress long has authorized as much 
as $900 million for conservation-minded land purchases, but usually 
only about a third of that has been provided. 
</P>
<P>
	Bills introduced by Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., and Sen.  
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., would establish permanent funding of more 
than $2 billion, including $900 million for land purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	A different version, introduced by lawmakers mainly from coastal  
states with offshore oil interests, would calls for even more 
spending, but would earmark nearly $1.2 billion for mitigating 
coastal impacts from oil development. Environmentalists have 
opposed those bills because, they say, they would funnel 60 percent 
of the money to a half dozen states with offshore oil development 
and encourage new oil drilling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
