<DOCNO> APW19990304.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:38:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> After Lewinsky, What Next for TV? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Closure for Monicagate? Don't hold your breath.  
</P>
<P>
	What was most notable about Barbara Walters' much-hyped  
interview with Monica Lewinsky was how it raised questions about an 
unknowable future, rather than resolving the bizarre twists of the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that both parties to this ratings sweeps spectacular didn't  
shine in their prescribed roles. For Wednesday's special ``20/20'' 
edition, ABC News star Walters excelled as the caring but sometimes 
stern aunt trying to get to the bottom of this White House mess. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have been described as a bimbo, a stalker and a  
seductress,'' Walters began, looking sad to have to say it. 
``Describe yourself.'' And they were off and running. 
</P>
<P>
	For the interview, taped in Manhattan on Feb. 20, Walters and  
Ms. Lewinsky sat facing each other from plush wing chairs in the 
studio set of a comfortable living room. But the program also wove 
in file footage and other visuals, as well as Walters in her other 
role as omniscient narrator laying out the saga of Oval Office 
shenanigans. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the final fade-out, after two interminable hours (and  
more commercials than a viewer could count), the lasting impression 
dwelled not so much on what had transpired, but on what comes next 
in the celebrity pageant Walters presides over. Who will be the 
next notch on her belt? 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Ms. Lewinsky showed herself to be poised and  
well-spoken, and almost eerily prepared. She claimed to have spent 
much of the past year worrying and knitting scarves. But judging 
from her smooth performance, the 25-year-old former White House 
intern might have been working with a media consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	She smiled demurely at the mention of her flashing her thong  
underwear at President Clinton, then described it as ``a small, 
subtle, flirtatious gesture, and that's me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The famous blue dress ... ,'' Walters said a little later.  
</P>
<P>
	``What dress?'' Ms. Lewinsky replied with a laugh.  
</P>
<P>
	When Walters asked Ms. Lewinsky whether Clinton was a sensuous  
man, she answered, ``I'll get in trouble.'' Responded Walters: 
``Not in any more trouble than you've already been in, Monica. You 
have immunity here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But summing up the past year at the program's close, Ms.  
Lewinsky lost her composure. Effectively. She was brought to tears 
when she talked about her and her parents considering suicide 
during the ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have no idea what this has done,'' she said, glancing  
heavenward, her voice choking -- ``that behind the name Monica 
Lewinsky there's a person and there's a family, and so much pain 
has been caused by all this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Granted. But what happens next? Ms. Lewinsky seemed to have no  
real plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to make a contribution to society,'' she ventured,  
``a good contribution this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No closure there, either.  
</P>
<P>
	For her final question, Walters asked what Ms. Lewinsky would  
tell her children in the future about the incident. ``Mommy made a 
big mistake,'' she answered. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky's sitdown with Walters surely furthers her image  
resurrection that began last month with her television debut in the 
form of a prerecorded deposition for Clinton's impeachment trial. 
Taped a few days earlier, it was excerpted for the U.S. Senate and 
broadcast by TV networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Richly benefiting from low expectations, Ms. Lewinsky impressed  
her audience. Almost instantly the conventional wisdom did an 
about-face. For instance, New York magazine's Michael Wolff 
observed how, much to everyone's surprise, Monica Lewinsky has 
emerged not as damaged goods but as ``one of the major brand names 
of our time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fitting, then, that she would have allied herself with Walters,  
the reigning brand name of TV news. 
</P>
<P>
	But was closure for the Lewinsky affair anywhere in sight?  
</P>
<P>
	``This will put an end to it,'' Regis Philbin had proposed to  
Walters with ill-disguised longing when she dropped by ``Live with 
Regis and Kathie Lee'' on Wednesday morning. ``You know, to go to 
you for final absolution, and then it's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it is over,'' said Walters, laughing.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's GOT to be over after YOU!'' Regis erupted.  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe they were both right.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:08:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Boost Aviation Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal aviation-related spending would double  
over the next five years under legislation introduced Thursday by 
House Transportation Committee Chairman Bud Shuster. The bill would 
require all airport taxes to be used for aviation investment, a 
move that would affect the overall budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster's bill to reauthorize the Federal Aviation  
Administration for five years will compete with significantly 
different bills proposed by Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John 
McCain, R-Ariz., and the Clinton administration in what could be 
one of the biggest legislative battles of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster, R-Pa., a tenacious advocate of funding for  
transportation programs, has backing in the House in demanding that 
the Aviation Trust Fund, supported by airport user taxes, be spent 
solely on airport projects. But the idea faces strong Senate and 
administration opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, in a major highway construction bill, he succeeded in  
boxing off a similar highway trust fund from any effort to spend 
the money for other purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, he said, the airport fund will accumulate some $10  
billion in revenues but because of spending legislation approved 
last year, only $6 billion will be spent on airport improvements. 
The rest is counted toward the budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	If the current system isn't changed, he said, the trust fund's  
balance will grow from $10 billion last year to more than $90 
billion in 2009. ``The money is there, it just isn't being spent,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his ``AIR 21'' bill, total FAA funding would grow from $10  
billion this year to more than $20 billion in 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain would reauthorize the FAA for only two years and not  
change the status of the aviation trust fund. Neither would the 
five-year administration proposal, which would increase the airport 
ticket tax from $3 to $5 per airport and institute $1.5 billion in 
new user fees for the air traffic control system. 
</P>
<P>
	All three bills would try to increase competition by adding  
flights from O'Hare in Chicago and La Guardia and Kennedy in New 
York to smaller markets. They differ on increasing flights from 
Washington's Reagan National. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's bill, approved by the Senate Commerce Committee and  
awaiting floor action, would add 48 slots, or 24 round-trip 
flights, from Reagan National. Half of those new flights would go 
beyond the 1,250-mile limit set in 1986 for flights out of the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster would add only six slots at the Reagan National, and the  
administration bill, which would drop limits on flights into the 
Chicago and New York airports in five years, would not change the 
flights or the distance limit at the Washington airport. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's bill has drawn strong opposition from lawmakers  
representing the Washington metropolitan area. They say adding 
flights at Reagan National would damage the environment and hurt 
the other two regional airports, Dulles and Baltimore-Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John Warner, R-Va., in a Senate floor speech Thursday,  
stressed ``how detrimental this excessive increase in flights will 
be for our hard-fought regional balance, air traffic safety and 
consumer service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He introduced legislation to limit the number of new round-trip  
flights at Reagan National to 12, the number in a similar bill the 
Senate passed last year, 92-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to reach a House-Senate compromise last year on FAA  
reauthorization stalled over the increased flight issue, with Rep. 
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the House Judiciary Committee chairman, 
strongly opposing more flights out of O'Hare. 
</P>
<P>
	A stopgap six-month bill was approved, and that legislation  
expires March 31. The House has already passed another six-month 
extension to give the two chambers time to work out their 
differences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Arizona Executes 2nd German Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
