<DOCNO> APW19990304.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Delivery: Rodman-Grams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	This postman always clicks twice.  
</P>
<P>
	Readers of this column recently were provided with an e-mail  
address and invited to respond. Predicting which topics would draw 
the most responses was easy; it was much tougher to anticipate the 
range. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's a sampling:  

</P>
<P>
	A column on Dennis Rodman, (``Close Cover Before Striking''),  
noted that the Worm's rap sheet from his time with the San Antonio 
Spurs included, among other things, stockinged-feet strikes. 

</P>
<P>
	From Trey McClure:  
</P>
<P>
	``If you researched the reason Rodman took off his shoes ... you  
might find he has a rare skin disease that causes his covered feet 
to heat up more than the average person. The best way for him to 
cool them off is to take off his shoes. ... There needs to be more 
written about Rodman's pre-basketball days, then maybe people would 
understand why he is the way he is.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dear Trey:  
</P>
<P>
	Excuses, excuses. I can't believe being forced to wear ``Dr.  
Dentons' '' is the reason little Dennis grew up to become such a 
menace. 

</P>
<P>
	A column about golf's Match Play Championships, (``Sure These  
Guys Are Good. But Are They Interesting?'') argued that fans lost 
out when journeymen Jeff Maggert and Andrew Magee wound up in the 
final. 

</P>
<P>
	From Hugh Bursi:  
</P>
<P>
	``Good, but not interesting, was a pretty apt description of the  
article itself. If you wanted to write something interesting, why 
didn't you write about how Tiger choked in his match against 
Maggert?'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dear Hugh:  
</P>
<P>
	Now it can be told: Tiger choked because he couldn't take off  
his shoes between shots. 

</P>
<P>
	From Don Wozniak:  
</P>
<P>
	``It was refreshing to hear the announcers lavish praise on  
someone other than Tiger. ... If the media only wants to see 
marquee players and juvenile displays of emotion, you are right 
about this event not being interesting. But for showing top-quality 
competition and conduct, there has never been a better telecast.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dear Don:  
</P>
<P>
	Is it possible you got your channels crossed? I turned on the  
set Sunday hoping to see a marquee player display some juvenile 
emotion, but all I got was top-quality competition and conduct, 
too. After a while, though, I realized I was watching Rodman and 
the Lakers playing Houston. 

</P>
<P>
	A column about Walter Payton and his battle with a rare liver  
disease, (``A Message Worth Repeating''), stirred personal memories 
and even prompted one offer of a liver for transplant. 

</P>
<P>
	From an Interested Party:  
</P>
<P>
	``I know this might be an odd e-mail, but I would really like  
information on what kind of donor Walter Payton needs. ... P.S.: I 
am a very healthy white woman, age 38. Do not drink or do any 
drugs, except prescription. This story has really torn at my heart 
and would really like to help.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dear Interested Party:  
</P>
<P>
	While still awaiting a transplant, Payton's condition has  
stabilized and he is resting comfortably. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, spokeswoman Pam Silvestri of the Southwest Transplant  
Alliance, part of a national network of agencies providing 
information and assistance on organ donation, said Payton's story 
has been the best thing for business since Yankee great Mickey 
Mantle went on the liver-transplant list. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of our agencies report 20-to-30 requests a month,'' she  
said. ``They're averaging that many every day now, and in the 
Chicago area, it's two or three times that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Incredible'' is the way Silvestri described the number of  
people designating Payton for directed donations -- that is, a 
donation made to a designated recipient if the organ is compatible. 
</P>
<P>
	Told that one reader had offered a liver on the spot, she  
laughed. ``We've got a few of those, too. Tell her as long as she's 
alive, she'll need to hang on to it.'' 

</P>
<P>
	A column on Latrell Sprewell moving to New York, (``The NBA Gets  
Off On The Wrong Foot''), speculated about how a known tough guy 
would make out in an even tougher town. 

</P>
<P>
	From Jeff Gomez:  
</P>
<P>
	``If you feel compelled to write about how he tormented other  
players and coaches and will continue to do so in the future, I 
hope you'd be able to say those same comments to his face. If you 
can honestly answer ``yes,'' then I don't criticize you one bit for 
your article.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dear Jeff:  
</P>
<P>
	The day Spree asks for a heart-to-heart is the day I enroll in  
the federal witness-protection program. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
