<DOCNO> APW19990304.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:55:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. To Court Expos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The seats at RFK Stadium have been realigned.  
Base paths have been carved out of fresh sod for the first time in 
six years, all awaiting the arrival of the Montreal Expos for a 
couple of days next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Next time, maybe they'll stay a lot longer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Let's just say that they'll find a much larger and warmer  
welcome than they have in their own home stadium for quite some 
time,'' said Mike Scanlon, part of a group that wants to bring 
major league baseball to the Washington area. 
</P>
<P>
	It's mere coincidence that the Expos are accompanying the St.  
Louis Cardinals for a pair of exhibition games at RFK on April 2 
and 3. When the event was arranged, the big attraction was supposed 
to be Mark McGwire; now the focus will be on a financially troubled 
team on display in an area that's been trying lure baseball back 
since the Senators left to become the Texas Rangers 28 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are closer now than we ever have been,'' said Jim  
Dalrymple, who has been working on the task for 14 years as 
executive director of the District of Columbia Sports Commission. 
``I think we've got the right game plan in place. We just need a 
little luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talk of relocation does not sit well with major league baseball  
-- no team has moved since the Senators. But with a Saturday 
deadline approaching for a financing plan for a new stadium in 
Montreal and no money in sight, commissioner Bud Selig is expected 
to give Expos president Claude Brochu permission next week to 
negotiate with out-of-town bidders who could buy the team and move 
it elsewhere as early as the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading contenders would be groups from Charlotte, N.C.,;  
the District of Columbia and Northern Virginia -- the generic name 
for the densely populated suburbs to the west of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	For fans in the D.C. region, it's another hill on a roller  
coaster ride that has left them somewhat jaded. It seems there's a 
new team every other year that is rumored to be on the verge of 
coming to the Washington area -- the Astros and Pirates were the 
most recent. 
</P>
<P>
	The group from Northern Virginia, headed by telecommunications  
executive William Collins, has come close twice. Collins made the 
finals in the last round of expansion in 1995 and had a handshake 
agreement to buy the Astros had voters not approved a new stadium 
there by a narrow margin in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ready to deal,'' said Scanlon, executive vice president  
of the Collins group. ``We would welcome Claude and any other 
members of his group in our membership group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Real estate developer Douglas Jemal, who wants a team in the  
district, is also waiting for the go-ahead to negotiate with 
Brochu. Tim Newman, vice president of entrepreneur Don Beaver's 
group in Charlotte, said such talk is ``all premature,'' but that 
Beaver is ``monitoring the situation very closely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While each bid has promise, all three have their drawbacks,  
starting with how to finance a $300 million stadium and where to 
build it. And, for the two D.C. area groups, there will be certain 
opposition from Baltimore Orioles owner Peter Angelos, whose team 
draws heavily from the Washington area and considers the region one 
big market. Of the Northern Virginia bid, Angelos had said that if 
the state of Virginia wants a team, it should be placed in 
Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baltimore and Washington have always been separate markets,''  
Scanlon said. ``There is no way people in Virginia consider 
themselves a suburb of Baltimore, Maryland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ironic that Mr. Angelos would make such a statement,''  
said Gabe Paul, executive director of the state-created Virginia 
Baseball Stadium Authority. ``The Orioles, in order to move from 
St. Louis in 1954, had to ask for and receive permission from the 
Senators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte group doesn't have to deal with Angelos, but it's  
biggest drawback could be its plan to have the Expos play in the 
Charlotte Knights' minor league stadium -- expanded to seat perhaps 
25,000 -- during the two years it would take to build a new 
facility. The two D.C. area groups would use RFK, which housed the 
Senators, as an interim stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Collins group also has a head start on the financial end.  
The Virginia legislature has approved partial funding for a stadium 
and given Gov. Jim Gilmore authority to negotiate the rest of the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason for Northern Virginia is because of the growth of  
this region,'' Paul said. ``How can baseball overlook the No. 7 
(television) market in the country forever?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Comeback One for Books </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- Theo Fleury simply may have been trying to  
boost the spirits of his new teammates. Or maybe he had a gut 
feeling. 
</P>
<P>
	With Colorado trailing Florida 5-1 after two periods Wednesday  
night, the Avalanche's newest acquisition -- out nursing a knee 
injury -- predicted his new team would rally to win 6-5. 
</P>
<P>
	It turns out he underestimated his teammates. Colorado stormed  
back for a 7-5 triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	Imagine how potent the Avalanche are going to be when Fleury  
does his best work on the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I'm going to get to play with these guys?'' Fleury said in  
amazement after watching the Avalanche score seven unanswered goals 
to match the NHL record for the biggest comeback in a victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven other teams have rallied to win from a five-goal deficit,  
the last time coming Dec. 26, 1991. That's when the New York 
Rangers climbed out of a 6-1 hole in the first period to beat the 
Washington Capitals 8-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's feat is likely to go down as the most remarkable  
because of the short time frame the Avalanche had to work with. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche trailed 5-0 when Peter Forsberg broke the drought  
with 1:49 left in the second period, fighting off Florida's Bret 
Hedican to put a backhander behind Sean Burke. 
</P>
<P>
	That only set the table for a six-goal third period, which  
opened with Claude Lemieux's power-play goal after 17 seconds and 
snowballed with a four-goal binge over the final five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Goals by Adam Deadmarsh and Chris Drury 41 seconds apart tied  
the game at 15:41. Milan Hejduk put Colorado ahead at 17:40, and 
Forsberg scored an unassisted goal 49 seconds later. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before we walked out for the third, we said if we get a  
power-play goal, maybe we have a chance,'' Forsberg said. ``We got 
it right off the bat and after that, we just kept on working. It 
turned out pretty good at the end there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forsberg finished with three goals and three assists, his best  
outing in the NHL and matching a club record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Forsberg? He put on quite a display of his immense  
talent,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley said. ``He was outstanding out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartley had raised some eyebrows when he put Forsberg and Joe  
Sakic on the same line in early December. The duo has combined for 
32 goals and 52 assists in 30 games since then, and the rest of the 
Avalanche haven't lagged, either, with 66 goals during the same 
span. 
</P>
<P>
	Mix in Fleury, who tallied 30 goals and 39 assists in Calgary  
before last Sunday's trade, and the Avalanche can match anybody's 
firepower. 
</P>
<P>
	``With 20 games to go, this is a great sign for our season,''  
Hartley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Things got worse for the Panthers on Thursday, when they learned  
high-scoring Pavel Bure would be lost for at least two weeks with 
torn knee cartilage. He was scheduled for arthroscopic surgery 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bure's three goals -- his second hat trick in 11 games this  
season -- had helped stake the Panthers to the 5-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's as tough a loss as any I've ever been a part of,''  
Florida captain Scott Mellanby said. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the second time this season Florida had blown a  
sizeable lead. In December, the Panthers squandered a four-goal 
edge against Ottawa before escaping 6-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Leafs' McCauley Taken to Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Toronto Maple Leafs center Alyn McCauley was  
taken from the ice on a stretcher after being checked hard into the 
boards early in the third period of a game against the New Jersey 
Devils on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	McCauley was driven heavily into the end boards by Devils  
defenseman Sheldon Souray at the 6:51 mark of the third period. 
McCauley's left shoulder and head appeared to take the brunt of 
Souray's hit against the glass next to New Jersey goalie Martin 
Brodeur. 
</P>
<P>
	McCauley appeared to lose consciousness and lay motionless on  
the ice for several minutes. He was attended to by four emergency 
personnel including Maple Leafs team doctor Leith Douglas who 
directed the crew to fit McCauley with a neck brace. McCauley was 
lifted onto a stretcher and taken along with his fiancee to Toronto 
Western Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Team officials said that he suffered a head injury and that he  
had movement in all of his extremities. He was to spend the night 
in hospital and be re-examined Thursday. While the injury was not 
considered serious, coach Pat Quinn was concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was unconscious for quite a while,'' Quinn said. ``We won't  
know anything until the evaluation is complete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey was leading 3-2 at the time, and the Devils went on  
to a 5-2 victory. The game was delayed about 10 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	It been a tough season for McCauley, who was playing in just his  
fourth game after missing 22 with a knee injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:11:07 </DATE_TIME>
