<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:35:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For Larry Walker, the first day of the exhibition season  
couldn't have been much better. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Rockies outfielder, who won a batting title and the  
National League MVP award in the past two years, agreed Thursday to 
a $75 million, six-year contract extension, then drove in two runs 
with a home run and a single against the Arizona Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to relax, finally,'' said Walker, who jumped into a  
tie for sixth on the salary scale. ``I've been shaking for the last 
three days, not only thinking about six years and all the money 
that's involved, but just the fact that it's over and we can quit 
talking about `What if?' I'm so elated it's sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, 32, will make $5,075,000 this season as he finishes a  
five-year contract. The new deal calls for a $1 million signing 
bonus, $12 million each in 2000 and 2001 and $12.5 million annually 
from 2002-05. 
</P>
<P>
	His new deal, with a $12.5 million average annual value, ties  
him with Boston pitcher Pedro Martinez and New York Yankees 
outfielder Bernie Williams, behind only Los Angeles pitcher Kevin 
Brown ($15 million), Anaheim first baseman Mo Vaughn ($12.33 
million), Arizona pitcher Randy Johnson ($13.1 million) and New 
York Mets catcher Mike Piazza and Baltimore outfielder Albert Belle 
($13 million each). 
</P>
<P>
	Walker tied Martinez for fifth in total dollars, trailing Brown  
($105 million), Piazza ($91 million), Williams ($87.5 million) and 
Vaughn ($80 million). 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing was to stay here,'' Walker said. ``I was going  
to say the money doesn't need to be astronomical going through the 
roof, but it is. You think about it, it's ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other news:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Nearly 19 years after an angry parting with the Boston Red  
Sox, Carlton Fisk is considering returning to the team for which he 
hit one of baseball's most famous homers. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing on the field Thursday before Boston's spring training  
opener, Fisk said he had a ``nice conversation'' with general 
manager Dan Duquette in the morning and planned further 
discussions. Although an exact role hasn't been determined, 
Duquette said Fisk could be ``a role model, a liaison'' or a 
catching instructor. 
</P>
<P>
	-- At Coral Gables, Fla., Florida Marlins third-base prospect  
Mike Lowell, recovering from surgery for testicular cancer, went to 
the ballpark for therapy. Lowell, unlikely to return by opening 
day, sat in the stands, soaked up some sunshine and watched the 
Marlins' exhibition opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching baseball is a breath of fresh air,'' Lowell said. ``I  
just wanted to catch the game and see some guys play. It's good 
therapy, to say the least.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- At Dunedin, Fla., the Toronto Blue Jays said David Wells will  
be back on the field Friday after four days of treatment for back 
spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	-- At Winter Haven, Fla., Mark Whiten's stress fracture in his  
right foot, now expected to keep him off the field 4-7 weeks, could 
give a couple of prospects a chance to prove themselves. Rookie 
outfielders Jacob Cruz and Alex Ramirez will now get longer looks 
as the Indians could be searching for a backup center fielder 
behind Kenny Lofton. 
</P>
<P>
	-- At Bradenton, Fla., the Pirates have not altered their offer  
to first baseman Kevin Young, who said he is frustrated by the lack 
of progress in contract talks. Young wants a 4- to 5-year contract 
in the $6 million-per-year range, while the Pirates have not budged 
off their offer of $16.5 million over three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	In exhibition games:  
</P>
<P>
                        *Yankees 4, Blue Jays 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tampa, Fla., the World Series champions started 1999 the same  
way they ended 1998: with a victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Spencer had an RBI double during a two-run seventh inning.  
Both starters, New York's Orlando Hernandez and Toronto's Chris 
Carpenter, allowed one run and two hits in three innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez struck out four and walked one, while Carpenter fanned  
two. Jeff Nelson was the winner and Mariano Rivera got the save as 
four New York relievers combined to allow one run and three hits. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Red Sox 9, Twins (ss) 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Fort Myers, Fla., newcomer Jose Offerman doubled in one run  
and Nomar Garciaparra tripled in one in a five-run third inning. In 
their first game since Mo Vaughn signed with Anaheim, the Red Sox 
had 16 hits, seven for extra bases. Two were solo homers by Bob 
Hamelin in the fourth and Lou Merloni in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Rapp, signed as a free agent after going 12-13 with Kansas  
City last season, got the win after allowing one run and two hits 
in two innings. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Reds 4, Twins (ss) 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Sarasota, Fla., Pete Harnisch pitched four scoreless innings  
and Hal Morris' two-run single won the game in the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Rockies 7, Diamondbacks 6    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tucson, Ariz., the Rockies scored three runs in the eighth  
off closer Gregg Olson, who had 30 saves last year in a big 
comeback season. Derrick Gibson tied it at 6 with a two-run double 
and Chris Sexton doubled past diving Andy Fox at third base for the 
go-ahead run. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Stottlemyre, in his Diamondbacks debut, gave up three runs  
and three hits in two innings. He experimented with a new changeup 
and didn't throw his slider. Colorado starter Brian Bohanon allowed 
two runs and one hit in two innings, struck out three and walked 
two. 
</P>
<P>
 *Athletics 7, Brewers 5    	
</P>
<P>
	At Phoenix, AL Rookie of the Year Ben Grieve hit a grand slam  
off Hector Ramirez to cap a seven-run third inning. Brewers starter 
Bill Pulsipher retired his first six batters, then gave up two 
singles opening the third. Ramirez, a non-roster invitee who 
pitched for Florida's Triple-A team at Charlotte last season, 
allowed six of seven batters to reach base, and five scored. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Phillies 13, South Florida 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Clearwater, Fla., Curt Schilling, coming off consecutive 	
300-strikeout seasons, pitched three perfect innings and struck out 
six. Schilling, who led the National League in innings, strikeouts 
and complete games last year, left with a 4-0 lead after throwing 
34 pitches. Only three batters put the ball in play against 
Schilling, getting two groundouts and an infield pop. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Braves 15, Georgia Tech 5 	
</P>
<P>
	At Kissimmee, Fla., Danny Bautista had two home runs and five 	
RBIs and Randall Simon hit a two-run homer.	
</P>
<P>
                     *Marlins 12, Univ. of Miami 3 	
</P>
<P>
	At Coral Gables, Fla., rookie right-handers A.J. Burnett and  
Dario Perez, contending for the No. 5 spot in Florida's rotation, 
pitched two hitless innings apiece. The 22-year-old Burnett, trying 
to make the jump from Single-A, struck out four and walked one, 
gaining the victory. 
</P>
<P>
                 *Pirates 5, Manatee Community Coll. 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Bradenton, Fla., Jason Schmidt started and pitched two  
scoreless innings and Ivan Cruz hit a solo homer. Kris Benson, the 
No. 1 pick in the 1996 amateur draft, gave up two hits and a run 
and struck out three in two innings. 
</P>
