<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Gov't Shakeup Rumors Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Boris Yeltsin fired controversial tycoon Boris  
Berezovsky as head of an alliance of former Soviet republics 
Thursday, and reports that Yeltsin was planning to reshuffle his 
Cabinet again sent Russian lawmakers into a political frenzy. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential aides quickly denied any such plans, but Communists  
and other hard-liners who dominate the parliament's lower house, 
the State Duma, took the reports seriously. The issue dominated the 
Duma floor and national television news. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian media reports claimed that Yeltsin told Prime Minister  
Yevgeny Primakov he had 10 days to purge the government of all 
Communists, or risk getting booted himself. The alleged threat 
appeared to target two deputy prime ministers, Yuri Maslyukov and 
Gennady Kulik. 
</P>
<P>
	Maslyukov is the highest-ranking Communist in the government,  
while Kulik is a member of the Agrarian Party, a hard-line faction 
that often aligns itself with the Communists. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin immediately denied the  
reports, calling them ``complete rubbish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin, still in the hospital recovering from a recurring  
ulcer, ``has made no statements on this topic, he has not demanded 
anything from anyone,'' Yakushkin told the NTV television station. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian president abruptly fired the entire Cabinet two  
times last year, contributing to the nation's economic crisis. He 
often acts rashly after recovering from an illness to show that 
he's still in control. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors of a government shakeup have been circulating in Moscow  
for the past few weeks and have not been quelled by Kremlin 
denials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sooner or later, (a reshuffle) is bound to happen,'' said  
Sergei Ivanenko, a lawmaker with the liberal Yabloko faction. 
</P>
<P>
	Berezovsky, a billionaire with holdings in oil, media and  
airlines, was named last March to oversee the Commonwealth of 
Independent States, an unruly alliance of 12 former Soviet 
republics. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin is chairman of the CIS, a mostly ceremonial post. The  
other CIS countries must approve Berezovsky's ouster, but none is 
likely to protest the move. 
</P>
<P>
	The prime minister has publicly criticized Berezovsky for  
meddling in the Cabinet's work, and several recent police raids and 
probes have targeted companies believed to be controlled by the 
tycoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
