<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury in Gondola Case Deliberates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Eight military jurors began a second  
day of deliberations today on whether a Marine pilot whose jet hit 
an Italian ski gondola cable last year is guilty of involuntary 
manslaughter for the 20 people who died. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury met for about four hours Wednesday afternoon. Six of  
the eight officers on the jury must vote guilty in order to convict 
Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's lawyer, Frank Spinner, has urged jurors to rely on the  
expert testimony. He said his client suffered from an optical 
illusion that made him think his jet was higher than it was, that 
an altimeter on the jet malfunctioned and that the gondola at 
Cavalese, Italy, wasn't marked on American maps. 
</P>
<P>
	But prosecutor Maj. Daniel Daugherty said the only reason the  
mishap happened was because Ashby flew by his own rules. He said 
the pilot ignored speed and altitude limits, which Ashby testified 
he didn't know about. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby faces more than 200 years in prison if convicted of all  
counts. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened on the final leg of a 42-minute training  
route through the Italian Alps. Afterward, Italians demanded that 
U.S. landing rights be revoked at bases in their country. 
</P>
<P>
	While the jury deliberated, attorneys for Capt. Joseph  
Schweitzer, the navigator in Ashby's EA-6B Prowler jet, said 
closing arguments made them optimistic that charges against their 
client could be dismissed. Schweitzer faces charges similar to 
Ashby's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:45:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davey Johnson Ready for the LA Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The pressure is on in Los Angeles, and  
Davey Johnson knows it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bring it on, he says.  
</P>
<P>
	``My first (managing) job was in New York,'' Johnson said  
Thursday from spring training. ``And I played in Japan. My survival 
instincts are intact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers, who haven't won a postseason game since 1988, have  
made sweeping changes since the Fox Group purchased the team from 
the O'Malley family last March. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice, they've switched managers and general managers, and the  
payroll has gone from the middle of the pack in baseball to near 
the top. 
</P>
<P>
	The obvious goal? Win now.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 56, was hired as manager, succeeding Glenn Hoffman,  
last October -- after Montreal's Felipe Alou turned down the job to 
remain with the Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Felipe, he's a good man,'' Johnson said. ``He doesn't  
need the stress that will come with this job. I'm more used to 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson had been out of baseball since resigning as manager of  
the Baltimore Orioles following the 1997 season. He quit the same 
day he was honored as AL manager of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I loved Baltimore,'' he said. ``I tried to do whatever the  
owner (Peter Angelos) wanted, and I couldn't quite please him. You 
want to do good for your boss. I didn't accomplish that. It was a 
failure on my part because I couldn't win him over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles were the AL wild-card team in Johnson's first year,  
and went wire-to-wire in winning the AL East championship in his 
second and final year. It was Baltimore's first division crown in 
14 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles reached the AL Championship Series both years before  
being eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was more to it,'' Johnson said of his leaving the  
Orioles. ``I don't want to go into it. I thought we had nothing to 
be ashamed about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The job Johnson did in Baltimore was typical of him. In his 10  
full seasons, none of his teams finished lower than second place. 
His .575 winning percentage (985-727) is the best among all active 
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Johnson was unemployed until the Dodgers hired him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I always say things work out for the best,'' he said.  
``Somebody's looking out for me. I had a great interview with 
Toronto (last year), they decided to go with a Johnson -- Tim 
Johnson, not Davey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, it would seem, Johnson has a much greater opportunity to  
win than his namesake in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in a big market,'' he said. ``It's a talented team.  
My job is to give them the best opportunity to win. We have a 
chance to do that. It's miserable to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way this camp has gone so far, I'm really pleased with the  
work ethic and attitude. I couldn't ask for any better, it's been 
very gratifying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His ace pitcher, Kevin Brown, says Johnson is ``dedicated to  
winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows what winning's all about,'' Brown said. ``He's not  
the kind of guy who's got to have his fingers on each individual 
person all the time. He has a plan. He understands there's 
different strokes for different guys. I expect to have a lot of 
good years playing under him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said outfielder Gary Sheffield: ``He's a player's manager. He  
has a loose clubhouse. He's gotten straight to the point of what he 
wants us to accomplish and so far, we have. I respect him just like 
I did (former Florida Marlins manager) Jim Leyland. They're real 
intense guys. You know who the manager is on the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he hopes the Dodgers' job is the final one of his  
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is not only to win here, but help the organization get  
back to where they were a few years ago,'' he said. ``(The front 
office) has been exceptional. Now, it's up to me and the players to 
do our job. I'm up for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he believes fans in Los Angeles are similar to  
those in New York, with a few key differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just as well informed, maybe less cynical, not quite as hard,  
attitude-wise,'' he said. ``In New York, I think it's who can you 
step on to step up. In LA, it's who can you work with to step up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:42:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big East Heavyweights Play Thurs. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For Seton Hall, Georgetown and Rutgers,  
first-round victories in the Big East tournament came with a price. 
Now they get to play the conference heavyweights. 
</P>
<P>
	Seton Hall draws No. 3 Connecticut, while Georgetown goes  
against No. 9 Miami and Rutgers draws No. 10 St. John's in today's 
quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll take their chances.  
</P>
<P>
	Seton Hall (15-13) lost twice to UConn (25-2) in the regular  
season, including a five-point defeat three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing tough and coming close doesn't matter,'' Pirates coach  
Tommy Amaker said. ``This is the Big East tournament. This is the 
showcase for our league, and they are the best in our league. They 
are sharp and ready to go. We're going to have an unbelievable 
battle just to stay on the court with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown (15-14) lost both games against Miami (21-5), the  
first when John Thompson was still coach of the Hoyas, the second 
after Craig Esherick took over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly hope we shoot a lot better,'' Esherick said. ``A  
lot of how poorly we shot was attributed to Miami's defense. Miami 
has a very good defense, one of the best in the league, if not the 
country, and there's a lot of people that did not shoot well 
against Miami.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rutgers (18-11) was swept by St. John's (23-7), and four  
straight losses at the end of the regular season left the Scarlet 
Knights struggling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worry about St. John's physically,'' coach Kevin Bannon  
said. ``They're big when you look at all the positions. They're 
strong. We played them tough. We've been in two wars with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In today's other quarterfinal, Syracuse (20-10), coming off the  
biggest blowout in tournament history, meets Villanova (21-9). It 
will be the 10th meeting between the schools, most for any matchup 
in Big East tournament history. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Seton Hall 79, Notre Dame 69    	
</P>
<P>
	The postseason frustration continued for Notre Dame, which has  
never won a Big East Tournament game. The Irish (14-16) beat Seton 
Hall twice in the regular season, but the Pirates knocked them off 
this time with an efficient defense that capitalized on 23 
turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we tried to do was really pressure the ball,'' Amaker  
said. ``We tried to at least force them out a little bit further. I 
thought our perimeter defense was pretty good and we got some easy 
baskets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duane Jordan and Rimas Kaukenas led Seton Hall with 18 apiece,  
while freshman Ty Shine had 17. Troy Murphy, Big East freshman of 
the year, led all scorers with 28 on 10-for-16 shooting for Notre 
Dame. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Syracuse 96, Boston College 55    	
</P>
<P>
	For the third time this season, Syracuse took advantage of a  
matchup mismatch to beat BC. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just bigger and stronger than them,'' coach Jim Boeheim  
said as the Orangemen staged the biggest rout in the 20-year 
history of the Big East tournament. ``You don't like to beat 
anybody this way. The game just got out of hand early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Etan Thomas had 19 points and Jason Hart 15 as every Syracuse  
player scored, sending BC (6-21) to a seventh straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Villanova 73, West Virginia 61    	
</P>
<P>
	Down 11 points in the second half, Villanova rallied to overtake  
West Virginia (10-19). 
</P>
<P>
	John Celestand scored 26 points and Howard Brown 16 for the  
Wildcats, who came back after West Virginia point guard Jarrett 
Kearse fouled out. 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia had a 46-32 rebounding edge, and that concerned  
Villanova coach Steve Lappas for today's game against Syracuse. 
``We're going to have to rebound much better or we'll be in deep 
trouble,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Georgetown 68, Providence 66    	
</P>
<P>
	The Hoyas saved their 24-year postseason appearance streak with  
a late comeback against Providence, wiping out a 10-point 
second-half lead to edge the Friars on a pair of free throws by 
Ruben Boumtje Boumtje in the last 1:23. Boumtje Boumtje led 
Georgetown with 18 points and contributed nine rebounds to a 57-32 
rebounding advantage 
</P>
<P>
	The Hoyas (15-14) are assured of a .500 record, the minimum  
necessary for an NIT bid. Providence (16-13) is probably headed 
there, as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their offensive rebounding was relentless,'' Providence coach  
Tim Welsh said. ``Their work on the boards just wore us out. You 
get 24 turnovers and they have 16 more shots. That was the 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, covering the tournament for a Washington, D.C. radio  
station, asked Boumtje Boumtje a question about being nervous and 
was challenged by his ex-player who said, ``Can I see your press 
credential first?'' 
</P>
<P>
                      *Rutgers 64, Pittsburgh 51    	
</P>
<P>
	Rutgers got 11 points apiece from Rob Hodgson, Alvydas Tenys and  
Geoff Billet, with Hodgson also grabbing 11 rebounds. Ricardo Greer 
led Pitt with 14 points and 14 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We deserved this,'' Bannon said. ``We've been right there with  
nothing to show for it the last few weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pitt (14-16) missed its first 10 shots and never recovered,  
finishing with 28.6 percent on 18-for-63. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the final game as Pitt coach for Ralph Willard, who  
announced his resignation at midseason. No replacement has been 
named. 
</P>
</TEXT>
