<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears Add to Soldier Field Lease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- For years, the Chicago Bears have argued with the  
city and flirted with the suburbs. On Thursday, the football team 
said it was planning to stay put in Chicago, at least for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're 100 percent committed to Chicago,'' new Bears president  
Ted Phillips said, taking a different stance from predecessor Mike 
McCaskey, who was ousted three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaskey had turned to Chicago's suburbs in search of a new  
location after clashing repeatedly with Chicago Mayor Richard M. 
Daley over the Bears' current home. The cost of a new stadium and 
opposition from residents put a damper on those plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, in a new ``spirit of cooperation,'' the club has signed a  
letter of intent with the city to extend the team's five-year lease 
at Soldier Field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited,'' Phillips said during a telephone  
conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Signing this lease extension in our opinion is step one to  
ultimately sitting down with the city to discuss a long-term plan 
for the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips said he is ready to begin discussions about a permanent  
home for the Bears in Chicago, adding that he is ``open to all 
possibilities,'' including a renovated Soldier Field. He declined 
to comment on some city officials' opposition to using public funds 
for a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which extends through the 2004 football season, is  
similar to the current lease that McCaskey long denounced as the 
``worst in NFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the lease agreement, the Bears will have to pay a fixed  
annual rent of $4,616,948, the same rent the team paid during the 
1998 season, officials said. In the past, the rent varied depending 
on the percentage of ticket and skybox revenue the team forked over 
to the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the park district will continue to retain all  
revenue from parking, concessions and stadium advertising. In 
return, the city will maintain the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm delighted we've reached this agreement,'' park district  
General Superintendent Carolyn Williams Meza said in a statement. 
``It ensures that Soldier Field will continue to generate revenues 
to help us improve and maintain our neighborhood park system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new lease also includes an escape clause allowing the  
football team to leave Soldier Field after three years, provided it 
pays the Park District $3 million for the final two years of the 
lease. If the team signs for a long-term home in Chicago, it will 
not have to pay the termination fee. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips did not know when the lease would be signed and said  
that details still needed to be ironed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
