<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 191.52 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied Thursday as benign economic data  
allowed buyers to re-enter the market following several days of 
weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also lifted by a huge contract signed by IBM to  
supply parts to Dell Computer Co. and rising oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 191.52 to 9,467.40,  
more than erasing a 48-point loss over the previous two sessions 
and closing above 9,400 for the first time in more than a week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite ended higher, closing at 2,292.89, up  
27.69. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 18.94 at 1,246.64. 
</P>
<P>
	The market's recovery, which extended a turnaround in technology  
shares that started late Wednesday, was ``totally justified'' by 
recent economic data, said Thomas McManus, portfolio strategist at 
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. Plus, he said, investors still 
have a lot of money to put to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Once stock prices get low enough, ``people find out that there's  
some strong underlying demand,'' McManus said. ``After all, there's 
lots of cash in money-market mutual funds, and so there is a lot of 
liquidity, and earnings growth is improving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, the manufacturing economy is improving and  
inflation is under control. 
</P>
<P>
	The market opened stronger after IBM said it would supply Dell  
with $16 billion in computer parts over seven years. Analysts said 
the arrangement could lead to more highly lucrative deals for IBM, 
whose stock rose 3 1/4 to 171. Dell added 15/16 to 81 7/8 in Nasdaq 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil and oil-service stocks rose for the second day in a row,  
after oil prices advanced following reports of dwindling domestic 
supplies and a temporary interruption of pumping in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	While McManus said he worries that higher oil prices could prove  
inflationary, that wasn't bothering investors on Thursday. Dow 
component Exxon rose 2 1/8 to 67 13/16. Schlumberger, an oil field 
services company, added 4 5/8 to 56 3/8. Crude oil for April delivery 
settled Thursday at $13.35 a barrel, up 42 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial-services stocks rose as bond prices stabilized after  
falling earlier this week. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond 
eased 31.25 cents per $1,000 invested, leaving its yield unchanged 
at 5.69 percent. American Express climbed 5 3/16 to 113. Salomon 
Smith Barney started coverage of the stock with a ``buy'' rating. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market was quiet following Commerce Department report  
that new orders for U.S. factory goods rose 1.7 percent in January 
to a $349.6 billion annual rate. While that was a record high, it 
was still a little under economists' expectations and as such, 
didn't raise fears of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The market's price advances stalled on profit-taking in  
mid-afternoon, but resumed climbing in the final hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Laux, the head trader of listed stocks at ABN/Amro First  
Chicago, attributed the pullback to nervousness ahead of Friday's 
release of February unemployment data. ``A lot of people thought 
there would be a reasonable spate of profit-taking in front of the 
unemployment number,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail stocks also moved higher amid strong February sales  
figures. Wal-Mart, whose February sales rose 10.3 percent at stores 
open at least a year, was up 2 at 89 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume totaled 
922.73, up from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 8.20 to 590.75, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.07 to 698.52. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.08 to 394.03. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign trading, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo rose 0.09  
percent. In Europe, the DAX index in Frankfurt rose 1.20 percent, 
the FT-SE 100 in London added 0.88 percent, and the CAC in Paris 
climbed 2.09 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
