<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules on Billy Martin Estate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Billy Martin's widow is entitled to half the  
value of the heirlooms he bequeathed to his son, daughter and 
granddaughter, a state appeals court ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The items are ``community property'' of the late baseball  
manager's estate, the court ruled, and as such Jilluann Martin has 
a one-half interest in them. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Appellate Division of state Supreme Court noted that the  
creditors of Martin's estate might ultimately be the ones to 
benefit from the ruling. If the estate is found to be insolvent, 
the judges said, the heirlooms will be among Martin's assets which 
could be used to satisfy his debts. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling sends the decade-long battle over Martin's estate  
back for a final disposition to Surrogate's Court in Broome County, 
where Martin had a home and where he died in an auto accident in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line on this is that the ruling confirms the fact  
that Billy's widow has properly handled the financial affairs of 
his estate and clears the way now for the closing of the estate,'' 
Robert Pearl, Jilluann Martin's attorney, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearl said creditors and the government have claims of about  
$600,000 outstanding against Martin's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are a Rolex watch and a gun collection which Martin  
bequeathed to his son, Billy Joe, and a New York Yankees' pendant 
he willed to his daughter, Kelly Martin-Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin also stipulated in his 1988 will that his son, daughter  
and granddaughter were to share in proceeds from the sale of his 
Billy Martin Western Wear clothing line, from his books other than 
``Billy Ball'' and from the money remaining from his contract with 
the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The appellate division judges also directed the Surrogate's  
Court to determine the disposition and value of Martin's book 
proceeds and of the remaining portion of his Yankees contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearl said the items such as the Rolex watch and the gun  
collection have been appraised in the thousands of dollars and are 
``very nominal'' compared with the outstanding debts of the estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was killed on Christmas Day 1989, when a pickup truck he  
was a passenger in struck a culvert near Binghamton. The driver of 
the truck, family friend William Reedy, was convicted of a 
misdemeanor charge of driving with a blood-alcohol content of more 
than 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Jilluann Martin and Billy Martin's children split a  
settlement reached with the Ford Motor Co. and Reedy's insurance 
company over the accident. At that time, papers in Broome County 
Surrogate Court detailed cash flow problems that the Martins had 
when he died. At the time, the couple was $941,233 in debt to 
credit card companies and the IRS. 
</P>
<P>
	The Martins' home outside Binghamton was not ruled part of Billy  
Martin's estate. The 5,200-square-foot structure on 144 acres was 
sold for $250,000 last summer, and Jilluann Martin kept that money, 
her lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's ruling largely upheld a determination by the  
Surrogate's Court about the dispensing of the Martin heirlooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Raymond Schlather, a lawyer for Martin's children, was not  
immediately available to comment on the ruling. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:31:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monica's Career May Benefit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After the mess she helped make at the White  
House, who would hire Monica Lewinsky now? 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, she might find more success than you'd think.  
Employment experts say that with a little image polishing, she 
could have a future in fashion, media, public relations, women's 
issues, even the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her name is a gold mine,'' says Marty Nemko, a career  
counselor in Oakland, Calif. ``I would want her as my 
spokeswoman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She'd be great in public relations,'' adds Nick Corcodilos,  
who runs the Ask the Headhunter job-search Web site, citing her 
ability to stick to her message through fierce interrogation. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal aside, Ms. Lewinsky has exhibited some pretty poor  
work habits. Her e-mails and letters were riddled with spelling 
errors. She was not always truthful and showed signs of petulance 
and laziness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to have to work for this position,'' she groused  
as Clinton's associates pounded the pavement to find her a job. ``I 
just want it to be given to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet she has also offered glimpses of the ambitious young woman  
who used a family connection to secure a White House internship in 
1995. By the time President Clinton's impeachment trial wound to a 
close, U.S. senators were fairly gushing about her poise and 
intelligence. 
</P>
<P>
	Her best bet might be in a very public sort of job.  
</P>
<P>
	``In the entertainment industry, for example, it really doesn't  
matter if you're good famous or bad famous,'' says Laura Berman 
Fortgang, author of the career advice book ``Take Yourself to the 
Top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are plenty of precedents. Marv Albert, the sports  
announcer who lost his job with NBC in 1997 after he admitted 
biting a woman during a sexual encounter, is back in broadcasting. 
Donna Rice, whose romance with Gary Hart helped end his 
presidential campaign 1987, modeled blue jeans for a while and now 
crusades against Internet pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, Ms. Lewinsky could hit the lecture circuit, offering  
lessons to young women about how to avoid her mistakes. ``I could 
see her becoming a powerful speaker,'' Fortgang says. 
</P>
<P>
	She might even find a job asking questions instead of answering  
them. Barbara Walters, during her daytime talk show ``The View,'' 
invited Ms. Lewinsky on Wednesday to audition for a slot as a host 
on the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Others suggest that the impeccably dressed young woman who  
picked out ties for the president might do well in the fashion 
world, or that she turn the tables on the lawyers who pried into 
her personal life by becoming an attorney herself. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing is sure: She's highly unlikely to slip into a  
low-profile position befitting a former intern with a bachelor's 
degree from an undistinguished liberal arts college. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine if you came to work one morning and found her in the  
next cubicle,'' says Cathleen Faerber, president of the Wellesley 
Group, a headhunting firm in Lake Zurich, Ill. ``Her presence would 
be so disruptive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a while anyway, Ms. Lewinsky's main job will be promoting  
her book, ``Monica's Story,'' written by Andrew Morton with her 
cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	She will split a $1.6 million advance with Morton, who also  
chronicled the life of Princess Diana. More media deals are sure to 
follow. But with legal bills estimated at $2 million, she may need 
to scale back the lifestyle that has included sumptuous restaurant 
meals, stays in fancy hotels and house calls from her hairdresser. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think she's going to walk right into a $90,000 job  
somewhere,'' Faerber says. ``But there is light at the end of the 
tunnel for Monica.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
