<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Pressure, Senility Linked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Treating high blood pressure in middle age can  
lower the risk of small, ``silent'' strokes that cause senility in 
later years, researchers say. 
</P>
<P>
	Among 414 men studied from middle age into their 70s, even  
moderately high blood pressure -- and to a lesser extent, smoking, 
drinking and diabetes -- were linked to faster aging of the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The take-home message is, if you've got high blood pressure or  
you smoke or you drink, go see your doctor and treat them,'' said 
lead author Dr. Charles DeCarli, director of the Alzheimer's 
Disease Center at the University of Kansas. ``If you have risk 
factors and don't treat them, your brain will be a decade older 
when you hit 70.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study was published in this month's issue of Stroke, a  
journal of the American Heart Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at five health centers conducted brain scans of men  
who had taken part in a study of twins that dated to 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers looked at cardiovascular disease, including  
strokes and small, temporary strokes called transient ischemic 
attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The men with strokes were the same age as the other subjects but  
had consistently registered higher blood pressure while in their 
40s. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who had suffered strokes had more than three times as much  
damaged white matter in their brains as the other men. 
</P>
<P>
	``People with damaged white matter slow down. They have more  
difficulty doing complicated things,'' DeCarli said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study has important implications for the aging U.S.  
population, said Dr. Edgar J. Kenton, a professor of clinical 
neurology at Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia and a 
member of the American Heart Association's stroke council. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our population is living longer, and we're starting to see  
that one of the major causes of dementia may no longer be 
Alzheimer's but may be these little strokes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We better start looking at middle-aged people who are  
hypertensive and treat them sooner rather than wait until someone 
shows signs of dementia.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
