<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Feb. Retail Sales Beat Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at the nation's biggest retailers topped  
expectations in February as the U.S. economy continued strong. Not 
only were consumers buying up discounted winter merchandise, there 
was also great demand for full-priced spring goods as well. The 
healthy results pleased merchants who had anticipated that 
consumers would scale back their spending in 1999 amid expectations 
that global financial turmoil would slow down U.S. economic growth. 
The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer of 
sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was up 
4.5 percent in February. It rose 6.4 percent in January and was up 
5.3 percent in February 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Rise 1.7 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New orders to U.S. factories surged in January  
for the second consecutive month, perhaps signaling the start of a 
rebound in American manufacturing after a year of struggling with 
fallout from Asia's economic crisis. Orders increased 1.7 percent 
to a seasonally adjusted $349.6 billion following an even stronger 
2.3 percent increase in December, the Commerce Department said 
today. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Touch 10-Year Low  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing first-time  
applications for unemployment benefits fell last week and, for 
February, the average level of new applications reached a 10-year 
low. Jobless claims totaled a seasonally adjusted 286,000 last 
week, down 8,000 from the week before, the Labor Department said 
today. The four-week moving average of claims, which evens out the 
volatile weekly totals, declined to 290,750, from 293,000 for the 
four-week period ending a week earlier. That was the lowest average 
since February 1989 and reflected the continued strength of the 
American economy. The department was scheduled Friday to report the 
unemployment rate for February and, in advance, analysts believed 
it would hold at a 29-year low of 4.3 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Advance; Dow Up 97.26  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were higher at this afternoon although  
below their highest levels of the day, in a broad-based rally that 
included technology, retail, financial and energy shares. Just 
before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 97.26 at 
9,373.14. Earlier, it got as high as 9,448.66, up 172.78. Many 
broader stock indicators were higher as well, although the Nasdaq 
composite was down 7.34 at 2,257.86. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. has agreed to merge its Canadian  
operations with MetroNet Communications Corp., a local Canadian 
phone service supplier to businesses, in a deal that values 
MetroNet at least $2.3 billion. The deal announced today would 
enable the merged company to offer business customers in Canada 
everything from long-distance to Internet to local phone service. 
It would also extend AT&AMP;T's strategy of creating a one-stop shop 
for telecommunications. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Threatens To Veto Bank Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A financial overhaul bill proposed by Senate  
Banking Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, split the committee along 
partisan lines today. It faces a presidential veto because 
President Clinton believes the bill, which would lift the 
Depression-era barriers separating banks, securities firms and 
insurance companies, fails to protect consumers and would hurt 
community lending laws. The measure was adopted and sent to the 
full Senate by the Banking Committee, 11-9, with only the 
Republican senators supporting it. In principle, the Clinton 
administration supports legislation to overhaul the financial 
services laws. But the White House has threatened to veto several 
versions in recent years that took an approach it rejected. 

</P>
<P>
	US-EU Banana Trade Hassle Continues  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- EU Trade Commissioner Leon Brittan said today  
the United States Risks a major confrontation with its imposition 
of tariffs on $520 million worth of European goods in its banana 
dispute with the European Union. He added that any EU retaliation 
would be ``in accordance'' with rules of the World Trade 
Organization, the global referee of trade disputes. The Clinton 
administration yesterday began notifying U.S. importers that they 
now are liable for hefty tariffs on a wide variety of goods because 
of the long-running dispute involving European barriers on banana 
imports. 

</P>
<P>
	German Industry Fighting Tax Reform  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- The lower house of Germany's legislature  
passed a bill Thursday overhauling the country's tax system, 
increasing the burden on industry to allow relief for 
average-income families. Bitterly attacked by the conservative 
opposition and industry, the bill passed on the strength of 
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's center-left majority by 312-251 
votes, with 27 abstentions. The law includes cuts in personal 
income and corporate tax rates, but also scraps a string of 
corporate tax exemptions. 

</P>
<P>
	Online After-Hours Trading Planned  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long excluded from the world of after-hours  
trading, individual investors may now get the chance to react to 
late-breaking news when it occurs. Beginning this summer, a leading 
Internet brokerage will offer an evening trading session for its 
customers through a new electronic exchange named IndivEx. The move 
by Discover Brokerage, a unit of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., 
may be quite profitable considering how the soaring popularity of 
Internet trading has overwhelmed online trading systems at major 
firms in recent months. 

</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs To Vote on IPO  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The partners at Goldman Sachs Group LP, the last  
of Wall Street's large private investment banks, will vote next 
week on whether to sell a stake in the firm to the public. The 
firm's 220 partners are to vote on the deal Monday. If approved, it 
would clear the way for a stock sale of 10 to 15 percent of the 
firm in May or June. Goldman Sachs originally planned to go public 
last year but aborted its attempt in September because turmoil in 
financial markets scared off many investors and ate into Goldman's 
profits. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 8,000 to 286,000  
</P>
<P>
	Factory orders: up 1.7 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales: up 4.5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Unemployment  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Consumer credit  

</P>
