<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Marine Pilot Acquitted in Crash  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military jury acquitted a Marine  
pilot today of all charges that he recklessly flew his jet into an 
Italian gondola cable, killing 20 people more than a year ago. A 
whoop went up in the courtroom at the Camp Lejeune Marine base when 
the verdict was announced. Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, was charged 
with 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter and one count each of 
destroying government property, destroying private property, 
dereliction of duty and failure to plan the flight properly. The 
crash and its aftermath strained relations between the United 
States and Italy, a NATO ally. 

</P>
<P>
	Italy Stunned by Marine Acquittal  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italians were stunned and indignant today at the  
acquittal of a Marine pilot whose jet severed a cable, sending a 
gondola packed with 20 people to their deaths in the Italian Alps. 
``We had said before that U.S. justice couldn't handle the case, 
and we were right,'' said lawyer Giuseppe Pontrelli, head of a 
citizens' group formed after the Feb. 3, 1998, tragedy. ``We had 
largely predicted a verdict like this, it's not unexpected.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Book Goes on Sale  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The inner feelings of Monica Lewinsky on the  
President Clinton scandal are being unveiled in her book that is 
hitting stores today. Included in ``Monica's Story'' are her 
thoughts of hurling herself out a 10th floor window when 
prosecutors first confronted her about the affair; her abortion, 
the result of an affair with a fellow Pentagon worker in 1996 
before her relationship with Clinton ended; and her feeling now 
that Clinton is ``a much bigger liar than I ever thought.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Retired Justice Harry Blackmun Dies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The retired Supreme Court Justice who authored  
the 1973 Roe versus Wade decision that legalized abortion has died. 
Justice Harry Blackmun was 90. Blackmun served 24 years on the 
nation's highest court after being appointed in 1970 by President 
Richard Nixon. He retired in 1994. The lifelong Republican was 
considered a staunch conservative in his early days on the court, 
but by the time he retired he was considered its most liberal 
justice. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Addresses U.N.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is tantalizing New  
Yorkers who look at the first lady and see their next senator. But 
so far she's just keeping them guessing. On her second day in New 
York, Mrs. Clinton gave a speech at the United Nations about the 
upcoming Women's Rights Day and later was to host a preview of an 
HBO documentary on women in sports at a school in Manhattan. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Threatens To Veto Bank Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A financial overhaul bill proposed by Senate  
Banking Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, split the committee along 
partisan lines today. It faces a presidential veto because 
President Clinton believes the bill, which would lift the 
Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms and 
insurance companies, fails to protect consumers and would hurt 
community lending laws. The measure appeared headed for adoption by 
the Banking Committee with only the Republican senators supporting 
it. 

</P>
<P>
	Tourist Killers Make More Threats  
</P>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Ugandan troops are scouring the dense  
jungle near the Ugandan-Congo border where eight foreign tourists 
were killed by Hutu rebels. The rebels responsible for the killings 
are reportedly threatening further attacks. An FBI team, meanwhile, 
was in Kampala investigating the deaths of the two Americans among 
those killed Monday in remote campgrounds in southwestern Uganda's 
Impenetrable Forest where rare mountain gorillas live. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Higher; Dow Gains 143  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EST, the Dow industrials were  
up 143.98 to 9,419.86. NYSE advancers led decliners 1,616-1,165. 
The Nasdaq index was up 23.58 to 2,288.78. 

</P>
<P>
	Cablevision May Try To Buy Mets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan is reportedly  
negotiating to buy the Mets, after failing in his attempts to buy 
into the New York Yankees last year, according to published reports 
today. Dolan is believed to be offering $500 million to $600 
million for the team. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
