<DOCNO> APW19990304.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Marlins' Lowell Fighting Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) -- Florida Marlins third-base prospect  
Mike Lowell, recovering from surgery for testicular cancer, went to 
the ballpark for therapy Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell sat in the stands, soaked up some sunshine and watched  
the Marlins open their exhibition season with a 12-3 victory over 
the University of Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The power-hitting rookie hopes to join the Marlins before the  
end of spring training. He's unlikely to be ready for opening day 
April 5, but doctors say his chance of a full recovery is 
excellent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching baseball is a breath of fresh air,'' Lowell said. ``I  
just wanted to catch the game and see some guys play. It's good 
therapy, to say the least.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, 25, was diagnosed with cancer after a small mass was  
found during a routine physical exam. He underwent surgery Feb. 21 
and will start a short course of lose-dose radiation next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlins manager John Boles visited briefly with Lowell before  
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of gave everybody a boost to have him here,'' Boles  
said. ``He's a big part of us, and we're pleased he's doing so 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Lowell returns, he'll challenge veteran Kevin Orie for the  
starting job at third. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've wanted to play in the big leagues since I was 6 years  
old,'' Lowell said. ``Then someone tells me there's something that 
could threaten my life. 
</P>
<P>
	``It definitely puts things in perspective. You realize how  
precious baseball is and how meaningless baseball is. But since 
it's such a curable cancer, I'm really expecting to make a total 
recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell said he's walking free of pain, but doctors don't want  
him jogging yet. He said there's no way of knowing whether the 
radiation will make him ill, which would delay his return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm eager to get back, but I know it's a process,'' Lowell  
said. ``I'll deal with it. It's the hand I've been dealt. It wasn't 
the greatest hand, but I might have a couple of aces up my sleeve 
for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, who grew up in Miami, was acquired Feb. 1 from the New  
York Yankees for three pitching prospects. In the past two 
minor-league seasons he hit .309 with 56 home runs and 191 RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
