<DOCNO> APW19990304.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:32:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Lynx Reintroduction Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- State wildlife officials are revising the strategy  
for reintroducing the lynx to Colorado after the deaths of two cats 
released a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The lynx found dead last week were among five released Feb. 3 by  
the Colorado Division of Wildlife in the Rio Grande National Forest 
near South Fork, in southwestern Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The juvenile male and adult female apparently starved to death  
despite the presence of their favorite prey, snowshoe hares, 
officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that there will be mortality as there is in any  
reintroduction effort,'' said Gene Byrne, a biologist on the 
state's lynx recovery team. ``Some animals are going to do better 
than others in finding the best habitat and in hunting success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said recovery team members have decided to make two changes:  
wait longer to release female lynx and ensure all lynx released are 
adults. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to hold the females longer to ensure that they're  
well-fed before they are released,'' Byrne said. 
</P>
<P>
	The young lynx that died had tried and failed to kill a snowshoe  
hare and pine squirrel, a wildlife monitoring team reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The division plans to reintroduce about 50 more lynx by early  
spring and another 50 could be released next winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the program started, lynx were last seen in Colorado in  
1973, near Vail. Activists oppose Vail's current expansion plans, 
saying they will destroy lynx habitat. The Environmental Liberation 
Front referred to the animal when it claimed it set fires causing 
$12 million in damage at the ski area last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:45:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Keeps Interest Rates Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Europe's central bank left its  
benchmark interest rate unchanged at 3 percent Thursday despite new 
signs of trouble in Germany's economy, the largest in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns about worsening the euro's slide against the dollar, as  
well as the European Central Bank's determination not to be seen as 
giving in to political pressure, all argued against the bank 
lowering rates for the 11-nation bloc that uses the new currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank chief Wim Duisenberg told reporters after the regular  
policy-setting meeting that he was not concerned about the 
fledgling currency's drop against the dollar. The euro is down 
nearly 7 percent from its debut at $1.1668 at the beginning of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg said dip was due to the strength of the dollar,  
buoyed by the U.S. economy, and not due to any inherent weakness in 
the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at the level of the euro reached by now, it is  
more or less the level that the German mark had for most of last 
year,'' Duisenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, the news that rates remained unchanged dropped the  
euro below $1.08, surprising some economists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the currency markets were disappointed,'' said  
Peter Dixon, senior economist at Commerzbank. ``That's the 
difference between currency markets and economists. Economists tend 
to be more conservative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appeals by political leaders, most vocally German Finance  
Minister Oskar Lafontaine, to drop interest rates have taken on 
added urgency as Germany teeters on the brink of a recession. He 
argues that a crop would stimulate growth in Europe and create 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth has slowed in many European economies, but Germany's  
economy, heavily dependent on exports, actually shrunk 0.4 percent 
in last quarter of 1998, compared to 6.1 percent growth in the 
United States over the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
