<DOCNO> APW19990304.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:42:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders, NFL Case Over LA Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal judge dismissed most of a lawsuit  
between the Oakland Raiders and the NFL that includes a battle over 
who owns rights to the Los Angeles football market. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling, which was issued Tuesday and released Wednesday,  
does not end the legal battle between the Raiders and NFL. The 
Raiders immediately refiled their lawsuit in state court. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George H. King said neither the NFL nor the  
Raiders provided ``sufficient reasons for this court to provide a 
forum'' and dismissed most of the claims. 
</P>
<P>
	King said the dismissed claims should be heard in state court.  
However, on the issue of antitrust, the judge ruled that the 
Raiders' allegation had no merit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders claimed the NFL violated antitrust laws by refusing  
to schedule the Raiders' home games in Oakland for the 1994 season. 
</P>
<P>
	But to prove there was damage from the 1994 schedule, the  
Raiders would have had to shown that their ``relevant market'' was 
the San Francisco Bay area, King said. The team couldn't do this 
because, in 1994, they were still the Los Angeles Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling stems from a 1995 lawsuit in which the NFL sued the  
Raiders and owner Al Davis over territorial rights to the Los 
Angeles area, where the Raiders played for 13 years before 
returning to Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides claimed victory in King's ruling.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pure procedural motion that was made in federal court.  
Now what happened is we simply have to start over in the state 
court,'' Raiders lawyer Jack Quinn said. ``The claims of the 
Raiders are still the same -- they own control and have the rights 
to the Los Angeles market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders refiled their lawsuit in state court but dropped the  
antitrust allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL spokesman Greg Aiello declined comment. A league lawyer  
characterized the ruling as a boost for the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are delighted with the results. It establishes what we have  
always contended -- that there are no antitrust violations involved 
in our actions with the Raiders,'' Los Angeles-based lawyer Frank 
Rothman said. ``It's just another big win for the league and 
another loss for Davis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders moved from Oakland to Los Angeles in 1982. The NFL  
sued the Raiders over a failed plan to play in Oakland in 1994, 
when the Northridge earthquake damaged the Los Angeles Coliseum 
earlier that year. The league also sued over revenue-sharing 
discrepancies after the team moved to Oakland the following year. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL claimed the team scheduled games in Oakland without  
league approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders countersued, claiming the league blocked the team's  
1994 move to Oakland, interfered with the move the following year 
and destroyed negotiations between the team and Hollywood Park in 
nearby Inglewood. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations to build a new stadium in Hollywood Park fizzled  
and the team decided to return to Oakland in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Quinn called the federal judge's ruling ``unfortunate'' because  
the team originally wanted to file in state court, but the NFL 
pushed for it to be filed in federal court. He said 2 1/2 years have 
been wasted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We probably could have built the same stadium and played  
there,'' Quinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the complaint, the team alleges that the NFL ``engaged in a  
concerted course of conduct'' to keep the Raiders out of the Los 
Angeles area. The team claims the league reneged on promises to 
fund part of the deal to bring the team to the park. The Raiders 
also want the NFL to pay the team the differential between the more 
profitable Los Angeles market and Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	Raiders spokesman Mike Taylor did not immediately return a phone  
call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles has been without a franchise since the Raiders went  
back to Oakland and the Rams moved to St. Louis before the 1995 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Two opposing groups in Los Angeles are bidding for the expansion  
franchise along with their own stadium proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is expected set up an expansion vote at an owner's  
meeting in Phoenix on March 14-18. A new team could begin play by 
2002. Houston is the other top contender for expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
