<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Hundley Says He's Healthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Catcher Todd Hundley has a message for  
all interested fans of the Los Angeles Dodgers: He is absolutely 
not a question mark for the upcoming season. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of weeks ago, maybe. But not now.  
</P>
<P>
	Hundley blew out his right elbow in September 1997 while playing  
for the New York Mets, and underwent reconstructive surgery about a 
week later. Following a frustrating 1998 season, he was traded to 
the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm back, man, I'm back,'' Hundley said Thursday at the team's  
training facility. ``There's no pain, knock on wood. The joint is 
pain-free. The elbow feels the best it has in six years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundley, 29, admitted that while he may have said otherwise,  
like after the Mets traded him to the Dodgers during the offseason, 
he remained a question mark in his own mind until recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really get over the hump until about the third day of  
spring training, after getting as many swings as I got, throwing as 
much as I did,'' he said. ``You don't know it until you really do 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are the skills still there? Until you get out and do it, you  
don't know. Now, I'm good to go. I'm no different than anyone else 
-- none whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundley won't appear in an exhibition game for about a week, but  
said it's not because he can't play. The Dodgers open the 
exhibition season Friday against the St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Davey and I discussed it,'' Hundley said, referring to manager  
Davey Johnson. ``I just feel I need the practice more. I had bad 
mechanics, that's why I blew out my elbow. It's my decision and 
Davey's decision. It's not because I'm hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't missed a step. I haven't been limited in any way.  
I'll be throwing more on the practice field than I would in 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundley, a switch-batter, hit 41 homers for the Mets in 1996 to  
set a big-league single-season record for catchers. His elbow 
bothered him throughout the 1997 season before he blew it out. 
</P>
<P>
	When he returned to the Mets last July, they had already  
acquired Mike Piazza. Hundley hit just .161 with 55 strikeouts in 
124 at-bats, and also spent some time in the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	He was used in left field by the Mets, an experiment that turned  
out to be a fielding disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't wish this (the surgery and then last season) on my  
worst enemy,'' Hundley said. ``(The surgery) was almost like the 
plague. You don't want to have that surgery, it was the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers hope Hundley can catch at least 120 games this year.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's been fine, he's done everything,'' Johnson said. ``If you  
saw him today, we took infield, he threw the ball very well. We 
want to take it easy on him. There's plenty of time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long spring, I know what he can do.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
