<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Demonstrates Staying Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is demonstrating more evidence of  
staying power. Retailers reported strong sales, orders for factory 
goods rebounded and applications for unemployment benefits hit a 
10-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	``They economy is firing on all cylinders. It's getting a boost  
from increased tax refunds and manufacturing is showing signs of 
life, especially because aircraft and high-tech goods are beginning 
to sell better in Asia,'' said economist Sung Won Sohn of Wells 
Fargo &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination fueled a stock-market rally. The Dow Jones  
industrial average climbed 192 points to close at 9,467, erasing 
much of this week's and last week's losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists, who once were predicting a significant slowdown in  
growth this year, from last year's robust 3.9 percent, are starting 
to revise their forecasts higher. This week, a 34-member panel 
assembled by the National Association for Business Economics 
projected 3 percent growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economy is ... continuing to make a monkey of economists  
that were looking for a slowdown,'' said Robert Brusca of Nikko 
Securities Co. International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he cautioned that temporary factors, including a stretch  
of mild weather, may be responsible for some of the recent 
strength. It permitted fewer layoffs than usual at construction 
firms ``and it may be the fine weather has encouraged people to get 
out and shop a little more,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax refunds, up 18 percent through Feb. 26 from last year,  
according to the Internal Revenue Service, will help support 
spending over the next month or two. But after that higher 
long-term interest rates could start to erode the economy's vigor. 
</P>
<P>
	The average rate on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages jumped to 7.06  
percent this week, the highest level since the end of May, said 
Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. Already, that's sharply cut the 
number of mortgage refinancings, a key factor underpinning consumer 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thursday's reports, the Commerce Department said factory  
orders increased a seasonally adjusted 1.7 percent in January 
following an even stronger 2.3 percent increase in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the nation's biggest retail chains reported  
higher-than-expected sales in February. Not only were consumers 
buying up discounted winter merchandise, there was great demand for 
full-priced spring goods as well. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the Labor Department said the number of Americans filing  
first-time applications for unemployment benefits fell 8,000 last 
week to a seasonally adjusted 286,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average of claims, which evens out the  
volatile weekly totals, declined from 293,000 for the four-week 
period ending a week earlier to 290,750, the lowest since February 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of January's strength at factories was concentrated in  
aircraft orders, which doubled from December, the largest increase 
in five years. Excluding the volatile transportation sector, orders 
fell 0.3 in January, the first decline in three months. 
</P>
<P>
	But aircraft wasn't the only high point. Orders jumped 4.9  
percent for electronic equipment, including a 13 percent increase 
for communications equipment. Computer and office equipment orders 
fell 4.8 percent; steel orders, 8 percent, and engines and 
turbines, 27.3 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
