<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clouds hung over the northern states this morning, bringing the  
promise of rain and snow from the Pacific Northwest across to 
northern New England. Pleasant weather was expected across the 
southern tier. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure moving from the Northeast into Canada was allowing  
colder air to filter into the United States, meaning 4 to 8 inches 
of snow in the eastern Great Lakes and rain changing to snow in New 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	Morning snow was accompanied by thunder in Buffalo and  
thunderstorms rattled the region between Boston and New York City. 
Snow-blowing winds of 20 to 30 mph, with gusts above 40 mph, could 
bring visibility to below a half-mile across the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, scattered snow was falling this morning from the northern  
Plains to the Ohio Valley. A few inches were expected to 
accumulate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Northwest was again getting rain and snow, but not  
as much as in recent days. Up to 6 inches of snow was expected in 
the higher Cascades, and only a few inches were forecast for the 
northern Rockies. Rain should remain light in coastal Washington 
and Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Southeast, bludgeoned by storms Wednesday, was looking  
forward to partly cloudy, dry weather today, though morning winds 
were still brisk. 
</P>
<P>
	Winds could reach 30 mph from Kansas to Texas later today,  
though partly cloudy skies and dry weather should remain in the 
central and southern Plains, as well as in the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast in the 20s from the northern Plains to  
the eastern Great Lakes; the 30s from the inland Northwest to 
northern New England; the 60s to the 80s from southern California 
to the deep South; and the 40s and 50s elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures Wednesday in the lower 48 states ranged from 91 in  
Thermal, Calif., to 2 below zero in Roseau, Minn., and Devils Lake, 
N.D. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
