<DOCNO> APW19990304.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:54:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hunt for Rebels Continues in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BWINDI NATIONAL PARK, Uganda (AP) -- Hundreds of Ugandan troops  
spread out through the dense rain forests of eastern Congo on 
Thursday in a huge manhunt for the Rwandan rebels who slaughtered 
foreign tourists. At least 15 rebels were reported killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The search came as rebels warned in leaflets that they would  
launch further attacks. The report by Uganda's private Central 
Broadcasting Service did not say whether the threat was 
specifically aimed at foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Six hundred Ugandan forces were joined by a number of Rwandan  
troops and Ugandan police, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint forces killed 15 of the rebels Wednesday in Congo's  
Rutshuru county, 12 miles southwest of Bwindi National Park, which 
the tourists were visiting, said Lt. Col. Benan Biraaro, divisional 
commander of Uganda's southwestern region. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pursuing them and we are going to kill them,'' he said.  
``It won't be a day, it won't be a week, but we will get them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biraaro said rebels were seen wearing clothing they had  
obviously stolen from the tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also reinforced troops on the Uganda border, trying to  
close in on the Congo-based rebels who slaughtered the tourists 
with machetes and axes in southwestern Uganda's Impenetrable 
Forest. The tourists were there to view rare mountain gorillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Roadblocks were set up in two villages north of where the eight  
tourists were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI team was in Kampala, the capital, investigating the  
deaths of the two Americans. Four Britons and two New Zealanders 
also were killed. Six other tourists were seized but survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives from Scotland Yard were flying to Kampala on Thursday  
night to help investigate the massacre. Simon Bond, a British 
Embassy spokesman in Kampala, said the bodies of the slain tourists 
would be flown out Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the State Department said the bodies of the  
Americans -- Rob Haubner, 48, and his wife, Susan Miller, 42, both 
employees of Intel Corp. -- were to be returned to Portland, Ore., 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's government-owned New Vision newspaper said the army  
arrested a suspect who had apparently helped brief rebels on the 
positions of tourists in the park before the attack that began 
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper, citing an unidentified source, said several  
people had been heard helping the rebels before the attack. ``They 
seemed to know which tents were occupied and by who. They only 
missed one (tent),'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The simultaneous raids marred several campgrounds, leaving them  
looted and burned. Papers scattered along the ground Thursday 
included a receipt from a London cinema. 
</P>
<P>
	The charred frame of a vehicle in which one Ugandan park ranger  
was burned to death after being shot by rebels flanked the park 
gate north of the camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedda Turyananuka, a park ranger, said he opened fire on the  
rebels but soon was overpowered and fled into the forest. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's president, Yoweri Museveni, promised Wednesday to hunt  
down the rebels and appealed for help from the international 
community. He also delivered a harsh ultimatum to the insurgents. 
</P>
<P>
	``These bandits are not able to permanently engage us because  
they will be wiped out,'' he said. ``Now that they have invited us, 
I think they are going to find out that it was not a wise 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels were among Hutu fighters who fled Rwanda in 1994  
after killing more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically 
moderate Hutus in a government-orchestrated genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hutu fighters, who have been carrying out cross-border raids  
from bases in eastern Congo, are angry at the United States, 
Britain and Uganda for providing aid to the Rwandan government. 
</P>
<P>
	American-born pilot and guide Mark Ross, credited with  
negotiating the release of the six survivors, told The Associated 
Press before leaving for Kenya that he would return once the park 
is deemed safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a beautiful forest, and the people that ran it were  
exceptionally friendly and knowledgeable,'' he said Thursday. The 
attack ``was a really sad, freaky and, I think, unpredictable 
occurrence, unlike the wildlife which is quite predictable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tourists were abducted at campgrounds on the edge of Bwindi  
National Park, the starting point for visitors hoping to glimpse 
the 320 rare mountain gorillas made famous by the 1988 film 
``Gorillas in the Mist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Museveni admitted partial responsibility for the bloodshed,  
saying park rangers should have known an attack was possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:54:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hunt for Rebels Continues in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BWINDI NATIONAL PARK, Uganda (AP) -- Hundreds of Ugandan troops  
spread out through the dense rain forests of eastern Congo on 
Thursday in a huge manhunt for the Rwandan rebels who slaughtered 
foreign tourists. At least 15 rebels were reported killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The search came as rebels warned in leaflets that they would  
launch further attacks. The report by Uganda's private Central 
Broadcasting Service did not say whether the threat was 
specifically aimed at foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Six hundred Ugandan forces were joined by a number of Rwandan  
troops and Ugandan police, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint forces killed 15 of the rebels Wednesday in Congo's  
Rutshuru county, 12 miles southwest of Bwindi National Park, which 
the tourists were visiting, said Lt. Col. Benan Biraaro, divisional 
commander of Uganda's southwestern region. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pursuing them and we are going to kill them,'' he said.  
``It won't be a day, it won't be a week, but we will get them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biraaro said rebels were seen wearing clothing they had  
obviously stolen from the tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also reinforced troops on the Uganda border, trying to  
close in on the Congo-based rebels who slaughtered the tourists 
with machetes and axes in southwestern Uganda's Impenetrable 
Forest. The tourists were there to view rare mountain gorillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Roadblocks were set up in two villages north of where the eight  
tourists were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI team was in Kampala, the capital, investigating the  
deaths of the two Americans. Four Britons and two New Zealanders 
also were killed. Six other tourists were seized but survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives from Scotland Yard were flying to Kampala on Thursday  
night to help investigate the massacre. Simon Bond, a British 
Embassy spokesman in Kampala, said the bodies of the slain tourists 
would be flown out Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the State Department said the bodies of the  
Americans -- Rob Haubner, 48, and his wife, Susan Miller, 42, both 
employees of Intel Corp. -- were to be returned to Portland, Ore., 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's government-owned New Vision newspaper said the army  
arrested a suspect who had apparently helped brief rebels on the 
positions of tourists in the park before the attack that began 
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper, citing an unidentified source, said several  
people had been heard helping the rebels before the attack. ``They 
seemed to know which tents were occupied and by who. They only 
missed one (tent),'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The simultaneous raids marred several campgrounds, leaving them  
looted and burned. Papers scattered along the ground Thursday 
included a receipt from a London cinema. 
</P>
<P>
	The charred frame of a vehicle in which one Ugandan park ranger  
was burned to death after being shot by rebels flanked the park 
gate north of the camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedda Turyananuka, a park ranger, said he opened fire on the  
rebels but soon was overpowered and fled into the forest. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's president, Yoweri Museveni, promised Wednesday to hunt  
down the rebels and appealed for help from the international 
community. He also delivered a harsh ultimatum to the insurgents. 
</P>
<P>
	``These bandits are not able to permanently engage us because  
they will be wiped out,'' he said. ``Now that they have invited us, 
I think they are going to find out that it was not a wise 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels were among Hutu fighters who fled Rwanda in 1994  
after killing more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically 
moderate Hutus in a government-orchestrated genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hutu fighters, who have been carrying out cross-border raids  
from bases in eastern Congo, are angry at the United States, 
Britain and Uganda for providing aid to the Rwandan government. 
</P>
<P>
	American-born pilot and guide Mark Ross, credited with  
negotiating the release of the six survivors, told The Associated 
Press before leaving for Kenya that he would return once the park 
is deemed safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a beautiful forest, and the people that ran it were  
exceptionally friendly and knowledgeable,'' he said Thursday. The 
attack ``was a really sad, freaky and, I think, unpredictable 
occurrence, unlike the wildlife which is quite predictable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tourists were abducted at campgrounds on the edge of Bwindi  
National Park, the starting point for visitors hoping to glimpse 
the 320 rare mountain gorillas made famous by the 1988 film 
``Gorillas in the Mist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Museveni admitted partial responsibility for the bloodshed,  
saying park rangers should have known an attack was possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
