<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Suspect Refuses To Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The man accused of killing two policemen in  
the U.S. Capitol has been returned to the District of Columbia from 
Missouri after refusing for a month to talk with psychiatrists. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the advice of my attorneys I have no comment,'' Russell  
Eugene Weston Jr. said Wednesday to repeated questions from U.S. 
District Judge Emmet Sullivan, who plans to proceed with a 
competency hearing on April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan declined at this time to hear a preliminary assessment  
from a government psychiatrist. Doctors at the Medical Facility for 
Federal Prisoners in Springfield, Mo., where Weston was being 
examined, failed repeatedly in their efforts to interview him. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston, 42, allegedly gunned down officers John Gibson and Jacob  
J. Chestnut in a corridor of the Capitol on July 24. He was 
returned to the District of Columbia on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government sought to have the competency hearing moved up,  
citing Weston's lack of cooperation even against the advice of his 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston was examined by a court-appointed government psychiatrist  
last October who determined that he was incompetent to stand trial 
and recommended indefinite hospitalization. Sullivan, however, 
ordered a second evaluation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
