<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:56:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Wants Rayburn Items Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONHAM, Texas (AP) -- For the 17 years that Texan Sam Rayburn was  
speaker of the U.S. House, he practically owned the office. Now the 
House wants the office back. 
</P>
<P>
	The House is demanding the Sam Rayburn Library and Museum return  
an enormous crystal chandelier, the original marble House speaker's 
rostrum and a nearly 3,000-year-old urn that was a gift to the 
speaker from the Greek government. Its estimated value: $3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those items belong to the American people. They belong in a  
place where all the people in the country can view them,'' said 
Jason Poblete, spokesman for the House Administration Committee in 
Washington. ``Not everyone can travel to the Rayburn museum to view 
those items.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House is also trying to reclaim antique furnishings and  
other items that other speakers took after they left office. But 
the fight has become particularly bitter in Bonham, the small 
northeastern Texas hometown of one of the most powerful politicians 
in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say the suggestion that Rayburn took the items improperly  
is especially insulting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Rayburn was one of the greatest men who ever lived. He had  
more integrity than anyone I've known in my life,'' said H.G. 
Dulaney, director of the Rayburn library in this town of about 
6,000 people near the Oklahoma state line. ``He was the most 
revered man in Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Sam'' served in Congress for 48 years, from 1913 until his  
death in 1961. His career in Washington spanned the administrations 
of eight presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrat co-wrote such landmark laws as the Federal  
Communications Act, the Rural Electrification Act and the 
Securities and Exchange Act, and played a major role in passing the 
New Deal. A master parliamentarian, he was Lyndon B. Johnson's 
mentor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last August, then-House Clerk Robin H. Carle wrote to the  
Rayburn library, demanding the items' return. Ms. Carle said 
Rayburn should have turned over gifts from foreign governments, 
like the urn, to the State Department and then gotten congressional 
approval to take them back. She also charged that he failed to 
obtain proper authorization to take the other items. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Carleton, director of the University of Texas Center for  
American History, of which the library is a part, insisted the 
state has the proper documentation. The library was established in 
1957, before Rayburn had even left office. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, members of the House clerk's office have  
also spoken with custodians of artifacts taken by former Speakers 
Tip O'Neill and John McCormack of Massachusetts, who have died, Tom 
Foley of Washington and Carl Albert of Oklahoma. Former Speaker Jim 
Wright of Texas offered to return some items last year. All five 
were Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort to reclaim the items began after the Republicans won  
control of the House in 1995 and took an inventory. Some Democrats 
have decried the effort as partisan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's petty beyond belief,'' former Texas Democratic Party  
chairman Bob Slagle, whose hometown of Sherman was in Rayburn's 
congressional district, told The Dallas Morning News. ``I guess 
when you haven't had power in a long time, it is tough to learn to 
use it with any discretion or honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dulaney, 80, who worked as a secretary for Rayburn and has been  
with the library since it opened, said the artifacts' absence would 
be obvious. 
</P>
<P>
	The rostrum, which stood on the dais from 1857 until 1950 when  
the House underwent renovations, is in the library's front hall. 
The glittering chandelier -- which once hung in the White House but 
was moved to the speaker's office because President Franklin D. 
Roosevelt thought the crystals were too noisy -- now lights a 
replica of Rayburn's office. The brown urn sits atop a bookshelf in 
a glass case. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaking his head, Dulaney said, ``They've got so much to see in  
Washington, I don't know why they want this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In December, Ms. Carle resigned as House clerk after she was  
accused of using a staff member to perform personal tasks and using 
a government credit card for her own purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Carleton, the UT Center for American History director: ``We  
are pleased to have discussions with whoever becomes the clerk when 
they get that straightened out up there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 08:47:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice: No White House Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House did not apply any pressure to  
the Justice Department before a surprise reversal on whether the 
law that led to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation 
should stay or go, a top Justice official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration withdrew its support for the  
independent counsel law Tuesday, saying the Watergate-inspired 
investigations statute failed its goal of removing politics from 
investigations of senior administration officials. Deputy Attorney 
General Eric Holder said then that Congress should let the law 
expire on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	White House lawyer Charles F.C. Ruff asked for a day or two to  
``think about'' that position beforehand, ``but they had no 
substantive role in the formulation of the change in policy or the 
positions that I took two days ago,'' Holder said during the 
department's weekly press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Holder convened a task force at the Justice Department months  
ago to consider them future of the law, which the Clinton 
administration supported the last time it was up for a five-year 
extension. At first, even Attorney General Janet Reno did not know 
about the task force, Holder said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted her to be in a position to be able to say in these  
press availabilities, among other places, that, you know, it was 
something ... she had not been involved in,'' Holder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno, who has appointed seven independent counsels during her  
six-year tenure, has been the frequent target of congressional 
critics such as Sen. Orrin Hatch, who claims she has been biased 
toward the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of weeks ago, Holder said, he told Reno the task force  
had concluded the law could not be fixed and should be scrapped. 
She signed off, and the Justice Department made that recommendation 
to the White House in a meeting with Ruff, Holder said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And all he said was, `Let me think about this for a day or  
so,' ... and then they came back to us and said that the testimony 
that I was going to give had been cleared. '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 08:47:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Blackmun Opinions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Excerpts from Supreme Court opinions written by Justice Harry A.  
Blackmun. 

</P>
<P>
	From Roe vs. Wade in 1973:  
</P>
<P>
	One's philosophy, one's experience, one's exposure to the raw  
edges of human existence, one's religious training, one's attitude 
toward life and family and their values and the moral standards one 
establishes and seeks to observe, are all likely to influence and 
color one's thinking and conclusions about abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Our task, of course, is to resolve the issue by constitutional  
measurement, free of emotion and of predilection. 
</P>
<P>
	A right of personal privacy ... is broad enough to encompass a  
woman's decision whether or not to terminate her pregnancy. 

</P>
<P>
	From Bates vs. Arizona State Bar in 1977:  
</P>
<P>
	We are confronted with the arguments directed explicitly toward  
the regulation of advertising by licensed attorneys ... whether the 
state may prevent the publication in a newspaper of (a) truthful 
advertisement concerning the availability and terms of routine 
legal services. We rule simply that the flow of such information 
may not be restrained. 

</P>
<P>
	From Santoski vs. Kramer in 1984:  
</P>
<P>
	Under New York law, the state may terminate, over parental  
objection, the rights of parents in their natural child upon a 
finding that the child is ``permanently neglected.'' (The law) 
requires that only a ``fair preponderance of the evidence'' support 
that finding. 
</P>
<P>
	We hold that the due process clause of the Fourteenth Amendment  
demands more than this. Before a state may sever completely and 
irrevocably the rights of parents in their natural child, due 
process requires that the state support its allegations by at least 
clear and convincing evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The fundamental liberty interest of natural parents in the care,  
custody and management of their child does not evaporate simply 
because they have not been model parents or have lost temporary 
custody of their child to the state. Even when blood relationships 
are strained, parents retain a vital interest in preventing the 
irretrievable destruction of their family life. 

</P>
<P>
	From Garcia vs. San Antonio Metropolitan Transit Authority in  
1985: 
</P>
<P>
	We revisit (a 1976 decision in which the court) ruled that the  
(Constitution's) commerce clause does not empower Congress to 
enforce the minimum-wage and overtime provisions of the Fair Labor 
Standards Act against the states in areas of traditional functions. 
</P>
<P>
	In the present case, a federal district court concluded that  
municipal ownership and operation of a mass-transit system is a 
traditional governmental function ... exempt from the obligations 
imposed by the FLSA. The attempt to draw the boundaries of state 
regulatory immunity in terms of traditional governmental functions 
is not only unworkable but also inconsistent with established 
principles of federalism. (The 1976 ruling) accordingly is 
overruled. 

</P>
<P>
	From his concurring opinion in Casey vs. Planned Parenthood in  
1992: 
</P>
<P>
	Just when so many expected the darkness to fall, the flame has  
grown bright. In brief, five members of this court today recognized 
that the Constitution protects a woman's right to terminate her 
pregnancy in its early stages. 
</P>
<P>
	While there is much to be praised about our democracy, our  
country since its founding has recognized that there are certain 
fundamental liberties that are not to be left to the whims of an 
election. A woman's right to reproductive choice is one of those 
fundamental liberties. Accordingly, that liberty need not seek 
refuge at the ballot box. 
</P>
<P>
	I am 83 years old. I cannot remain on this court forever, and  
when I do step down, the confirmation process for my successor may 
well focus on the issue before us today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins' Barrasso Breaks Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANONSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Pittsburgh Penguins goalie Tom Barrasso  
learned Thursday he might be done for the regular season with a 
broken hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrasso was injured while gloving a shot from Montreal's Shayne  
Corson on Wednesday, and X-rays revealed a broken hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury leaves Peter Skudra the Penguins' only goalie with  
any appreciable NHL experience. Backing up Skudra will be rookie 
Jean-Sebastien Aubin, who has started four games, finished three, 
and mopped up parts of five others during the first month of the 
season when both Skudra and Barrasso were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Skudra's first big start will come Friday in Pittsburgh against  
the Edmonton Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any injury, and certainly one to a key guy like Tommy ... is  
going to be tough,'' Penguins coach Kevin Constantine said after 
practice Thursday. ``For us and for him, 4-6 weeks is a long time, 
and I'm sure that's a degree of frustration for Tommy because he's 
had a few injuries this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a guy who's up there in terms of wins in this league, and  
he wishes he could be here to contribute to our games down the 
stretch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Constantine said Barrasso should be ready for the playoffs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kurdish Suicide Bomber Kills Self </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A Kurdish suicide bomber killed herself  
and wounded three civilians outside a police station Thursday in 
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	Local officials said they believe the bomber was a Kurdish  
guerrilla protesting the capture of Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the 
rebel Kurdistan Workers Party or PKK. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the wounded were primary schoolchildren, who suffered  
minor injuries, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing came one day after the PKK's political wing said the  
rebels would escalate their war for autonomy in southeastern 
Turkey. It took place in the town of Batman, the scene of a 
shootout between Ocalan supporters and police two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Batman bombing was the first suicide attack since Turkish  
commandos captured Ocalan in Kenya on Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan is awaiting trial on treason charges on the heavily  
guarded prison island of Imrali in the Sea of Marmara. 
</P>
<P>
	The Council of Europe said Thursday that its delegation for the  
prevention of torture was allowed to speak privately with Ocalan 
this week when it visited the prison island. It gave no details. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Thursday, the jailed leader of the small leftist  
Worker's Party, Dogu Perincek, was sentenced to a year in prison 
for separatist propaganda. 
</P>
<P>
	Perincek also faces charges of aiding the PKK, which carry 20  
years of prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The PKK has fought Turkish troops for an independent Kurdish  
state since 1984, a conflict that has cost 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0237 </DOCNO>
