<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feb. Retail Sales Beat Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at the nation's biggest retailers topped  
expectations in February, as the continued strength of the U.S. 
economy encouraged Americans to do lots of shopping last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only were consumers buying up discounted winter merchandise,  
there was also great demand for full-priced spring goods as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't just good. It's better than good, well above what  
we had expected,'' Michael Niemira, a retail analyst at Bank of 
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, said about today's sales reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Most merchants fared well in February, especially discount  
chains, such as Wal-Mart and Target, and specialty clothing stores, 
including the Gap and Limited. 
</P>
<P>
	The only weakness was spotted at the moderately priced  
department stores, such as J.C. Penney and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., 
which have lost business to the lower-priced discounters. 
</P>
<P>
	The healthy results pleased merchants who had anticipated that  
consumers would scale back their spending in 1999 amid expectations 
that global financial turmoil would slow down U.S. economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	But the economy continues to rage, and unemployment and  
inflation levels remain at the lowest levels in years. That's made 
consumers confident about their personal finances and has raised 
their eagerness to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately today, the Labor Department reported the number of  
Americans filing first-time applications for unemployment benefits 
fell by 8,000 to 286,000 last week, and the average level of new 
applications reached a 10-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts, however, warned that any signs of economic weakness in  
coming months could cause a sharp downturn in consumer spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, there is strong consumer confidence now, but I am still  
very cautious about the rest of the spring season,'' said Walter 
Loeb, who runs the retail consulting firm Loeb Associates. ``It 
gets much harder from here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	February is the first month of most retailers' fiscal year.  
</P>
<P>
	The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer  
of sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was 
up 4.5 percent in February. It rose 6.4 percent in January and was 
up 5.3 percent in February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, reported sales from  
stores open at least a year rose 10.3 percent from a year earlier, 
while total sales were up 17.7 percent. sales from stores open at 
least a year, known as same-store sales, are considered the most 
accurate measure of a retailer's strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Other retailers' reports:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sears: Same-store sales up 0.8 percent, total sales down 2.6  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kmart: Same-store sales up 5.8 percent, total sales up 7.4  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney: Same-store department store sales fell 0.4  
percent, same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores up 12 percent, total 
sales rose 5.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson: Same-store sales up 8.3 percent, total sales up  
13.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated: Same-store sales rose 1 percent, total sale up 0.5  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores: Same-store sales up 3.7 percent, total  
sales up 8.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited: Same-store sales up 13 percent, total sales rose 5  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gap: Same-store sales up 12 percent, total sales up 32 percent.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
