<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:53:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Offers Online Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch introduced online trading Thursday  
for a small group of wealthy customers, becoming the first 
full-service broker to tip-toe into Wall Street's fastest growing 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Averting -- or probably delaying -- a potential clash with its  
commission-paid brokers, the huge firm limited the service to just 
55,000 customers with special accounts that aren't charged on a 
per-trade basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Those accounts, which can only be opened with a minimum of  
$100,000 in assets, represent about 1 percent of the 5 million 
accounts at Merrill Lynch, the nation's biggest investment firm. 
</P>
<P>
	While most traditional investment firms already allow their  
customers to view their accounts on the Internet, all had been 
resisting the move into online trading. Notably, Merrill Lynch did 
not issue a news release on the new service. 
</P>
<P>
	``They fear broker backlash. Online trading will reduce the  
power of the broker in the customer relationship,'' said Bill 
Doyle, an industry analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, 
Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the same time, it's absolutely unavoidable,'' he added,  
forecasting that the number of online trading accounts will surge 
from 5.3 million to 8.4 million in 1999. Likewise, the assets in 
online accounts are expected to grow from $233 billion to nearly 
$400 billion, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissions charged for online trades are just a fraction of  
the trading fees at full-service firms such as Merrill Lynch, 
Salomon Smith Barney, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Prudential 
Securities and PaineWebber. Those firms often command fees of more 
than $100 or $200 per trade. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, Charles Schwab, the biggest online broker, charges  
about $30 for each Internet trade. Industry pioneer ETrade charges 
about $15 a trade, while upstarts such as Ameritrade charge as 
little as $8. 
</P>
<P>
	The traditional firms have maintained that their customers want  
more personal service and don't mind paying more for trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``The financial consultant works closely with clients for  
long-term investing. The financial consultant is an overall part of 
their financial planning,'' said Merrill Lynch spokeswoman Bobbie 
Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	But Doyle said Merrill's move will pressure other full-service  
firms to offer online trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``The traditional firms often dismiss the assets held at the  
online brokerages as play money,'' he said. ``But real money is 
moving into online trading, and it's something these firms can't 
afford to ignore.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:28:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Base Closing Process Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is signaling it  
wants to work with congressional critics in hopes of finding common 
ground to permit additional rounds of base closings. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen suggested he's open to a new  
formula that could restrict the type of bases that might be closed 
at the beginning of the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most frustrating aspects is that every single  
community ... feels compelled to hire high-priced PR firms ... 
high-priced legal teams'' to try to fight potential closings, Cohen 
told the House Appropriations defense subcommittee on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current process, all military bases in the country are  
essentially on the block in each new round of base closings. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration wants Congress to authorize two new rounds of  
base closings, one in 2001 and another in 2005. But having gone 
through four rounds since 1989, Congress has little appetite for 
further closings. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Republicans accuse Clinton of manipulating the  
process to save defense jobs in electoral-rich California and Texas 
as part of his 1996 re-election effort. House Majority Leader Dick 
Armey, R-Texas, predicted this week that Congress would not approve 
any further base closings ``under this president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Cohen, a Republican who represented Maine in the Senate, has  
been quietly working on Capitol Hill in hopes of finding a new 
formula that overcomes most GOP objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current system, Congress authorizes an independent  
nonpartisan commission -- the Base Realignment and Closure 
Commission -- which then decides which bases should be closed, 
supposedly without political interference. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Congress' sharpest critics of the system, including  
Sens. James Inhofe, R-Okla., and Pat Roberts, R-Kan., both members 
of the Senate Armed Services Committee, have suggested that the 
scope of future base-closing reviews be limited at the outset to 
just certain type of bases -- principally those for which the 
Pentagon clearly has an overabundance. 
</P>
<P>
	That could keep cities near other military bases -- ones not  
likely to be closed down -- from panicking unnecessarily, they 
suggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen met privately on Monday with Inhofe and afterward  
indicated interest in such a plan, both in an appearance Tuesday 
before the Senate Budget Committee and Wednesday's House testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure that you folks sitting in Washington can really  
appreciate what every community near a proposed realignment ... 
goes through,'' Inhofe told Pentagon officials at a separate Senate 
Armed Services Committee hearing on Tuesday. ``They pay $100,000 
for a consultant, and many of them are getting fleeced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If only 10 percent of the bases are deemed to have surplus  
capacity, ``why put the (other) 90 percent of the installations 
through that?'' Inhofe asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen on Wednesday suggested that it would be hard to entirely  
remove the suggestion of political interference from the process. 
If the Pentagon made the initial cuts, charges would surely arise 
that politics played a role, he suggestion. 
</P>
<P>
	But Inhofe has proposed a process under which either the  
Pentagon or the congressional General Accounting Office come up 
with the initial list -- or at least determine the category of base 
to be closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., another advocate of such an  
approach, told Cohen at Wednesday's hearing that the list should be 
narrowed in the beginning ``rather than have every single base and 
post in the country go through the cost, the analysis, the 
examination and the frustration and upset that comes with 
determining whether you're going to be around or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree with you,'' Cohen said. ``There's got to be a way of  
somehow minimizing the cost and expense to communities who suddenly 
feel they've got to put on the best possible presentation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen noted he had been on both sides of the situation -- first  
as a senator from Maine with bases targeted for closure, and now as 
defense secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Base-closing rounds, in 1989, 1991, 1993 and 1995 closed 70  
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 03:52:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Executes 2nd German Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- The brother of a German citizen executed  
a week ago was poisoned by cyanide gas in Arizona's death chamber 
despite protests that reached the highest tribunals in Europe and 
the United States. 
</P>
