<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chernobyl Survivor Wants To Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The only survivor of eight Ukrainian children  
brought for medical treatment after the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear 
accident is asking for permission to stay in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir ``Vova'' Malofienko, 14, of Short Hills, N.J., has  
leukemia, but doctors say he has a good chance of reaching 
adulthood if he stays in the United States, Rep. Steven Rothman 
told a House subcommittee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the seven other children died after returning to homes  
near the Chernobyl nuclear reactor in Ukraine. 
</P>
<P>
	``He lived about 30 miles from Chernobyl. Of the eight children  
brought from Chernobyl in 1990, seven of the eight are dead,'' 
Rothman, D-N.J., told the House Judiciary Committee's immigration 
subcommittee. Doctors believe ``that given the continued existence 
of the poisons in the atmosphere at Chernobyl, if he returns he 
will die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee approved a one-page bill granting Vladimir, his  
mother and his father legal permanent residence in the United 
States. The bill now goes to the full committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Frank Lautenberg and Robert Torricelli, both New Jersey  
Democrats, introduced the same bill in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir's father is an engineer and his mother is an  
accountant, so the family isn't likely to need public assistance, 
Rothman said. ``They will not be living off the government of the 
United States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir entered the United States on Aug. 7, 1990, as a  
non-immigrant visitor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
