<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Soar in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen early Friday  
in Tokyo, while Japanese stocks advanced following an overnight 
rally on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 123.52 yen in early trading, up 0.94 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
123.35 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 246.76 points,  
or 1.74 percent, to 14,430.21 in the first 30 minutes of morning 
trading. On Thursday, the average gained 13.09 points, or 0.09 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar rose on buying by Japanese  
banks and overseas funds who used the release of Japanese price 
data as an excuse to buy the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's overall wholesale price index for February was up  
0.2 percent from January but was 3.8 percent lower than the 
year-earlier month, the Bank of Japan said Friday. The data fell 
within analysts' forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the data were considered neutral, currency investors were  
using it to buy dollars, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 133.27 yen, up from  
133.13 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices were sharply higher in response to  
the overnight gain on Wall Street and the dollar's strength against 
the yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial Average  
climbed 191.52 points to close at 9,467.70, boosted by benign 
economic data, strong retail sales reports and higher oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, traders said Sony and Toshiba shares were heavily  
sought by buyers following the announcement Thursday that Sony 
Computer Entertainment Inc., a Sony unit, and Toshiba had agreed to 
set up a joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	It will produce in Japan the 128-bit central processing unit for  
the next generation PlayStation game console. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 11.65 points, or 1.05 percent, to 1,116.76 
points. The TOPIX rose 5.30 points, or 0.48 percent, the previous 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond sank to 1.535 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.610 percent, 
driving its price up to 102.15 yen from 101.53 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
