<HEADLINE> Wind To Test Wright Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOFFETT FIELD, Calif. (AP) -- NASA engineers have mounted a  
full-scale replica of the Wright brothers' original biplane in a 
wind tunnel to learn more about its stability, control and 
handling. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists hope the tests will help the plane buffs who plan to  
fly the replica in 2003 to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the 
first flight at Kitty Hawk, N.C., on Dec. 17, 1903. 
</P>
<P>
	``By understanding the flying characteristics of the Wright  
Flyer, we gain a better understanding of the Wright brothers' 
science and engineering skills, as well as an appreciation of the 
process that led to the development of the airplanes we fly 
today,'' said Craig Hange, a wind tunnel test engineer at NASA's 
Ames Research Center. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of volunteers from the American Institute of Aeronautics  
and Astronautics built the replica using data from the original 
airplane provided by the Smithsonian. 
</P>
<P>
	The wings are fabric, the supports are wood, and there are no  
wheels to land on -- just skids. 
</P>
<P>
	The replica, perched in the cavernous wind tunnel this week,  
will be subjected to conditions it would face traveling 30 mph 
about 10 feet off the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	California Institute of Technology aeronautics professor Fred  
Culick, 63, is slated to be the first to fly the plane four years 
from now. 
</P>
<P>
	Gazing up at the 600-pound biplane Wednesday, he said he's  
looking forward to actually feeling what Orville Wright felt on 
that first flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Orville won a coin flip with Wilbur to determine who would be at  
the controls; the plane went about 120 feet on a flight that lasted 
about 12 seconds. It was the first engine-powered flight of a 
heavier-than-air machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Culick said he'll be wearing a helmet and a safety harness.  
</P>
<P>
	``I may be foolhardy, but I'm not crazy,'' Culick said.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
