<HEADLINE> Secret Service Gets New Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brian L. Stafford, former head of President  
Clinton's security detail, was being sworn in today as the 20th 
director of the Secret Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Stafford replaces Lou Merletti, who retired two months ago to  
run the security operation for the Cleveland Browns football team. 
Merletti fought to keep Secret Service agents from testifying in 
the Monica Lewinsky investigation, but the courts ruled against 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Stafford, a 28-year veteran of the Secret Service, is a native  
of Sharpsville, Pa. He served in the Army prior to joining the 
agency, serving a tour of duty in Vietnam from 1969 to 1971. He was 
head of Clinton's security detail for about a year, but did not 
testify in the inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who oversees the agency, was  
swearing Stafford in., said spokesman Jim Mackin. 
</P>
