<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T: We Don't Want To Buy AOL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. doesn't want to acquire the  
nation's largest Internet provider, America Online, despite 
persistent rumors about such a deal, AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael 
Armstrong said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely not interested in, nor are we pursuing  
acquiring America Online,'' Armstrong said, responding to a 
question about whether a deal between the two titan companies is in 
the works. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been published reports that the two companies were  
thinking about pairing up. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong made his remarks after giving a speech to the American  
Enterprise Institute here. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL, meanwhile, had wanted federal regulators, as a condition of  
approving AT&AMP;T's planned merger with cable giant 
Tele-Communications, to make the merged company provide other 
companies with access to TCI's high-speed lines, which reach 
one-third of U.S. homes. The FCC, in clearing the merger last 
month, refused to to that. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong said it's in AT&AMP;T's financial interest to get as many  
companies as it can onto its high-speed networks. The company, 
along with the cable industry, opposes government-mandated access 
to cable companies' high-speed lines into their customers' homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, AT&AMP;T and cable companies support voluntary agreements  
for businesses offering competing services to gain access to the 
lines, which allow people to surf the Internet and receive data at 
speeds considerably faster than normal phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	If AOL can spare time from lobbying on the cable access issue,  
``We'd be happy to sit down and negotiate'' a deal giving AOL 
access to TCI's lines, Armstrong said. 
</P>
<P>
	The AT&AMP;T-TCI merger has won all major regulatory approvals.  
Armstrong said he hopes to close the deal March 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Armstrong, in his speech, said U.S. companies --  
backed by the U.S. government -- need to work on lowering the fees 
U.S. carriers must pay foreign telephone companies to complete 
calls to many countries. Armstrong believes the fees, which get 
passed onto customers, are artificially high, forcing U.S. callers 
to pay $5 billion a year more than they should for many 
international calls. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint asked the Federal Communications  
Commission last week to help force foreign carriers in Kuwait, 
Cyprus and Netherlands Antilles to lower their fees. AT&AMP;T and 
WorldCom have also complained to the FCC that fees charged by 
Mexican carriers are too high. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
