<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Seek Final Pieces to Puzzle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- With their starting rotation,  
bullpen and everyday lineup pretty much in order, New York Mets 
manager Bobby Valentine is looking for the accessories to finish 
the product. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning with the exhibition opener Friday night against the  
Montreal Expos, Mets manager Bobby Valentine will be playing the 
numbers game. 
</P>
<P>
	Depending on whether or not New York goes into the season with  
11 or 12 pitchers, the Mets still need to make a decision on five 
or six bench players to complete the 25-man roster for opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring injury, New York's starting rotation of Al Leiter, Rick  
Reed, Bobby Jones, Masato Yoshii and Hideo Nomo is set. 
Left-handers coming out of the bullpen include Allen Watson, Dennis 
Cook and John Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	From the right-handed side are Greg McMichael, Turk Wendell and  
Armando Benitez. 
</P>
<P>
	Should the Mets decide to go with a 12th pitcher, they could  
take Jason Isringhausen, Paul Wilson or Jeff Tam north. 
</P>
<P>
	The oft-injured Isringhausen threw about 50 pitches during two  
innings of simulated game conditions Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looks healthy and he feels healthy, and right now that's  
more important than how he looks,'' Valentine said. ``He threw all 
his pitches, and I think he's going to go on from here and pitch an 
inning in a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen underwent two arthroscopic procedures in 1996 to  
repair his right shoulder and right elbow. Last April, he broke his 
right wrist while with the Triple-A team in Norfolk, and was placed 
on the disabled list in March to recover from the previous season's 
surgeries. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the pitching is set, New York will add backup catchers,  
infielders and outfielders to the roster, plugging in needs for 
left-handed and right-handed hitting as well as speed off the 
bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Catcher Todd Pratt leads the race to fill in behind Mike Piazza,  
based on his .275 average in 41 games last year with New York and 
his ability to also play first base. 
</P>
<P>
	Infielder Matt Franco also has the versatility factor, having  
the ability to serve as an emergency catcher, and he hits from the 
left side. Luis Lopez is a switch-hitting middle infielder who 
spent 117 games in New York last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariano Duncan also is in the mix after spending a year in Japan  
and the 1997 season as the starting second baseman for the New York 
Yankees' championship team 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the guys who play the infield and hit right-handed  
will be in competition here,'' Valentine said while discussing 
Duncan. ``You wonder how he could contribute to the long season, 
guys who have more experience have a better idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets starting infield is set with John Olerud at first,  
Edgardo Alfonzo at second, Rey Ordonez at shortstop and Robin 
Ventura at third. 
</P>
<P>
	Backing up an outfield of Bobby Bonilla, Brian McRae and Rickey  
Henderson could be Roger Cedeno who came over from the Los Angeles 
Dodgers, and Jerome Allensworth, who played 34 games last year with 
the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said the battle will continue for the final roster  
spots throughout the spring training schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think as things develop, guys could work their way into a  
situation that could increase their chances of making the team,'' 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
