<DOCNO> APW19990304.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Holds Internet Smut Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A proposal requiring certain schools and  
libraries to use Internet software to block material inappropriate 
for children would undermine efforts by communities to solve the 
issue, a Senate panel was told Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress must understand that there is no one-size-fits-all  
solution that the federal government can impose that is better or 
more thoughtful than the solutions communities adopt,'' Candace 
Morgan, associate director of the Fort Vancouver Regional Library 
in Washington state, told the Senate Commerce Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan bill is intended to shield minors from sexually  
explicit material on the Internet by requiring schools and 
libraries that get federally subsidized hookups to install and use 
special computer software to block access to such sites, and the 
proposal got some support at the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This legislation ... is an absolute necessity,'' said Bruce  
Taylor, president of the National Law Center for Children and 
Families. ``The libraries and the schools are not going to use 
these technologies unless someone makes them do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill -- sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the panel's  
chairman, and Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., its senior Democrat -- 
recommends no specific blocking device and would let schools, 
school boards, libraries and other authorities decide what material 
should be blocked or filtered. It does require that libraries have 
at least one computer fitted with the software. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing featured a testy exchange between Morgan and McCain,  
who disagreed with the librarian's contention that the bill would 
require libraries and schools to have the filtering software up and 
running at all times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your testimony does not coincide with what the intent and the  
language of the legislation says,'' snapped McCain, who is 
exploring a run for president in 2000. ``I'm sorry that you would 
not read English the same way that everybody else does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Franks, R-N.J., is sponsoring a companion measure in  
the House. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 97.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
