<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walker Signs 6-Year Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- National League batting champion Larry Walker  
agreed today to a six-year extension of his contract with the 
Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, in interviews, had been pressuring the Rockies to come  
up with a deal before the season began, hinting he might choose to 
become a free agent if they didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the contract were not disclosed. But a statement said  
the Rockies will help Walker fund a foundation for children and 
families in need in the Rocky Mountain region and Walker's native 
British Columbia. The Rockies and Walker together will provide 
$3,333,333 to get the foundation going. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, 32, won the 1998 National League batting title with a  
.363 average. In 1997, he was the MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	His defensive play has earned him two consecutive Gold Gloves.  
He is the Rockies career leader with a batting average of .335, 
slugging percentage of .643 and on-base percent of .414. His 
lifetime average, including his seasons at Montreal, is .305. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker signed a four-year free-agent contract with the Rockies  
before the 1995 season. It included a 1999 club option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
