<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Howland To Coach Pittsburgh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Northern Arizona basketball coach Ben Howland  
reportedly will be the new head coach for the University of 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona Republic said today that Howland declined comment,  
but that sources at Pittsburgh and Flagstaff confirmed he had 
signed a contract, details of which were unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	Howland, who interviewed for the position earlier this week, was  
en route Wednesday night to Ogden, Utah, where the Lumberjacks 
(20-7 12-4), runners-up to Weber State (22-7, 13-3) in the Big Sky 
Conference regular season, will participate in the conference 
playoffs this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Howland, 40, led the Lumberjacks to a 75-57 record in five  
seasons, including back-to-back conference championships. Northern 
Arizona also made the NCAA playoffs last year for the first time 
and still hopes to do so this season. The winner of the conference 
tournament gets an automatic bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh was expected to hold off introducing Howland as its  
new coach until after the weekend. Pittsburgh lost to Rutgers 64-51 
in Wednesday night's first round of the Big East tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Under coach Ralph Willard, Pittsburgh is 14-16 overall and 5-13  
in the conference this season. The Panthers have had only one 
winning season in his five with the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Willard announced at midseason that he was leaving Pitt after  
the season ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Holton, Northern Arizona's athletic director, said he had  
nothing to announce Wednesday night, but that the Lumberjacks were 
in the preliminary stages of a coaching search. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republic said Holton acknowledged that Jamie Dixon, an  
assistant at Hawaii and former assistant at Northern Arizona, has 
inquired about the job. ``He is definitely somebody we're 
considering,'' Holton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
