<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. rose 6 11/16 to 84 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
 *Morgan Stanley Dean Witter rose 3 11/16 to 96 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Salomon Smith Barney raised its first-quarter and 1999 earnings  
estimate for both companies, saying underwriting volume is up 
sharply from the fourth quarter, retail sales volume is stronger, 
and fixed-income trading should be profitable after two weak 
quarters. 

</P>
<P>
 *International Game Technology Inc. fell 3 5/8 to 14 11/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company said it may not meet analyst earnings estimates for  
1999 because of low gambling-machine shipments. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sears rose 3 1/8 to 43 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Sales at U.S. stores open at least a year rose 0.8 percent from  
a year ago. Sears named Julian C. Day chief financial officer and 
executive vice president. Day had been chief financial officer and 
executive vice president of Safeway Inc. He succeeds Alan Lacy, 
president of Sears Credit. Lacy, former chief financial officer, 
reassumed the position in August when Gary Crittenden left the 
company. 

</P>
<P>
 *BJ's Wholesale Club, Inc. rose 1 to 24 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	February sales increased by 13.7 percent, reflecting ``strong,  
early demand for spring seasonal merchandise and continued strength 
in sales of apparel, tires and toys,'' said chief executive Jack 
Nugent. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Level 3 Communications Inc. rose 2 15/16 to 57 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company, which is developing a national fiber-optic network  
that will use Internet technology to offer local and long-distance 
communications services, sold 25 million common shares at $54 each, 
in an offering increased in size from 20 million shares. 

</P>
<P>
 *MCI WorldCom rose 13/16 to 81 7/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The telecommunications company is teaming up with Bell Canada to  
offer lower-cost phone service on both sides of the border. MCI 
WorldCom said its U.S. customers doing business with Canadians 
using its On-Net service would realize a savings. 

</P>
<P>
 *Level One Communications fell 5 1/4 to 27 1/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Adams Harkness downgraded shares of the maker of  
telecommunications and computer equipment to ``accumulate'' from 
``strong buy.'' 

</P>
<P>
 *Compuware Corp. rose 3/8 to 25 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company, which markets e-commerce and World Wide Web testing  
software, introduced its QARun computer testing tool, which 
includes Internet testing capabilities for a range of languages 
including Java. 

</P>
<P>
 *Verio Inc. rose 4 to 36 1/2.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Internet-service provider will pay America Online Inc. a  
minimum of $42.5 million to become AOL's exclusive business Web 
host provider. 

</P>
<P>
 *CheckFree Holdings Corp. fell 4 to 31 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
 *Intuit rose 1 5/16 to 113 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Intuit, which makes financial management software, sued  
Checkfree, alleging that Checkfree violated the terms of a 
billing-service contract signed last spring. Checkfree is the 
primary provider of bill-presentment and payment-processing 
services for Intuit's Internet site, and Intuit holds a 
19.9-percent stake in CheckFree. 

</P>
<P>
                               *AMEX    	

</P>
<P>
 *Horizon Pharmacies Inc. fell 2 9/16 to 5 11/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company said it resolved problems with its  
prescription-pricing technology but may still see a loss of $1 
million to $2.5 million. The company said Wednesday that its gross 
margins were reduced by a failure to receive updated wholesale 
prices. Horizon said its prescription costs rose, but customers 
weren't charged the updated prices. 

</P>
</TEXT>
