<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 05:28:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Storms in Northwest, South Kill Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Powerful winds and large waves whipped the Pacific Northwest  
coast on Wednesday, knocking out power to tens of thousands and 
interrupting ferry service across Washington state's Puget Sound. 
</P>
<P>
	In the South, tornadoes and strong storms tore across several  
states. 
</P>
<P>
	A 36-year-old man was killed in Washington when a tree fell on  
the car he was driving. In Alabama, a 23-year-old man was killed 
when a tree slammed into his trailer home in Milbrook. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden you just heard a big boom,'' said Stephanie  
Clecker, 17, who lives nearby the trailer home. ``Glass started 
flying everywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington Gov. Gary Locke declared a state of emergency in five  
counties in the western part of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	At the peak of the wind storm, gusts reached as high as 68 mph  
in Snohomish, northeast of Seattle, the weather service said, while 
35-foot seas and sustained 60 mph winds were reported off the 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200,000 people were without electricity early  
Wednesday as falling tree limbs felled power lines, but most had 
power restored by noon. 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger ferry service in the Puget Sound area was canceled  
Wednesday morning, affecting about 45,000 people, state ferry 
spokeswoman Susan Harris-Huether said. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm also closed the Evergreen Point Floating Bridge across  
Seattle's Lake Washington, bringing morning commuter traffic to a 
near-standstill. There was damage to the draw span of the bridge 
and crews said it could not be repaired until at least Friday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 100,000 cars use the Evergreen Point bridge each  
day, which connects Seattle to the eastern suburbs -- including 
Redmond where Microsoft headquarters is located. The damage leaves 
the Interstate 90 floating bridge, three miles to the south, as the 
only cross-lake span. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Washington coast, heavy seas combined with high tides to  
flood the town of Raymond's downtown area with up to 2 feet of 
water. Two apartment complexes were evacuated, and nearly 40 people 
sought shelter at a Red Cross facility. Downtown was reopened late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes touched down in Florida and Texas late Tuesday and  
early Wednesday, damaging dozens of homes and causing minor 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	In Virginia, a thunderstorm packing strong winds ripped through  
a construction site south of Richmond on Wednesday, injuring 16 
people, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Search dogs were brought in to help officials account for  
everyone at Chaparral Virginia Steel Recycling construction site, 
said Janet Clements, spokeswoman for the state Department of 
Emergency Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people injured at the construction site were taken to a  
Petersburg hospital with neck and back injuries and cuts. They were 
in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the injured were treated at the scene.  
</P>
<P>
	Two emergency workers en route to the construction site were  
injured in an automobile accident. One was in stable condition and 
another was critical. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, winds topped 60 mph knocked down trees and  
power lines as a cold front swept through the state and dumped up 
to 7 inches of snow in the mountains and spawning thunderstorms and 
hail. Power outages left more than 100,000 North Carolina utility 
customers in the dark for a time. 
</P>
<P>
	In east Texas, several Tuesday night twisters nearly demolished  
six homes and damaged as many as 25 others. Several people suffered 
minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	A tornado in the Florida Panhandle damaged about 55 homes, with  
20 sustaining major damage. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
