<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Killers Make More Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Uganda sent hundreds of troops into  
neighboring Congo and beefed up police and military presence today 
after rebels who slaughtered eight foreign tourists reportedly 
threatened further attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The search was focusing on dense jungle just over the border,  
where the rebels are based. Rwandan soldiers also were involved in 
the manhunt, which began in earnest Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI team, meanwhile, was in Kampala investigating the deaths  
of two Americans among those killed Monday in remote campgrounds in 
southwestern Uganda's Impenetrable Forest. 
</P>
<P>
	Four Britons and two New Zealanders also were killed. Six other  
tourists were seized but survived. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Ugandan side of the border, police reinforcements were  
sent into the western districts of Kasese and Bundibugyo after 
rebels distributed letters warning they would launch further 
attacks, the private Central Broadcasting Service reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	It said roadblocks had been set up in two villages in those  
areas, which are north of the Kisoro district where the tourists 
were killed. The report did not say how many forces were deployed, 
but Ugandan officials said a battalion of about 600 soldiers was 
sent into Congo. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's president, Yoweri Museveni, on Wednesday promised to  
hunt down the rebels and appealed for help from the international 
community to track them down. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels were among Hutu fighters who fled Rwanda in 1994  
after killing more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically 
moderate Hutus in a government-orchestrated genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hutu fighters, who have been carrying out cross-border raids  
from bases in eastern Congo, are angry at the United States, 
Britain and Uganda for providing aid to Rwanda's new Tutsi-led 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	A Ugandan commander said soldiers tracked the rebels to a base  
in Congo's Virunga National Park on Tuesday, killing some before 
they scattered. 
</P>
<P>
	Uganda's government-owned New Vision newspaper reported today  
that government forces killed 15 rebels in a gunbattle, and that 
the insurgents were retreating. It did not specify where or when 
the fighting occurred, or whether those killed had anything to do 
with the tourists' deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	New Vision also said the army arrested a suspect who had  
apparently helped brief rebels on the positions of tourists and the 
locations of their belongings in the park before the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper, citing an unidentified source, said several  
people had been heard briefing the rebels before the attack. ``They 
seemed to know which tents were occupied and by who. They only 
missed one,'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tourists were abducted Sunday at campgrounds on the edge of  
Bwindi National Park, the starting point for those hoping to 
glimpse rare mountain gorillas portrayed in the 1988 film 
``Gorillas in the Mist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American-born pilot and guide Mark Ross, credited with  
negotiating the release of the six survivors, told The Associated 
Press before he left for Kenya that he would return to Uganda once 
the park is deemed safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a beautiful forest and the people that ran it were  
exceptionally friendly and knowledgeable,'' Ross said today. The 
attack ``was a really sad, freaky and, I think, unpredictable 
occurrence, unlike the wildlife which is quite predictable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
