<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lewinsky Shares Her Anguish on TV  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky let the public share her  
anguish -- about her relationship with President Clinton, her sex 
life with others and the main players in the drama that led to a 
historic impeachment trial. After sharing her innermost feelings 
about her presidential affair and her loathing for Kenneth Starr in 
an ABC interview, Ms. Lewinsky says her major worry now is ``doing 
something to lose my immunity'' from prosecution. Months before her 
immunity deal with Starr was sealed last summer, Ms. Lewinsky filed 
a false affidavit in the Paula Jones case denying an affair with 
the president. 

</P>
<P>
	Fierce Winds Kill 3 in Northwest  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Residents of the Northwest and South picked up  
the pieces today after storms lashed both regions with damaging 
wind, rain and snow, knocking out power to hundreds of thousands of 
people. Three people were killed. Driving winds and likely 
tornadoes blew across several Southern states yesterday, destroying 
homes and downing power lines. Nearly a foot of snow fell in parts 
of the Appalachians. 

</P>
<P>
	Alaska Medical Marijuana Law Starts  
</P>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Alaska's medical marijuana law goes into  
effect today, offering a legal shield to people who smoke the weed 
for a short list of medical ailments. Nearly 60 percent of the 
voters in the November election favored the measure, which allows 
marijuana use for ailments including cancer, AIDS, glaucoma, 
chronic pain, seizures and muscle spasms. 

</P>
<P>
	Nigerian Government Frees Prisoners  
</P>
<P>
	LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) -- Nigeria's outgoing military government  
today freed at least 47 political prisoners, including a former 
deputy junta leader on death row for allegedly planning a coup 
against former dictator Gen. Sani Abacha, officials said. The move 
was seen as a bid to calm growing unrest by anti-government 
militants that have rioted and launched a series of attacks on 
police stations and barracks in the commercial capital of Lagos 
since Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	Tourist Killers Make More Threats  
</P>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Uganda sent hundreds of troops into  
neighboring Congo and beefed up police and military presence today 
after rebels who slaughtered eight foreign tourists reportedly 
threatened further attacks. The search was focusing on dense jungle 
just over the border, where the rebels are based. 

</P>
<P>
	Viagra Speeds Pill OK in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A government committee studying the safety of the  
contraceptive pill for women has finished its nine-year 
deliberation and concluded there was no reason to withhold 
approval, though it stopped short of deciding to actually approve 
it, a Health Ministry official said today. The pill suddenly came 
into the spotlight after Viagra was approved in late January in 
just six months. Women's groups accused the government of sexism. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Crafting Mitch Recovery Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate panel is crafting an emergency $1.2  
billion measure that would rush aid to Central Americans struggling 
to recover from Hurricane Mitch. But a similar House bill is 
falling victim to political dueling over the federal surplus. The 
Senate Appropriations Committee planned to vote today on the 
legislation. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Pipeline Resumes Pumping Oil  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq resumed shipping oil to Turkey early  
today through a pipeline shut down when U.S. airstrikes damaged 
communication centers that control the flow of oil. The Iraqi Oil 
Ministry said that work at the two centers hit by U.S. warplanes 
Sunday and Monday in northern Iraq resumed at dawn. About half the 
oil Iraq exports flows through the Iraqi-Turkish pipeline, some 1 
million barrels a day. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Share prices finished higher as the Nikkei gained  
13.09 points to close at 14,183.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Mighty Ducks 2, Kings 1  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM (AP) -- Guy Hebert stopped 33 shots and won his fourth  
straight decision, leading the Anaheim Mighty Ducks to a 2-1 
victory over the Los Angeles Kings last night. Matt Cullen and 
Teemu Selanne scored for Anaheim as the Mighty Ducks won for the 
11th time in their last 14 games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  
</P>
