<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State, Local Spending on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending by America's state and local  
governments has reached $1.39 trillion, a level approaching what 
Washington pays out. 
</P>
<P>
	The total was from 1995-96, the most recent period for which  
figures are available, the Census Bureau reports in data being 
released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In fiscal 1996 the federal government had spending of $1.56  
trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the state and local governments had an overall surplus  
that year, Uncle Sam posted a deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	State and local income totaled $1.51 trillion, leaving a surplus  
of $119 billion. Washington had income of $1.45 trillion, for a 
$107 billion deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal aid to state and local governments more than made the  
difference. Some $235 billion of state and local income came from 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, 1996 spending by state and local governments was up  
3.4 percent from the year before. On the other hand, state and 
local governments' income increased by 6.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Other findings include:  
</P>
<P>
	--State and local governments spent more than half their money on  
four areas. Topping the list was education ($399 billion), followed 
by public welfare ($193 billion), highways ($79 billion) and 
hospitals ($71 billion). 
</P>
<P>
	--Taxes continued as the primary source of government revenue.  
State governments relied primarily on general sales tax ($139 
billion) and individual income taxes ($133 billion). Local 
government got most of its income from property taxes ($199 
billion). 
</P>
<P>
	--State and local governments had an outstanding debt of $1.2  
trillion, interest payments on debt of $69 billion and cash and 
security holdings of $2.3 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Detailed state information for 1996 was being made available  
Thursday on the Census Bureau's Internet site at 
http://www.census.gov/govs/www/index.html. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
