<HEADLINE> Charges Upgraded on Womack, Burnim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- A judge has raised misdemeanor  
assault and battery charges against Virginia sophomore tailback 
Antwoine Womack and senior defensive back Adrian Burnim to felony 
malicious wounding charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges stemming from a campus fight last month were  
upgraded Wednesday at the request of assistant prosecutor Steven 
Buck. Each football player now faces two malicious wounding counts, 
as does a third person, Kevin D. Cromartie, who is not a student. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were charged after becoming involved in a Feb. 7 fight  
with two University of Virginia students, Jonathan Dean and Cabal 
Thornton, who sustained cuts and bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	Buck said he asked for the upgraded charges ``because of the  
brutality of the attack and the severity of the injuries. It was an 
unprovoked attack. It was an attack from behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conviction of malicious wounding carries a sentence of up to 20  
years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Cavaliers football players also were charged. Devon  
Simmons and John Duckett still face two counts each of misdemeanor 
assault and battery. 
</P>
<P>
	Buck said the attack resulted from a year-old grudge that  
Cromartie had against Dean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
