<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders Owner Claims L.A. Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis is pressing  
his claim to own the rights to professional football in Los 
Angeles, adding yet another twist in the campaign to bring the NFL 
back to the nation's second-largest city. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying Davis' claim has no legal merit, an NFL spokesman said  
Thursday that Davis' decision to sue the league in Los Angeles 
Superior Court won't derail the process of choosing where to put 
the league's next expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	League officials are considering bids from two groups in Los  
Angeles and another in Houston for a new NFL team that could begin 
play in 2002. Owners are expected to vote on the proposals when 
they meet March 14-18 in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to be prepared to move forward on expansion  
regardless of the pending litigation,'' said NFL spokesman Greg 
Aiello. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles has been without a franchise since the Raiders went  
back to Oakland and the Rams moved to St. Louis before the 1995 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls seeking comment from Davis' attorneys were not immediately  
returned Thursday. In statements Wednesday, they described U.S. 
District Court Judge George H. King's ruling as a victory because 
they originally wanted to pursue the claim in state court. 
</P>
<P>
	King on Tuesday threw out Davis' claim the Raiders owner owns  
the Los Angeles market, saying federal law did not apply to the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	King also dismissed Davis' claim the NFL violated antitrust laws  
in 1994 when the league refused to facilitate the Raiders' move 
from Los Angeles to Oakland by scheduling games there. 
</P>
<P>
	King said Davis was free to refile his claim in Los Angeles  
Superior Court, and Davis did just that Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the new lawsuit also is dismissed, it represents an  
unwelcome development for the NFL, said Mark Eschenfelder, 
professor of sports economics at Robert Morris College. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly given the NFL's track record with Al Davis, they  
have to be cringing,'' said Eschenfelder. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis successfully sued the NFL in 1982, winning the right to  
move the Raiders from Oakland to Los Angeles. Davis moved the team 
back to Oakland in 1995 after the Los Angeles Coliseum was damaged 
by an earthquake. The NFL sued, claiming the team scheduled games 
in Oakland without league approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders countersued, saying the league blocked the team's  
attempt to move in 1994, interfered with the move in 1995 and 
destroyed negotiations to build a new stadium the Los Angeles 
suburb of Inglewood. 
</P>
<P>
	Unhappy with fan turnout in Oakland, Davis last month began  
talks with Oakland city officials about moving back to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Two groups in Los Angeles are bidding for the expansion  
franchise, each with a stadium proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz is heading one campaign and his  
backers include Tom Cruise and Kevin Costner. The group wants to 
build a combined stadium and shopping mall in suburban Carson. 
Developer Ed Roski Jr. and billionaire Eli Broad are proposing to 
renovate the Los Angeles Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is scheduled to meet with Ovitz  
on Friday and tour the Carson site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
