<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canal Plus, BSkyB Merger Talks Stall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Merger talks between British Sky Broadcasting PLC  
and France's Canal Plus SA to create a Europe-wide pay-television 
service have stalled over issues of management control. 
</P>
<P>
	Rupert Murdoch, whose News Corp. media empire controls BSkyB,  
came to Paris on Wednesday to talk with Canal Plus chairman Pierre 
Lescure, but left without agreeing to a deal. Canal Plus has 
insisted that its management and primary shareholder remain French 
in the event of a merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``The talks have been suspended because there was no agreement  
on our fundamental conditions,'' a Canal Plus spokeswoman said 
Thursday. ``However, they have not been broken off altogether.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The breakdown of the talks came as the French government sternly  
warned Canal Plus on a potential merger, noting that Murdoch 
opposes government regulation of the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Canal Plus must bear in mind that the government will examine  
with the greatest vigilance any possible linkup -- no matter what 
the form -- with Murdoch's group,'' Culture Minister Catherine 
Trautman said Wednesday before parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. had no comment on the merger talks Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. owns 40 percent of BSkyB, the largest pay-TV provider  
in Britain with 7 million subscribers, and has been trying to 
expand its European holdings for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Canal Plus has 11 million subscribers in 10 countries, making it  
the biggest pay-TV company in Europe. Vivendi SA owns 34 percent of 
the company. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
