<DOCNO> APW19990304.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP To Strengthen Education Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the first, muted clash of the new Congress,  
Republicans are maneuvering to strengthen their standing on 
education, a top issue with the public. Democrats are determined 
not to be outflanked. 
</P>
<P>
	The result, according to congressional aides in both parties, is  
that GOP-drafted legislation to loosen federal strings on school 
aid is likely to pass the Senate by an overwhelming margin next 
week. But not before a politically charged struggle over Democratic 
amendments for hiring more teachers and funding after-school 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education was ranked as the most important issue by the single  
largest number of people'' in the 1998 elections, Mark Mellman, a 
Democratic pollster, said Thursday as the two parties jockeyed for 
position in the Senate. ``And those people voted overwhelmingly 
Democratic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure we've found a way to make it work,'' conceded Jan  
Vanlohuizen, a pollster whose clients include the GOP Senatorial 
Campaign Committee. GOP governors fared well last year among voters 
who care about education, he said, in contrast to candidates for 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they need to show that education is a priority and I  
think they need to show it in a non-punitive way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Long gone is the public talk among Republicans -- prevalent when  
the GOP gained control of the Congress in 1994 -- of abolishing the 
Department of Education. 
</P>
<P>
	And there has been little GOP emphasis thus far this year on  
establishing federally-funded voucher programs to allow children to 
attend private schools. While that issue has gained some appeal 
among those seeking an alternative to poorly performing inner city 
schools, it is not supported as strongly by the public as much as 
other GOP education proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, a former high school teacher and  
wrestling coach, has identified education as a top priority. 
Hastert, whose wife is a kindergarten teacher, journeyed to a 
District of Columbia elementary school earlier this week to read to 
school schildren to underscore his personal interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Already a bill to loosen federal strings on education aid has  
cleared a House committee and is expected on the floor next week. 
House Republicans will be introducing another measure next week to 
allow special education accounts, with interest to accumulate 
tax-free, that can be used for school expenses. That draws support 
of 90 percent of the public, according to a survey Vanlohuizen's 
firm, Voter Consumer Research, did last fall for Senate 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, Republican Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, the  
chairman of the Budget Committee, floated a proposal for a 40 
percent increase in federal school funding over the next several 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	And setting on a schedule for the post-impeachment era, Majority  
Leader Trent Lott decided on an early debate on legislation backed 
by governors of both parties to reduce federal restrictions on 
money that goes to the states. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats swiftly decided to seek passage of an amendment to  
complete the hiring of 100,000 teachers, and another for 
after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there are issues of higher importance to  
American families than these issues,'' Sen. Barbara Boxer of 
California said Thursday at a news conference where she and other 
Democrats disputed GOP claims they were pushing dilatory 
amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before those two issues could be brought up, though, the  
Senate bogged down during the day on preliminaries. Democrats 
sought approval of an amendment calling for $150 million for 
programs to keep dropouts in school. Republicans tried to supplant 
that proposal with one for money for special education programs, 
and appeared surprised when Democrats led by Sen. Edward M. 
Kennedy, D-Mass., decided to embrace it. 
</P>
<P>
	By evening, Republicans were charging Democrats with mounting a  
filibuster against a bill that has the backing of the White House 
and governors of both parties. Democrats denied it, and said Lott 
would fail with an effort prevent votes on their politically 
appealing amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	A test vote was set for Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, the way to passage of the underlying education  
measure was eased on Tuesday with a compromise on a call by Kennedy 
for greater accountability on the part of states in exchange for 
the ability to spend money more freely. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, dubbed ``ed flex'' would expand a pilot program  
to all 50 states. It gives local school districts greater 
flexibility over federal education as they seek improved schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
