<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:47:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Backdoor' Immigration Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A program that allows foreigners to  
temporarily remain in the United States rather than return to a 
country racked with political turmoil or suffering devastation from 
a hurricane has turned into a ``backdoor'' immigration program for 
illegal aliens, critics told a House subcommittee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Temporary Protected Status program allows the attorney  
general to allow foreigners to stay in the United States for six to 
18 months if their home countries become embroiled in political 
violence or suffer devastation because of natural disasters. Not 
everyone in the program is an illegal alien; some are on expiring 
student visas. 
</P>
<P>
	At the conclusion of this period, they are supposed to leave the  
United States. But the Immigration and Naturalization Service has 
said it doesn't know how many actually do. In some cases, U.S. 
officials have simply allowed them to stay permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	``Experience has shown that in every case, where large numbers  
of people have been granted temporary protection, they have 
eventually received permanent status,'' Mark Krikorian, executive 
director of the conservative Center for Immigration Studies, told 
the House Judiciary Committee's immigration subcommittee. 
``Temporary protection would simply be a lie if it were used as a 
backdoor to permanent immigration or as a fig leaf to cover 
political unwillingness to enforce the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, for example, Cubans were granted temporary  
protection, Krikorian said. But Congress gave them the right to 
remain permanently when it passed the 1966 Cuban Protection Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the 1970s, thousands fled the communist takeover of  
Indochina, and they too were granted temporary protection until 
Congress in 1977 made their status permanent,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said he  
doesn't question whether the program should exist. ``The question 
is whether it is really temporary and to what extent TPS invites 
fraud,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said there may be valid  
reasons why foreigners stay rather than return home. Offering help 
to those returning to their countries could encourage more to 
leave, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 220,000 people have applied for temporary protection  
against deportation since the program began in 1991, and about 
24,450 foreigners hold the status currently. That doesn't include 
the tens of thousands of Hondurans and Nicaraguans already in the 
United States and otherwise in danger of deported who got their 
first chance to apply to stay here in December because of Hurricane 
Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigrants applying for temporary protection must tell the INS  
their whereabouts and submit fingerprints. They must pay an 
application fee of $175, including $100 for a work permit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
