<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Doesn't Tip Her Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dropping a hint about a call to civic duty,  
Hillary Rodham Clinton is tantalizing New Yorkers who look at the 
first lady and see their next senator. But so far she's just 
keeping them guessing. 
</P>
<P>
	On her second day in New York, Mrs. Clinton was giving a speech  
at the United Nations today about the upcoming Women's Rights Day 
and later was previewing an HBO documentary on women in sports at a 
school in Chelsea. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's visit to the Big Apple had the feel of a campaign  
rally even as she remained coy on whether she will be a candidate. 
Democrats used her visit Wednesday -- her first to New York since 
saying she was giving careful thought to a Senate bid -- to woo the 
fence-sitting first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	And some of her supporters were anything but subtle.  
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you think it's time for a woman to represent New York in  
the United States Senate?'' Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., blared to 
an overflow crowd of about 900 mostly female donors who plunked 
down up to $1,000 apiece to soak up the Hillary phenomenon at a 
Democratic National Committee luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, standing behind Schumer, smiled as the crowd  
erupted in applause. 
</P>
<P>
	Although her aides sought to portray her jaunt to New York as  
just another of many forays here, Mrs. Clinton's words were just 
vague enough to stoke her boosters' hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot drop out of the political process and leave the  
arena to those with very specific agendas,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
``We cannot say `I won't be involved in politics because I don't 
like the negativity. I don't like all of the ads on television.'.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She alluded only once to the Senate race.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was told that there were some who thought that, uh, I might  
have an announcement to make,'' she said, pausing and holding the 
crowd in breath-catching suspense. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't.''  
</P>
<P>
	Groans followed.  
</P>
<P>
	The aura of mystery surrounding Mrs. Clinton's political  
flirtation is spawning a parlor game in Democratic circles. The 
buzz after her speech placed odds on her running. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she's not running she's giving a good impression of someone  
who is,'' New York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone said. ``I 
think every indication now is that she runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until she does decide, she is a huge cash draw for the  
Democrats. Wednesday's luncheon raised $500,000, a record for the 
DNC's Women's Leadership Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	Even political veterans marveled at the sea of awestruck  
supporters, cameras and clamoring reporters hanging on the first 
lady's every word. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could not believe the amount of press,'' said former Rep.  
Geraldine Ferraro, who once ran as vice president on the Democratic 
ticket and lost to Schumer in the Democratic Senate primary last 
year. ``It's like a presidential announcement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton began Wednesday with a visit to a middle school in  
the Queens, where she discussed the virtues of arts education, and 
capped the day with a private dinner at the home of Roger Altman, a 
former Treasury Department officials whose deep pockets could be 
crucial to financing a New York campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's visit came as Monica Lewinsky's face was again  
plastered on the covers of New York City's tabloids in anticipation 
of the former White House intern's interview broadcast Wednesday 
night about her affair with the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mrs. Clinton would be a formidable candidate, she would  
also face what looks to be a tough battle against her most likely 
Republican opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Her lead 
against Giuliani, which had surged into the double digits in 
earlier polls, shrank to just four points, equal to the margin of 
error, in a survey released Wednesday by the Marist College 
Institute for Public Opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	And not everyone was gushing. One man outside the Plaza Hotel  
held aloft a placard reading ``Hillary Clinton: Doormat of the 
Year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
