<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Marine Cable Car Verdict Reached </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Eight military jurors announced they  
reached a verdict today after a second day of deliberations on 
whether a Marine pilot whose jet hit an Italian ski gondola cable 
last year is guilty of involuntary manslaughter for the 20 people 
who died. 
</P>
<P>
	The jurors announced they would soon return to the courtroom to  
announce the verdict. Six of the eight officers on the jury must 
vote guilty in order to convict Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission 
Viejo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The jurors deliberated for four hours on Wednesday, and about  
three hours today. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's lawyer, Frank Spinner, has urged jurors to rely on the  
expert testimony. He said his client suffered from an optical 
illusion that made him think his jet was higher than it was, that 
an altimeter on the jet malfunctioned and that the gondola at 
Cavalese, Italy, wasn't marked on American maps. 
</P>
<P>
	But prosecutor Maj. Daniel Daugherty said the only reason the  
mishap happened was because Ashby flew by his own rules. He said 
the pilot ignored speed and altitude limits, which Ashby testified 
he didn't know about. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby faces more than 200 years in prison if convicted of all  
counts. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened on the final leg of a 42-minute training  
route through the Italian Alps. Afterward, Italians demanded that 
U.S. landing rights be revoked at bases in their country. 
</P>
<P>
	While the jury deliberated, attorneys for Capt. Joseph  
Schweitzer, the navigator in Ashby's EA-6B Prowler jet, said 
closing arguments made them optimistic that charges against their 
client could be dismissed. Schweitzer faces charges similar to 
Ashby's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
