<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 12:16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts Discuss Lewinsky Interview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joseph E. Jones kept coming back to Monica's  
smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Whenever Barbara Walters pressed Ms. Lewinsky on some painful or  
embarrassing subject -- the cigar, the blue dress, Linda Tripp -- she 
``answered with a smile, as if she was making light of it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To Jones, whose Alamo, Calif., company helps lawyers evaluate  
witnesses and jurors, the message in the smile was clear: ``She 
wants people to like her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones and other experts on the subtleties of communication were  
fascinated by Ms. Lewinsky's manner in the interview that aired 
Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert R. Butterworth, a clinical psychologist in Los Angeles,  
was impressed by Ms. Lewinsky's willingness to talk about 
everything -- ``She was actually so open that it was somewhat 
frightening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said there was little evidence of the emotional, moody  
Monica and noted that she acknowledged she was on anti-depression 
medication. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the medication is masking a lot,'' he said, though  
``she did blush when she talked about phone sex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All agreed that Ms. Lewinsky was well-prepared. Ray McGraime, a  
consultant on body language, noticed that she often looked up and 
to the right when she answered a question -- a tip-off, he said, 
that the answer was rehearsed. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is being very well-schooled,'' McGraime said. He said the  
70 million Americans who watched the ABC interview saw ``a work in 
progress,'' a new Monica being remade by advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's no longer a victim of an affair. She's a victim of the  
legal system,'' he said. She is ``going to go to a more `sensual 
woman' look, which is more marketable. Now, it's Monica Inc.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gone were the demure pearls. Instead, Ms. Lewinsky pulled her  
hair back, exposing her neck -- it's ``a sexual thing,'' McGraime 
said. The same with her bright red lipstick. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraime is not convinced that Ms. Lewinsky was totally  
truthful. He said that whenever she shook her head while answering 
a question, she most likely was fibbing, whether she knew it or 
not. 
</P>
<P>
	She shook her head when she said she didn't expect a job as a  
result of her liaison with President Clinton, when she said she saw 
Clinton as a man, not as the president, and when she said she 
believed oral sex was not really sex. 
</P>
<P>
	She said that when she showed her thong to the president, it was  
``a small, subtle, flirtatious gesture.'' According to McGraime: 
``She didn't believe that, and nobody else who was watching 
believed it, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said there were moments when Ms. Lewinsky showed real  
pain, such as when she talked about the effect of the scandal on 
her family. 
</P>
<P>
	Butterworth said he got the impression that regardless of her  
denials, Ms. Lewinsky still carried a torch for Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a part of her deep inside that is still living in this  
fantasy land,'' he said. ``The door is not completely closed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 09:47:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. 3-Year-Old Helps Save Sister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEMMES, Ala. (AP) -- Three-year-old McKenzie Moorer knows her  
colors and that's how she knew something was wrong with her 
2-year-old sister. 
</P>
<P>
	While her father, Frank, snoozed Tuesday night, and her mother,  
Amanda, was washing the dishes, McKenzie and Taylor were playing in 
another room. 
</P>
<P>
	Then McKenzie arrived on the run and told her mom: ``Taylor's  
not red anymore like my crayon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her of course she's not red, she's not supposed to  
be,'' Mrs. Moorer said. ``And then she came back in with her blue 
one and said she is the color of my blue crayon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mother realized something was seriously wrong, ran to Taylor  
and found that she had stopped breathing. Using CPR she learned in 
a maternity class, Mrs. Moorer revived the child, who began gasping 
for air and crying. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor was in good spirits Wednesday at Springhill Memorial  
Hospital, and gave McKenzie a big hug when she awoke from a nap, 
Mrs. Moorer said. Doctors planned to conduct tests to determine 
what caused the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	McKenzie's teacher at Moffett Road Baptist Child Development  
Center crafted her a medal Wednesday that read ``McKenzie Moorer, 
Hero.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Much of the Northeast was pounded by heavy snow on Thursday  
while rain was scattered around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of Vermont south through New York, Pennsylvania, West  
Virginia and Maryland received near-blizzard snow. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest snow was in western New York state, including  
Buffalo and Rochester. Totals throughout the region for the 24 
hours ending at midday ranged from six to 24 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	The coastal Northeast was drenched by rain, and snow mixed with  
rain in some areas. Wind was strong and gusty across the Northeast 
and mid-Atlantic region. Gusts blew between 40 and 60 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, high pressure produced fair and dry weather in the  
Carolinas south to Florida and west into the middle and lower 
Mississippi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The southern Plains had fair skies as well, with gusty wind from  
Kansas south into Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak storm system pushed across the northern Plains and  
northern Mississippi Valley, bringing light snow to the Dakotas, 
Minnesota and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the western United States was quiet, with scattered rain  
and snow from the central Rockies west to the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	At midday, the high in the lower 48 states was 77 degrees in  
Brownsville, Texas. The low was minus 9 degrees in Ironwood, Mich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
