<DOCNO> APW19990304.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:31:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Canada, MetroNet To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., forging a deal that will help extend  
its strategy of one-stop telecommunications services into Canada, 
plans to merge its Canadian business with MetroNet Communications 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced Thursday places a value of at least $2.3  
billion on MetroNet, a local Canadian phone service supplier to 
businesses. The merged company will be able to offer business 
customers in Canada everything from long-distance to Internet to 
local phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. long-distance companies have been looking toward Canada to  
help expand their business. On Wednesday, MCI WorldCom announced an 
agreement with Bell Canada that will allow the U.S. company to 
provide its service to Canadian customers. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, the biggest U.S. long-distance provider, initially plans  
to merge its AT&AMP;T Canada operations with Metronet's business in a 
company to be called AT&AMP;T Canada Corp. The new company would have 
annual revenue of about $925 million, more than 4,000 employees and 
over $2.3 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger will be carried out in several stages as the two  
companies await regulatory approval. After the first stage, 
Metronet shareholders would indirectly own 69 percent of the merged 
company and AT&AMP;T would have the remaining 31 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second stage, AT&AMP;T is to buy all of Metronet's shares for  
at least 75 Canadian dollars per share -- $49.50 at current exchange 
rates -- or the appraised fair market value of Metronet shares at 
the time. 
</P>
<P>
	At the minimum price, that would value Metronet's 45.5 million  
shares at about $2.3 billion. The payment would be in cash, stock 
or some combination. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal has been approved by the boards of both companies, but  
it must be approved by MetroNet shareholders at a meeting expected 
to be held in May. 
</P>
<P>
	But if AT&AMP;T doesn't purchase the shares before June 30, 2000,  
the minimum price per share would be increased by 16 percent a year 
through June 30, 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's stock rose $1.12 1/2 to $84.50 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 06:04:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RJR To Sell International Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. is taking bids for  
all or part of its international tobacco business and could make a 
decision by the end of next week, one analyst who follows the 
industry says. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Feldman, tobacco analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, said  
Wednesday he thinks RJR would like to be able to include a deal 
involving the international tobacco business in the proxy material 
being prepared for shareholders in advance of the May 12 annual 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would like to show shareholders they are building value  
and have found a way of enhancing the value of their holdings,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadline for proxy materials is March 12. That is the same  
deadline investor Carl Icahn faces for launching a proxy fight for 
control of the company. He has threatened to launch such a fight if 
the company fails to spin off its Nabisco food unit. 
</P>
<P>
	But other analysts said they don't expect a decision on the  
international tobacco business that quickly, saying they suspect 
RJR will need more time to strike the best deal. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR declined comment. Its shares fell 18 3/4 cents a share to  
$27.68 3/4 in trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Its chairman and chief executive, Steven Goldstone, recently  
told analysts that finding a way to give the struggling 
international tobacco business greater stature was a top priority 
for the first half of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But he hasn't specified whether he favors a sale of the business  
or creation of a joint venture as a way to make it more 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	The international tobacco division at RJR has seen profits  
shrink in each of the past two years as economic conditions 
deteriorated in key markets in Asia and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Feldman said the international tobacco business may fetch as  
much as $6 billion if it were sold outright. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the most likely buyers would be Philip Morris Cos.,  
RJR's chief rival in the United States, and Japan Tobacco and said 
France's Seita and Spain's Tabacalera may also make a bid. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MLB Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Randy Johnson's first two innings on the  
mound for the Arizona Diamondbacks were routine by his standards. 
</P>
<P>
	For the young University of Arizona batters who faced him, they  
were 31 pitches that are impossible to forget. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was almost like the Eiffel Tower because I'm only  
5-foot-7,'' said 19-year-old Keoni DeRenne, one of two batters who 
hit a ball into fair territory against the Big Unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's immense. It was just awesome. Hopefully, they got it on  
videotape because I'd like to show it to my kids someday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With his trademark glare, at 6-foot-10 towering on the mouned,  
Johnson methodically struck out four of the six batters he faced 
Wednesday. The other two grounded out to shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Torres struck out on three pitches, and was thrilled.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just to have the opportunity to face Randy Johnson, it's like  
a dream come true, it's like a childhood dream,'' he said. ``Yeah, 
three pitches, but those three pitches meant a lot to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was more or less satisfied with his effort. Of his 31  
pitches, five were call strikes, seven were swinging strikes, six 
were fouls, 11 were balls and two were hit in play. 
</P>
<P>
	He threw a couple of breaking balls and change-ups, but mostly  
four-seam and two-seam fastballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little disappointed the breaking ball wasn't there, but  
I'm always that way in spring training,'' Johnson said. ``I just 
went out there to work on my mechanics and my arm strength.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who signed a four-year, $52.4 million contract with the  
Diamondbacks, strolled to the mound at Tucson Electric Park under 
bright sunshine in 80-degree weather. In the distance beyond left 
field, the Catalina Mountains provided a scenic backdrop to what 
amounted to a historic moment for the second-year franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks purple was the fourth major-league uniform  
Johnson has worn. He started his career with Montreal and spent 9 1/2 
seasons with the Seattle Mariners. For a half-season last year, he 
on the Houston Astros. Now he's the marquee addition to a 
high-priced rotation that could vault Arizona into National League 
contention. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was exciting,'' Johnson said, ``not nearly exciting as the  
first start I make in L.A. (the April 5 season opener against Kevin 
Brown in Dodger Stadium) or probably even more so when I make my 
first start at Bank One. But it's going to be an exciting four 
years for this organization and for myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson didn't want to hit anybody.  
</P>
<P>
	``I get worried if it's a guy up there making millions of  
dollars, let alone a young kid trying to get a college education,'' 
he said. ``He might be president of the United States someday. You 
never know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks eventually won the game 10-2. It was, Johnson  
joked, a little revenge for other games he'd pitched against the 
Wildcats long ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Johnson faced the University of Arizona, he walked  
six and was shelled for six runs on 13 hits in a 7-3 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	That was 1985. He was no Big Unit then, just an extremely tall,  
extremely wild junior at Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting back at U of A after all those beatings I used to  
take at USC,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in baseball on Wednesday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Cleveland Indians outfielder Mark Whiten will miss at least  
two weeks of spring training with a stress fracture of his right 
foot. 
</P>
<P>
	Whiten, expected to open the season as a reserve, complained  
about pain in the foot and underwent tests Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Relief pitcher Jeff Shaw couldn't wait any longer for the  
birth of his third child and arrived at the Los Angeles Dodgers' 
camp at Vero Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw was given permission to report after wife Julie delivered,  
which was supposed to be Feb. 15, then Feb. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``Julie's still healthy, the baby's not in danger, that's the  
most important thing. . . . This one's being stubborn,'' Shaw said. 
The Shaws have been told they are going to have a son. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ron Wright's back appears to be all right. Wright, who missed  
most of last season with a back injury, hit two home runs in a 
Pittsburgh Pirates intrasquad game at Bradenton, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Pirates are still waiting for outfielder Jose  
Guillen, stuck in the Dominican Republic while awaiting an entry 
visa into the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The stars at the St. Louis Cardinals' Jupiter, Fla., camp  
weren't players. ``The real heroes were the groundskeepers,'' 
manager Tony La Russa said. ``They told us a storm was coming 
between 12:30 and 1 p.m., so we moved everything up an hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although rain cut short two intrasquad games, there was enough  
time for a 9-8 contest on a field where the wind was blowing out. 
The game on the field where it was blowing in was 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	-- At Port St. Lucie, Fla., the New York Mets assigned former  
catcher John Stearns as an advance scout during the regular season. 
Stearns will report on the tendencies of both pitchers and hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The Toronto Blue Jays signed six players, including pitcher  
Chris Carpenter and outfielder Shannon Stewart, who agreed to 
three-year deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-baseman Tom Evans, utility player Felipe Crespo and  
right-hander Nerio Rodriguez all signed one-year deals, and 
reliever Robert Person's contract was renewed. That means the Jays' 
entire 40-man roster is signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Carpenter's and Stewart's deals are believed to be worth  
more than $3 million. It's the first time the Blue Jays have signed 
long-term deals with players with fewer than two years of 
major-league service. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Carpenter and Stewart said they appreciated the Blue Jays`  
precedent-setting move. 
</P>
<P>
	``It`s good for me,'' said Stewart, 25, who batted .279 and  
stole 51 bases in 144 games last season. ``It gives me security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carpenter, 23, was 12-7 and had a 4.37 earned-run average in 33  
games last season, 24 of them starts. He was scheduled to start 
against Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez and the New York Yankees in 
Toronto's first exhibition game today. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:26:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing Champ at Odds Eith the Odds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Laurent Boudouani, the WBA super  
welterweight champion from France, isn't pleased being a 4-1 
underdog to David Reid, the only boxing gold medalist for the 
United States at the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not happy about that,'' Boudouani said. ``Saturday night,  
I will show them they are wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight in a 3,300-seat ballroom at the Boardwalk Convention  
Center will be the 33-year-old Frenchman's fifth defense of the 
154-pound title he won in 1996. His record is 38-2-1, with 32 
knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, on the other hand, will be fighting as a pro for only the  
11th time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've been pushed into this fight because of my  
talent,'' the 25-year-old Reid said of the influence of trainer Al 
Mitchell and promoter America Presents. ``They believe in my 
talent, and they know how far to push me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like to make predictions because anything can happen,  
but I will predict this -- I will win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, who says he doesn't pay any attention to odds,  
nevertheless agreed with Boudouani that they are out of line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got it 50-50,'' Mitchell, head coach for the 1996 Olympic  
team, said Thursday. ``You can throw the odds out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a fight between a young athlete, a good athlete, and  
veteran not past his prime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the HBO telecast set to start at 10:15 p.m. EST will be  
a 10-round heavyweight bout between veteran Lou Savarese and 
unbeaten, but untested Lance Whitaker. It is scheduled to start at 
10:25 p.m., with the title fight to begin 15 minutes after it ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is very fast and has a good right hand,'' Boudouani said of  
Reid. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell said he can see the fight going either way.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he can't handle David's speed, he's in trouble,'' Mitchell  
said Boudouani. ``If he can, David's in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The champion also must be wary of Reid's power, especially the  
right. Both of Boudouani's losses, one in 1991 and the other in 
1993, were by knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	Boudouani, of course, is much more experienced than Reid.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great champion,'' Reid said. ``I've seen a lot of tapes  
of his fights. He can fight, he can move real well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenger from Philadelphia boxed in world-class amateur  
competition, and has not been babied as a pro. He has been in with 
some good journeymen and two former but faded world champions -- 
Jorge Vaca and Simon Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Reid's seven wins within the distance was a single  
right-hand knockout of Vaca in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last fight, Reid demonstrated poise and heart. He was cut  
over the right eye and knocked down twice in the late rounds while 
winning a 12-round decision over previously unbeaten James 
``Cowboy'' Coker last Oct. 24 at Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid said one of the knockdowns was more of a slip, but admitted  
a punch had landed. His winning margins were four, six and eight 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old Savarese, who stopped former heavyweight  
champion James ``Buster'' Douglas in the first round in last his 
fight, on June 25, 1998, has a 38-2 record, with 32 knockouts. Both 
losses came in 1997, when he dropped a 12-round decision to George 
Foreman and was knocked out in the fifth round by David Izon. 
</P>
<P>
	Savarese, of New York, stands 6-foot-4, but he is four inches  
shorter than Whitaker, whose nom de guerre is Mount Whitaker. 
Savarese figures to offer the toughest test so far for the 
27-year-old Whitaker, from Van Nuys, Calif., who is 18-0 with 16 
knockouts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990304.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 10:10:45 </DATE_TIME>
