<HEADLINE> Pitt To Hire Howland As Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The University of Pittsburgh will hire Ben  
Howland of Northern Arizona as its new basketball coach, two 
sources told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Two sources close to the situation, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said today that Pitt athletic director Steve Pederson 
and Howland reached agreement Wednesday night to replace Ralph 
Willard, who resigned earlier this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Arizona (20-7) plays Friday in the Big Sky Conference  
semifinals in Ogden, Utah. Howland was expected to be introduced as 
Pitt's new coach on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Howland will get a five-year contract worth $375,000 to $400,000  
a year, according to the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette and the Arizona 
Republic. Howland makes $110,000 to $125,000 at Northern Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Andrews, a Pitt spokeswoman, said there would be no  
announcement on a new coach today. 
</P>
<P>
	Willard, who had a 63-77 record in his five seasons at Pitt,  
including 14-16 this season, coached the Panthers for the last time 
Wednesday night in a 64-51 opening-round loss to Rutgers in the Big 
East 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Arizona athleic director Steve Holton said Wednesday  
night he had nothing to announce, but that the Lumberjacks were in 
the preliminary stages of a coaching search. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republic said Holton acknowledged that Jamie Dixon, an  
assistant at Hawaii and former assistant at Northern Arizona, has 
inquired about the job. ``He is definitely somebody we're 
considering,'' Holton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
