<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interior Department Marks 150 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At the Interior Department's block-long  
granite headquarters, the story of America is emblazoned on 
floor-to-ceiling murals. 
</P>
<P>
	The art works, painted in the 1930s, show homesteaders racing  
westward vowing Oklahoma or bust; wildcatters working the oil 
fields of Texas; a landscape of barren Southwest desert turned to 
lush green thanks to a government dam and irrigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Having been at the center of history, the department today marks  
its 150th birthday, and President Clinton is among those who will 
celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth cabinet agency, created in 1849, no federal agency  
played a greater role in the sculpture of America. It directed how 
the West was to be developed, opened vast areas to timber, 
ranching, mining and the railroads and in the 1880s controlled the 
destiny of more than 1 billion acres -- at the time nearly half the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's reach is still substantial as steward of 440  
million acres of land, including 378 units of the national park 
system, 514 refuges, wilderness areas, millions of acres of 
rangeland and such American crown jewels as Yellowstone National 
Park and the Grand Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in taking part in the anniversary celebration, will be  
the first president since Jimmy Carter to visit the Interior 
headquarters a few blocks from the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	He will use the occasion to press for congressional approval of  
his $1 billion ``land legacy'' initiative unveiled last month and 
urge that a permanent fund be established to ensure at least that 
much money is spent each year to preserve treasured lands and green 
spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	It was land and concern about its management that prompted  
creation of the Interior Department, which now has nearly 70,000 
employees, in 1849. At the time, the United States had completed a 
rush of expansion. Texas had been annexed a few years earlier, 
California was added after the war with Mexico and new lands were 
added in the Northwest after a boundary dispute was settled with 
Britain. In three years the country grew by nearly a million square 
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	A new department was needed to, among other things, direct the  
settlement and exploitation of the West. Over the years the 
department would reflect the dual demands of overseeing the 
development of America's vast natural resources and, beginning with 
President Theodore Roosevelt, protect and preserve those resources. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a real sense, the history of the Interior Department  
mirrors the history of American expansion and western settlement,'' 
says Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who is the 47th person to 
head the department. ``It also dramatizes America's evolving 
relationship with the land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Interior in the 1800s directed -- at times with harrowing  
consequences -- how the U.S. government was going to deal with the 
Indians. And it parceled out land -- millions of acres -- to the 
railroads, to ranchers and to homesteaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the turn of the century, the department began a  
push over three decades to turn millions of arid acres into lush 
farmland by damming the West's most powerful rivers and building 
massive irrigation systems. The dams brought water, flood control, 
electric power and new recreational areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a department whose primary concern was helping ranchers,  
timber and mining interests exploit American resources, the agency 
now often finds itself challenging these interests to protect those 
same resources -- the grasslands, threatened species, scenic parks 
and wilderness and open spaces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
