<HEADLINE> Pepsi To Debut New Ads at Oscars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With help from singer Aretha Franklin and actor  
Marlon Brando, Pepsi-Cola Co. plans to launch an ad campaign called 
``Joy of Cola'' for its flagship brand later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The beverage company from Purchase, N.Y., disclosed Thursday the  
first three commercials in the new campaign will debut March 21 on 
the Academy Awards show on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Aretha Franklin has recorded a new anthem for the soft drink  
maker that will be heard in the ads and will make a cameo 
appearance in one of the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Marlon Brando and entertainer Issac Hayes will narrate the  
other ads although neither man will be shown in the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Child actor Hallie Eisenberg, who has previously appeared for  
Pepsi in an ad in which she adopts an unusually gruff voice when 
she finds Pepsi isn't served at a diner, will appear in all three 
ads. 
</P>
<P>
	In one ad, the little girl appears to sing the new anthem but it  
is Aretha Franklin's voice. Brando's voice is channeled through the 
girl in another ad in which she has been denied a Pepsi, while 
Hayes' voice comes through her when she poses as a disc jockey in 
the third ad. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi officials said the new campaign leverages the company's  
``key equities of humor, humanity and music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new theme replaces ``Generation Next'' which had been  
faulted by Phil Marineau, president of Pepsi-Cola North America, 
for appearing to appeal to only a narrow segment of the audience 
that Pepsi should court. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi-Cola's corporate share of the $56.3 billion U.S. soft  
drink market rose 0.5 percentage point to 31.4 percent last year, 
according to the Beverage Digest/Maxwell report. Coca-Cola Co.'s 
leading share rose 0.6 percentage point to 44.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pepsi-Cola brand's share fell 0.3 percentage points to 14.2  
percent, while industry leader Coca-Cola Classic was flat at 20.8 
percent of the market, the report said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
